[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ There is this joke that when you want to eat a meal that is cheap, tasty, and done fast, you must go to three different restaurants.  I have always felt the same when searching for opening weapons suitable for faster time controls. How can I find something that is relatively sound, can be learned fast and, most importantly, will surprise my opponent in the vast majority of cases.  Finally, after years of trying, I completed this task, and you are presented with the fruits of my labour @@StartBracket@@and in one course instead of three separate ones!@@EndBracket@@.  The Damiano Petroff that arises after  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nxe5  Nxe4!?  is a variation that fits in the categories described above perfectly.  • It is light on theory.  • Your opponent's theory will usually end after  3...Nxe4!?  or after  4.Qe2   • It is quite sound. The worst you can get is around 0.60-0.65, and it won't be the type of position where we are a pawn down, under attack or with some permanent weakness. It will be a symmetrical position where White has some initiative.  • The only variation that leads to White's advantage is played so rarely, that you should expect to see it in like 2-3% of your 1.e4 e5 games @@StartBracket@@higher on higher levels but not much more than 10%, lower on lower levels, sometimes as low as 1%@@EndBracket@@. Even if White gets to the critical position, I will guide you to make sure you still pose a ton of practical problems.  • When you check the Lichess database, even though it is considered that Black's opening is 'bad, ' after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nxe5  Nxe4!?  4.Qe2  Qe7  , Black scores higher than White does!  What I absolutely love is the fact that  3...Nxe4  has been considered @@StartBracket@@and still is considered@@EndBracket@@ to be refuted and unplayable. One of the first traps I have learned goes @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nxe5  Nxe4!?  4.Qe2  when  4...Nf6??  5.Nc6+  loses on the spot. Trust me on my word - this trap is the maximum that your opponent will know in the vast majority of cases, no matter the level.  Also, to quote WikiBooks: 'This position almost only occurs among beginners because this trap is so well known and black's position is terrible.' Well, I hope to change this assessment!  I also want to point out that this course is not only about the Petroff. It is a full 1.e4 e5 repertoire for Black. I have spent extra time to make sure that the variations that I suggest will print easy points for you. All of my suggested lines are sound, but I went for unexplored and tricky whenever possible.  One of the key resources for me was the Lichess database. It perfectly shows how people react both on lower levels and in games with faster time controls. I banked my approach on these numbers a lot, and I am delighted with the product I am offering. I am using these lines myself from now, and I am not afraid to test them against anyone.  Finally, this repertoire is designed to serve you in games with faster time controls, but there is no 'DON'T USE IN CLASSICAL CHESS' sign. It is certainly playable, and there are titled players who use the Damiano Petroff as their main weapon.  Good luck with the Damiano!  Kamil Plichta, Kołobrzeg 2022. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Why did I create this course?"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Since repertoires designed for faster time controls are somewhat rare, you might ask why it was exactly some FM from Poland who decided to create a course like this. The thing is that I always loved finding sneaky opening ideas designed for blitz. It started all the way back in 2006 when I created my first opening files  (devoted to the Traxler Counterattack)  and in 2007 the g4 lines against the Dutch. Since then, I am fully in love with the work on openings. A few points of my 'career' which convinced me that faster time control games are something I love the most and I excel in:  • Between 2012 and 2016, my blitz rating was around 100-200 ELO points higher than a classical one, while in general, it is exactly the opposite for people.  • In 2016, I became a Polish Academic Team Champion  (rapid)  .  • In 2018 I took 2nd place in Polish Blitz Championship.  • In 2019 I took 3rd place in Polish Rapid Championship.  • So far, I have three classical wins against GMs, while I counted I have won over 100 blitz or rapid over the board games against them so far.  • My online scalps in blitz include Nakamura, Artemiev, Mamedyarov, Duda and Rapport.  • Finally, I want to share the fun fact that only once in my whole career was my classical ELO rating the highest of the three ratings  (January 2018 list)  .  The above successes wouldn't be possible without a specific opening repertoire. This is what this course is about. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff: 7.Qxe5 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! } 1... e5
{ This is the very first course where I analyze something symmetrical. My general approach is to avoid symmetry and look for imbalances right from the start. However, I was shocked to discover how interesting the line I am going to recommend can get! }
2. Nf3
{ We will start by analyzing the mainline first, and leave the sidelines for the end. }
2... Nf6
{ Don't worry! I'm not suggesting entering the 'proper' Petroff. We will play something a bit more obscure :@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nxe5
{ By far the most common move, entering the big mainline of the Petroff. } 3...
Nxe4
{ In the first chess book that I ever touched, 'Chess Openings' by Theodor Schuster, one of the first openings that have been checked is the so-called Damiano Petroff, starting with the text move  3...Nxe4  . I remember the trap that arises after  4.Qe2  Nf6  5.Nc6+  is the first that I have ever learned, and for almost 20 years, I thought that this opening was simply refuted. Well, it is not! I am far from claiming that this line equalizes because it doesn't. However, I can make a few promises @@StartBracket@@I always keep them!@@EndBracket@@:    • There is only one sequence that leads to an edge for White. White has to play five precise moves to get an edge.   • The vast majority @@StartBracket@@95%+@@EndBracket@@ of players will have no clue what is going on. The Damiano Petroff is so neglected by theory @@StartBracket@@and practice@@EndBracket@@ that the chance of surprising your opponent in blitz or rapid is close to 100%.   • Even though the line is absolutely symmetrical, there will be a lot of dynamism going on in the next few moves in most cases.   • Last, it is MUCH more fun to play than it looks! Before I show you what the point behind 3... Nxe4 is, I want to mention that to this day, I played 66 training blitz games with this line, scoring 62% with Black. However, when I was playing this line, I barely knew any theory and I improvised a lot.   OK, let's see what this is all about! By taking on e4, we try to equalize by force by liquidating the centre. Usually, such an approach is preceded by the move 3... d6, making sure that White will retreat the Knight first, and only then do we take on e4. The 3... Nxe4 line is more dynamic. It is objectively worse than 3... d6, but it poses some immediate challenges. By keeping the pawn on d7, we will often play ... d5 in one go, leaving White with one move only to push for an edge.   OK, to be more specific, White can push in a few ways, but only one idea guarantees an edge. }
4. Qe2
{ Usually, White's theory will end here. Sometimes I like to use some bad jokes, but here, I am 100% serious. By playing 4. Qe2, White not only attacks our Knight, but also prepares discovered checks with the e5-Knight. This leaves us with no choice, meaning that the symmetry has to be sustained. Note that the alternatives to 4. Qe2 will be analyzed in chapter 6. }
4... Qe7
{ Now, if White doesn't take on  e4  , Black will fully equalize.  5.d3  Nf6  5.d4  d5  both leave us with no issues at all. In general, if White doesn't take on e4, we want to play ...d5 next and then challenge the e5-Knight. Castling queenside is usually a good idea. }
5. Qxe4
{ There is no point in checking anything else. Out of 1219 games, White chose this option in 1178 of them. }
5... d6 { Now, White faces a threat of ... Qxe5 which must be stopped. } 6. d4
{ White's choice in around 90% of games. Sometimes White decides on  6.f4  @@StartBracket@@chapter 5@@EndBracket@@,  and sometimes White simply allows ... Qxe5, which gives us an excellent game with no effort.  6.Nc3  Qxe5  7.d3  Bf5  is one example. }
6... dxe5
{ Now, we are at a crossroads. Out of around 1000 games, White chose to take on e5 with the Queen in 1/3 of them, and with the pawn in 2/3. Since I consider taking with the Queen less accurate, we will start with it. I also truly believe that the following variations will demonstrate the hidden power of our position. }
7. Qxe5 Qxe5+
{ We bank our play on the lead in development. Please don't try something like  7...Be6?  due to  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.Bb5  and we are significantly worse. By taking on e5:  • We get rid of the Queen that was blocking the Bishop and would slow our development down.  • White will be left with the pawn on e5, which will be a target.  • Finally, we will be left with a lead in development, and we exactly know where our pieces are going. The Knight will go to c6 and the Bishop usually to f5. The only lines where the Bishop is developed to d7 are those where White plays Bb5. Then we will follow with queenside castling. You should also look for opportunities to use the c6-Knight to jump to b4. }
8. dxe5 Nc6
{ 8...Bf5  is also possible and is in fact the most popular move for Black, but I think that moving the Knight first has no drawbacks at all. It also fits the general rule of developing the Knights first. After  8...Nc6  , White has three ways of defending the pawn. In the Quickstarter, we will check two of them. }
9. f4
{ Two inaccuracies in a row, and White is already worse! It is impossible to get a good position by neglecting development so much. }
9... Bf5
{ Another tempo move! We combine threats to the c2-pawn with queenside castling, when our lead in development will start to tell. }
10. Bd3 { This move is only a temporary solution. } 10... Bxd3 11. cxd3 Nb4
{ White can't cover both d3 and c2.  12.Kd2  O-O-O  doesn't really help. } *

