4... Qe7
{ Now, if White doesn't take on  e4  , Black will fully equalize.  5.d3  Nf6  5.d4  d5  both leave us with no issues at all. In general, if White doesn't take on e4, we want to play ...d5 next and then challenge the e5-Knight. Castling queenside is usually a good idea. }
5. Qxe4
{ There is no point in checking anything else. Out of 1219 games, White chose this option in 1178 of them. }
5... d6 { Now, White faces a threat of ... Qxe5 which must be stopped. } 6. d4
{ White's choice in around 90% of games. Sometimes White decides on  6.f4  @@StartBracket@@chapter 5@@EndBracket@@,  and sometimes White simply allows ... Qxe5, which gives us an excellent game with no effort.  6.Nc3  Qxe5  7.d3  Bf5  is one example. }
6... dxe5
{ Now, we are at a crossroads. Out of around 1000 games, White chose to take on e5 with the Queen in 1/3 of them, and with the pawn in 2/3. Since I consider taking with the Queen less accurate, we will start with it. I also truly believe that the following variations will demonstrate the hidden power of our position. }
7. Qxe5 Qxe5+
{ We bank our play on the lead in development. Please don't try something like  7...Be6?  due to  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.Bb5  and we are significantly worse. By taking on e5:  • We get rid of the Queen that was blocking the Bishop and would slow our development down.  • White will be left with the pawn on e5, which will be a target.  • Finally, we will be left with a lead in development, and we exactly know where our pieces are going. The Knight will go to c6 and the Bishop usually to f5. The only lines where the Bishop is developed to d7 are those where White plays Bb5. Then we will follow with queenside castling. You should also look for opportunities to use the c6-Knight to jump to b4. }
8. dxe5 Nc6
{ 8...Bf5  is also possible and is in fact the most popular move for Black, but I think that moving the Knight first has no drawbacks at all. It also fits the general rule of developing the Knights first. After  8...Nc6  , White has three ways of defending the pawn. In the Quickstarter, we will check two of them. }
9. Bb5
{ The most natural option for White is to pin our Knight and hope to save the e5-pawn. }
9... Bd7
{ This is our usual reaction to Bb5 in this line. You will also notice that we will use the same strategy in similar positions throughout the whole course. }
10. O-O O-O-O
{ Also possible is  10...Nxe5  11.Bxd7+  Kxd7  12.Rd1+  Kc6  when we fully equalize. The text move is more ambitious. }
11. Bf4 { 11.Bxc6  Bxc6  transposes to the 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. O-O variation. }
11... Nxe5
{ I love this small tactic! By attacking the b5-Bishop, we ensure that we won't be playing a pawn down. After  12.Bxd7+  Nxd7  , we can even go for ... g6 followed by ... Bg7 when we have more active pieces in this symmetrical pawn structure. We are at least equal. }
