[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff: 7.dxe5 8.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ By far the most common move, entering the big mainline of the Petroff. } 3...
Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5
{ Now we will check what is considered to be the mainline for White. By taking with the pawn, White keeps the Queens on the board and leaves us with a bit misplaced Queen on e7. Let's also not forget that our opponent is a pawn up! However, there are positives too! The position of our Queen might not be bad at all. The pawn on e5 is under attack and we are one step closer from castling queenside. }
7... Nc6
{ As you can see, our position is extremely logical and intuitive to play. White faces the threat of ... Qxe5, and to get any advantage at all, he has to give the extra pawn back with  8.Nc3  . }
8. Bf4
{ We will start our coverage with my favourite move to meet. Since I consider this repertoire to be a perfect weapon for blitz and rapid, I will refer to the Lichess database because there is quite a big sample size of games there. 8. Bf4 has been White's choice in 2280 games out of 13 898. This gives us around a 1/6 chance that our rival will play this move. What is absolutely amazing is that the chance that he will blunder on the next move @@StartBracket@@in faster time controls@@EndBracket@@ is almost 90%! }
8... g5
{ We attack the Bishop and plan to win the pawn back in the not-so-distant future. }
9. Bg3 { White's choice in 1313 games out of 1509 in Lichess database. } 9...
f5
{ The point! White probably thought that he would use the tricky 'en passant' rule against us, but since the Queen is pinned along the e-file, it won't be an option! Therefore, we will play ... f4 next and win the Bishop.  Do you know what is amazing? If you reach the position after 7. dxe5, in around 10% of games you will win with this trick! The victims of this trap in my training games are an IM and a GM, so no matter the level, people will fall into it constantly! }
10. Qe2 f4 11. Qh5+
{ This is how White usually tries to get some compensation. Note that after  11.Nc3  , we should go for  11...Qxe5!  first, to force the exchange of Queens. The hanging Bishop won't run away. }
11... Qf7 { The simplest. } 12. Qxg5 fxg3 13. hxg3 Qf5
{ We will either exchange Queens or take on e5 or c2 next. White's extra pawns are basically meaningless in such an open position. Game over! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff: 7.dxe5 8.Bb5 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ By far the most common move, entering the big mainline of the Petroff. } 3...
Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Bb5
{ There are a few things I love about this move:   • It is White's most popular move according to all databases but the correspondence one.   • Many sources claim that it gives White a @@StartBracket@@huge@@EndBracket@@ advantage due to one forcing line that we will analyze later.  • In fact, it gives White no advantage at all, and Black's play is straightforward and easy to understand. }
8... Bd7
{ First things first, as usual, we meet Bb5 with ... Bd7. What is lovely is that we will play a combination of ... O-O-O, ... a6 and ... Nxe5 next and White can do nothing about that. OK, White has a few ways to try to disrupt our play but if you learn a few patterns, you are good to go! }
9. O-O
{ This is a very modest idea, castling into safety and preparing to keep the e5-pawn. }
9... O-O-O { ... Nxe5 is a threat that is very difficult to parry. } 10. Nc3
{ Giving the pawn back is the most common way of playing for White. He hopes that it will be possible to create something on the queenside @@StartBracket@@it won't@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Nxe5
{ Simple. We are ready to continue with ... Ng6/Nc6 if nothing concrete is going on. There is also ... Bxb5 and only then ... Nc6. Engines already give us full equality. }
11. Bxd7+ Rxd7
{ Black usually captures with the Knight, but it is more logical to take with the Rook. The Knight will be relocated to g6 or c6, and the Rook makes room for the other one on d8. }
12. Be3 Nc6
{ We want to exchange Queens next with full equality. After  13.Qf3  , there are many good ways to play, but I like  13...g6!? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff: 7.dxe5 8.Bb5 #2/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ By far the most common move, entering the big mainline of the Petroff. } 3...
Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Bb5
{ There are a few things I love about this move:   • It is White's most popular move according to all databases but the correspondence one.   • Many sources claim that it gives White a @@StartBracket@@huge@@EndBracket@@ advantage due to one forcing line that we will analyze later.  • In fact, it gives White no advantage at all, and Black's play is straightforward and easy to understand. }
8... Bd7
{ First things first, as usual, we meet Bb5 with ... Bd7. What is lovely is that we will play a combination of ... O-O-O, ... a6 and ... Nxe5 next and White can do nothing about that. OK, White has a few ways to try to disrupt our play but if you learn a few patterns, you are good to go! }
9. Nc3
{ This is the start of the line that was considered a refutation of our concept. Fortunately, the current state of theory claims that it doesn't guarantee White anything. }
9... O-O-O 10. Bf4
{ This is the tabiya of the 8.Bb5 variation. White is ready to dodge two of our main concepts:  •  10...Nxe5??  doesn't work because the b5-Bishop is defended.  •  10...a6?  is wrong due to  11.Be2  and we have zero compensation.  • I'd also add that  10...g5  11.Bg3  leads nowhere because white can meet  11...f5??  with  12.exf6  . }
10... Qb4
{ Another try is  10...g5  but here, having the Queen defended, White can even try  11.Bg3  with an edge.   By playing  10...Qb4  , we hit the b2-pawn and prepare to exchange Queens. }
11. O-O-O { The widely considered 'refutation'. } 11... Qxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe5
{ Again we see this trick. It usually works whenever White has an undefended Bishop. }
13. Bxd7+ Nxd7 14. Ng5
{ I can't recall the concrete source, but I remember seeing an opening book that ended the analysis here by claiming that White is simply much better because f7 can't be defended. One thing we have to agree with - f7 can't be defended. However, what about the unprotected Bishop on f4?! Maybe we can exploit its position in some way?! }
14... Be7
{ The point of the whole line. If not for this variation, the whole concept of starting with 3... Nxe4 would be much less appealing. }
15. Nxf7 Rdf8
{ What is amazing is that it is White who has to find the correct sequence to maintain full equality! }
16. Nxh8 Rxf4
{ We threaten to play ... Rf8 when our minor pieces will eventually outweigh White's Rook and pawn. Therefore, White has to find a way to snatch the 2nd pawn. }
17. Rhe1 Kd8 18. Re6 { Otherwise, White would part with the Knight for free. }
18... Rf8 19. Ng6 hxg6 20. Rxg6 Rf7
{ ... Bf6 is also fine, but I prefer to defend the pawn with the Rook and play ... Bd6 next. It is tough to evaluate this position, especially when the engines give 0.00 everywhere, but we have to be doing fine. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff: 7.dxe5 8.Nc3 #1/3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ By far the most common move, entering the big mainline of the Petroff. } 3...
Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Nc3
{ Giving the pawn back is the only way for White to get an advantage. As a result, we will get a very symmetrical position with an extra tempo for White. Let's start with some statistics:   • In the Mega Database, White chose 8. Nc3 191 times out of 612 games which is an equivalent of around 30%.   • The number increases if we take a look at the 2000+ database. 8. Nc3 has been White's choice in 57 games out of 137, which increases the percentage to around 40%.   • However, what should interest us the most is the Lichess database, with big sample sizes and with information on how people usually react in blitz! After a quick look, we get a realistic number of 2330 games out of 13 917, which equals around 17%.   Long story short, the chance that someone will play 8. Nc3 against you when he is unprepared equals 1/6 after you reach the tabiya on move seven. If you wonder how things are looking on my level @@StartBracket@@around 2650-2700 blitz, 2700-2800 bullet@@EndBracket@@, I faced 8. Nc3 in 12 games out of 27 that went 7... Nc6. OK, let's leave the probability alone. In the previous lines, I demonstrated that Black has nothing to be afraid of when White tries to hold on to the pawn. That means that the pawn has to be sacrificed. Since playing a pawn down with the Queen on e7 isn't really my deepest dream, let's restore the material equilibrium! }
8... Qxe5 { Now, to get an advantage, White has to take on e5. } 9. Qxe5+
{ The only route for an edge. } 9... Nxe5
{ It is this position that offers White an edge. There are two ways to get it - Bf4 or Nb5. After anything else, we can develop the light-squared Bishop and castle queenside. Note that something like  10.Nd5?  is a shot in the dark due to  10...Bd6  and the Knight is misplaced on d5. }
10. Nb5
{ A less popular brother of 10. Bf4. The positions here will be much more symmetrical and the pawn structure will usually be untouched. White banks his play on the c7-weakness, and we need to be precise to get a playable position. }
10... Bb4+
{ With a simple idea of playing ... Ba5 next. White has two ways of dealing with this check. }
11. Bd2 { This is the correct approach.  11.c3  Ba5  is fine for Black. } 11...
Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Kd8
{ OK, both Kings are a bit loose, but it is White who has the initiative. If given a move, we would play ... Re8 or ... Bd7 and gradually untangle. White's only advantage in this position is time. If our rival plays too slowly, we will equalize. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. }
*

