[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff: 7.dxe5 8.Nc3 #2/3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ By far the most common move, entering the big mainline of the Petroff. } 3...
Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Nc3
{ Giving the pawn back is the only way for White to get an advantage. As a result, we will get a very symmetrical position with an extra tempo for White. Let's start with some statistics:   • In the Mega Database, White chose 8. Nc3 191 times out of 612 games which is an equivalent of around 30%.   • The number increases if we take a look at the 2000+ database. 8. Nc3 has been White's choice in 57 games out of 137, which increases the percentage to around 40%.   • However, what should interest us the most is the Lichess database, with big sample sizes and with information on how people usually react in blitz! After a quick look, we get a realistic number of 2330 games out of 13 917, which equals around 17%.   Long story short, the chance that someone will play 8. Nc3 against you when he is unprepared equals 1/6. If you wonder how things are looking on my level @@StartBracket@@around 2650-2700 blitz, 2700-2800 bullet@@EndBracket@@, I faced 8. Nc3 in 12 games out of 27. OK, let's leave the probability alone. In the previous chapters, I demonstrated that Black has nothing to be afraid of when White tries to hold on to the pawn. That means that the pawn has to be sacrificed. Since playing a pawn down with the Queen on e7 isn't really my deepest dream, let's restore the material equilibrium! }
8... Qxe5 { Now, to get an advantage, White has to take on e5. } 9. Qxe5+
{ The only route for an edge. } 9... Nxe5
{ It is this position that offers White an edge. There are two ways to get it - Bf4 or Nb5. After anything else, we can develop the light-squared Bishop and castle queenside. Note that something like  10.Nd5?  is a shot in the dark due to  10...Bd6  and the Knight is misplaced on d5. }
10. Bf4
{ The most popular choice. White hits the Knight and eyes the c7-pawn. Castling queenside is also on the menu. Placing the Bishop on f4 is also the most natural move because White develops another piece and speeds up the development, unlike in the  10.Nb5  variation. }
10... Bd6
{ We should maintain the Knight on e5. We also threaten ... Nf3+/Nd3+ which leaves White with no choice - the Bishop has to be moved to g3. }
11. Nb5
{ Played 114 times out of 762 games @@StartBracket@@Lichess@@EndBracket@@. This looks smart but it is, in fact, quite poor. What we need here are two accurate moves. }
11... Nf3+
{ But not  11...Nd3+?  12.Bxd3  Bxf4  13.g3  and we need to give up a pawn with  13...a6  to survive. }
12. Ke2 { 12.gxf3?  Bxf4  leaves White in a horrible position. } 12... Nd4+
{ This is the 2nd accurate move.  12...Bxf4?  13.Kxf3  once again forces us to do some dance to save c7. }
13. Nxd4 Bxf4
{ The Bishop pair leaves us with an edge. Just remember that after  14.Kf3  you should put the Bishop on g5, e5 or even d2, but not on d6 when it will run into Nb5. }
*

