[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff: 6.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5
{ By far the most common move, entering the big mainline of the Petroff. } 3...
Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. f4
{ This way of defending the Knight is much less logical, but it has some venom. The d-pawn will stay in the starting blocks and White might get a dangerous pawn majority if we don't play actively. I consider this line to be a pure pleasure to play with Black, even though White might hope to get a theoretical advantage out of the opening. }
6... dxe5 7. fxe5
{ Taking with the Queen is wrong as usual. This time  7.Qxe5  Be6!  is excellent for Black. }
7... f5
{ 7...f6  will eventually win the pawn back, but even if we do that, we will be left with an isolated pawn on e5. My suggested move is more dynamic. }
8. Qe3 { From here, the Queen won't run into any ... g5 tricks. } 8... Nc6
{ White has three options here and the only acceptable one is connected with parting with the e5-pawn. }
9. d4
{ The most common move in Lichess database, chosen 23 times out of 38 games. }
9... Qh4+ 10. g3 Qxd4 { Black is much better. } *

