[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "3.d4 without 6.Nxd7 #1/4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ This central strike is the 2nd big mainline in the Petroff. White ignores our e5-pawn for the time being and strikes at the centre, hoping that his extra tempo will give him either the advantage or the initiative. }
3... Nxe4
{ I think that allowing  3...exd4  4.e5!  is not something we have to agree on. Taking on e4 is much simpler, especially since we use this move against  3. Nxe5 as well, and some transpositional options are possible. }
4. dxe5
{ What I find amazing is that this move is the most popular on Lichess, but in practice, it is 10 times less frequent than 4. Bd3. It is understandable, since 4. dxe5 shouldn't give White even a shade of an edge. }
4... d5
{ Objectively best is  4...Bc5  when after  5.Bc4  Nxf2  6.Bxf7+  Kxf7  7.Qd5+  Kg6  @@StartBracket@@the only move@@EndBracket@@, Black has to know a ton of lines to reach a draw @@StartBracket@@at best@@EndBracket@@. It is extremely impractical to go for it in over-the-board chess @@StartBracket@@unless you are a professional player@@EndBracket@@, not to mention faster time controls. Therefore,  4...d5  is much more practical, even if the final result is not 0.00. }
5. Nbd2
{ The most promising plan, preparing to play Nxe4 followed by Qxd8+. Since I don't feel like moving the Knight from e4 makes sense, while taking on d2 is too cooperative, I suggest maintaining the Knight on e4 with the following rare plan. }
5... Qd7
{ Only the 10th most common move, played by beasts such as Giri and Caruana. The idea is to be able to meet Nxe4 with ... dxe4 without allowing White to misplace our King after Qxd8. It might look stupid to have the Queen on d7, but remember that White has to do something now! We are ready to target any of White's developing moves. }
6. Nxe4 dxe4 7. Nd4
{ 7.Qxd7+?  Nxd7  drops the e5-pawn. Note that  8.Ng5  Nxe5  9.Nxe4  Bf5  doesn't help White at all. }
7... Nc6 { White's centre is under pressure. There is only one way forward. }
8. Bb5 Bc5 9. Be3
{ White keeps the tension but we have a straightforward way to release it. }
9... Bxd4 10. Bxd4
{ 10.Qxd4  is possible but since the pin on the c6-Knight isn’t absolute, we can play  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd7+  Bxd7  12.Bxd4  O-O-O  with equality. }
10... Qd5 { White is forced to part with one of the Bishops. } 11. Ba4
{ I just want to point out that this doesn’t work.   11.Bxc6+  Qxc6  with  ... Be6/Bd7 and ...O-O-O to come is fully equal.   Similar is  11.a4  when after  11...a6  we force White to take on c6. }
11... b5 { We win one of the Bishops. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "3.d4 without 6.Nxd7 #2/4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ This central strike is the 2nd big mainline in the Petroff. White ignores our e5-pawn for the time being and strikes at the centre, hoping that his extra tempo will give him either the advantage or the initiative. }
3... Nxe4
{ I think that allowing  3...exd4  4.e5!  is not something we have to agree on. Taking on e4 is much simpler, especially since we use this move against  3. Nxe5 as well, and some transpositional options are possible. }
4. Bd3
{ This is the big mainline of the 3. d4 Nxe4 system. White wins a tempo by attacking the Knight, and will decide how to recapture on e5 later. }
4... d5
{ A way to surprise your opponent is  4...Nc6!?  when after  5.Bxe4  d5  we will win the piece back with a good position. Unfortunately, I didn't find a satisfactory solution to  4...Nc6  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  Nc5  7.Bc4  which looks pleasantly better for White. }
5. Nxe5
{ 5.dxe5  Nc5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  d5  5.Bd3  Nc5  variation. }
5... Nd7
{ The only move not to fall into some trouble. I dislike  5...Bd6  due to  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  when  7...c6  8.Nc3  gives White a very strong initiative.  5... Nd7 is simpler and better. }
6. O-O { Dealing with this modest move is rather easy. } 6... Nxe5
{ A recurring theme. We take on e5 and will play ... Nc5 next, winning a tempo on the Bishop. }
7. dxe5 Nc5
{ We will play ... c6 and then ... Be7 followed by ... O-O. At some point we can consider ... Nxd3, while whenever the d3-Bishop moves, we get an extra option in the form of ... Bf5. What you should also remember is that whenever White launches the f-pawn and plays f4, we should take on d3 and play ... g6. }
8. f4
{ I consider this pawn push to be a bit too barbaric to work. We didn't do anything wrong, so why should we be punished for no sins at all?! }
8... Nxd3 9. Qxd3
{ Note that in similar pawn structures, we meet  9.cxd3  with  9...Bf5  , hoping to provoke g4 when we would gladly reroute the Bishop to d7. }
9... g6 { White's main break f5 is successfully stopped. } 10. Be3 c6
{ We solidify the centre and prepare ... Bf5 followed by ... h5. Remember that we don't want to castle short @@StartBracket@@at least not yet@@EndBracket@@, and we will either keep the King in the centre or castle queenside. The fact that we want to play ... h5 and White has a 4v3 majority on the kingside should indicate that we should think twice before castling kingside.   After  10...c6  , we can see that White's space advantage is compensated by our Bishop pair. Especially the light squares are a juicy target for us to hit in the future.   Just please don't rush with  10...Bf5?!  due to  11.Qb5+  . }
*

