7. O-O Nxe5
{ A mandatory inclusion.  7...Nxc3?!  8.Qh5!  gives White an edge. } 8. dxe5
Nxc3
{ We have to grab the pawn. Otherwise, White would enjoy a significant edge without even giving up material. }
9. bxc3 Bxc3
{ White can either remove the Rook from attack or stop us from castling. } 10.
Rb1 { This is more popular, but we can get a good position by simple means. }
10... O-O 11. Bxh7+ { What else?! } 11... Kxh7 12. Qd3+ Kg8 13. Qxc3 a5
{ I like this plan. In the opposite-coloured Bishops middlegames, it is most of the time useful to put the pawns on the colours of our rival's Bishop. Not only do we control the b4-square and avoid some Rb4 lifts to the kingside, but we also prepare to play ... Ra6 next @@StartBracket@@shoutout to all the people who own my Budapest course!@@EndBracket@@. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. }
