[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ This central strike is the 2nd big mainline in the Petroff. White ignores our e5-pawn for the time being and strikes at the centre, hoping that his extra tempo will give him either the advantage or the initiative. }
3... Nxe4
{ I think that allowing  3...exd4  4.e5!  is not something we have to agree on. Taking on e4 is much simpler, especially since we use this move against  3. Nxe5 as well, and some transpositional options are possible. }
4. Bd3
{ This is the big mainline of the 3. d4 Nxe4 system. White wins a tempo by attacking the Knight and will decide how to recapture on e5 later. }
4... d5
{ A way to surprise your opponent is  4...Nc6!?  when after  5.Bxe4  d5  we will win the piece back with a good position. Unfortunately, I didn't find a satisfactory solution to  4...Nc6  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  Nc5  7.Bc4  looks pleasantly better for White. }
5. Nxe5
{ 5.dxe5  Nc5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  d5  5.Bd3  Nc5  variation. }
5... Nd7
{ The only move not to fall into some trouble. I dislike  5...Bd6  due to  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  when  7...c6  8.Nc3  gives White a very strong initiative.  5... Nd7 is simpler and better. }
6. Nxd7
{ After a few twists and turns, we arrive at the variation that is considered to be the mainline of 3. d4. White exchanges the loose Knight on e5 and will try to prove that Black's Knight on e4 is a liability. }
6... Bxd7 7. O-O
{ This is what you will see in over 80% of games that feature 6. Nxd7. White simply castles and will decide on his setup next. }
7... Bd6
{ White has all kinds of plans here - Nc3, Nd2, Re1, c4 or even Qh5. Of course, we won't cover all of them in the Quickstarter! }
8. Nc3
{ Only the 2nd most common choice, but definitely the most challenging option. The point of this move is not to attack the e4-pawn @@StartBracket@@  8.Nd2  tried that and it didn't work@@EndBracket@@ but to hit the d5-pawn instead. }
8... Nxc3
{ Since losing d5 is unacceptable @@StartBracket@@ask the Knight on e4 what it thinks about that@@EndBracket@@ and the King on e8 hints we don't have any tactical tricks yet, we should take on c3 voluntarily. White gets some temporary activity, but our long term prospects are excellent due to the better pawn structure. }
9. bxc3 O-O
{ Now, give us one tempo and we will play ... Qh4 or simply solidify the position with ... c6. That means that White should put the Queen on h5 immediately! }
10. Qh5
{ One thing I would like to mention before sticking to theory is that whenever White throws Rb1 in, unless you can play ... b5, just play ... b6 and press the clock @@StartBracket@@OK, if you play online just play it@@EndBracket@@. Going back to 10. Qh5. I consider blundering mate on h7 to be a bit sub-optimal, so we have to somehow cover h7. Since I also don't like giving pawns for free, we should cover d5 as well. There is only one way to do both. }
10... f5
{ OK, we had to weaken the e5-square, but don't forget that we have a bit better pawn structure on the queenside so it shouldn't be a big deal. Even though the Knights disappeared from the board @@StartBracket@@which should result in decreasing the number of blunders at least 6 times@@EndBracket@@, the position is still very rich and imbalanced.   White can try various ideas, such as Rb1 @@StartBracket@@attacking the b7-pawn@@EndBracket@@, Bg5 @@StartBracket@@trying to create something on the kingside@@EndBracket@@ or Re1, covering the e-file before doing anything else. In many of these lines, White will play c4, which we will usually meet with ... Be8 followed by ... dxc4 Bxc4+ Bf7.   I consider the position to be very interesting to play with Black, and one step in the wrong direction from our opponent will enable us to take over the initiative. }
11. Rb1 b6
{ The Rook appears on b1, we can't meet it with ... b5, so we play ... b6 and press the clock. If White plays slowly, we can continue with ... c6, ... Qf6 and ... Rae8. }
12. Re1
{ Putting the Rook on e1 is one of White's main ideas. Since we lack control over the e8-square, we need to be ready to meet Bg5 in some way. Usually, we will do it by freeing the c7-square for the Queen. }
12... c6
{ We solidify the d5-pawn and make room for the Queen at the same time. If White doesn't play vigorously, we will continue with ... Qf6-f7. }
13. Bg5 { Otherwise, we would play ... Qf6. } 13... Qc7
{ Since f6 is unavailable, we use c7 as a temporary stop for the Lady. We also connect the Rooks and create a battery on the h2-b8 diagonal. Now, if White doesn't use his initiative, we will continue with either ... b5 or ... Rae8. }
14. c4
{ This pawn break is the main plan for White. Our rival threatens cxd5 followed by Qf3 when we experience huge issues with d5. }
14... Be8
{ Please remember this way of dealing with c4. I have already mentioned it in the text, but it is the first time we see the actual variation featuring this idea. We will take on c4 next and block the check with ... Bf7. }
15. Qf3
{ The only benefit of  15.Qh3  is that after  15...dxc4  White can play  16.Bxf5  . Still, after  16...h6  , White's best shot at equality is  17.Be6+  Bf7  18.Bxh6  - everything else leads to a worse position for our rival.  18...gxh6  19.Qxh6  and here, after  19...Bxh2+  we will play ... Bf4 next or exchange Queens. In both cases, we are at least equal. }
15... dxc4 16. Bxc4+ Bf7
{ Now you can see the point why it was crucial to put the Bishop on e8 in the first place. }
17. Bxf7+ Rxf7
{ This is enough knowledge for this variation! After White defends against ... Bxh2+, we can continue with ... Qd7 to cover some sensitive light squares. White has a bit more active pieces, but we have fewer pawn islands. The position is balanced. }
