[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff Rare 3rd moves: 3.Bc4 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bc4
{ The Reversed Stafford Gambit which normally arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nxe5  Nc6  . Heaven for players who like to play for tricks only no matter what the objective strength of the move is. A Mekka for guys who don't care about the result of the game, but they feel the sadistic need to see their rival sweating for at least a few moves. I promise - if Elvis has played chess, then if he'd choose 3. Bc4, there would be no city named Memphis - Stafford it would be. On a serious note, this is a dangerous gambit if you don't know what to do against it. }
3... Nxe4
{ If you are into the safety-first approach, then  3...d5  4.exd5  e4  might be for you. However, the best way to refute this nonsense is to accept it. Before I show you the main ideas behind White's plan, I want to quickly mention two transpositions.   • @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2B1n3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nxe5  d5  is analyzed here @@StartBracket@@#1,  #2,  #3 @@EndBracket@@.   • @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2B1n3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qe2  d5  5.Nxe5  Bc5  is analyzed here. }
4. Nc3
{ The real gambit. White speeds up the development and hopes for tricks. } 4...
Nxc3
{ 4...Nf6  5.Nxe5  d5  would be a safe way forward.   Similar would be  4...Nc6  transposing to this line of the Four Knights chapter. However, I see no reason not to go for it and refute the gambit. }
5. dxc3
{ This is the first critical moment. White's hope is to lure us into playing  5...d6??  when after  6.Ng5  or  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Bxf7+  we lose the game. }
5... f6
{ Again, a way to bail out to an equal position is  5...c6  6.Nxe5  d5  .   Still, I believe in  5...f6  , and I promise it is worth spending a few trainable lines to get a big advantage. Our primary idea is to build a powerful centre continuing with ... c6 and ... d5. However, White's two main ideas fight against this plan, so I rather leave it up to you more as a fun fact and as a guideline on what White should find against. Since  6.Nxe5  doesn't work to both  6...Qe7  and  6...fxe5  7.Qh5+  g6  8.Qxe5  Qe7  pinning the Queen, let's see more serious stuff @@StartBracket@@if we can ever get serious about this gambit@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nh4 { White creates the threat of Qh5+. } 6... g6
{ The only way to parry it successfully. } 7. f4
{ As you can see, play here is very fast compared to the previous lines. } 7...
Qe7
{ This is the correct way of defending against f5. As a bonus, we threaten ... exf4+ and prepare to meet O-O?? with ... Qc5+. }
8. f5 Qg7 { The point. } 9. fxg6 hxg6 10. Qg4
{ This is the most direct way of attacking our position. Since both Qxg6 and Nxg6 are threats and the kingside is weakened, we will use a surprising resource. }
10... Kd8
{ Not only do we step out of danger, but by defending the Bishop, we create the threat of ... d5.  10...g5?  11.Nf5  with  Bd3  to come is wrong. With  10... Kd8, we dodge both captures.   •  11.Qxg6  drops the Knight.   •  11.Nxg6  d5  allows a discovered attack on the Queen. }
11. Qg3 { Otherwise, ... d5 would be deadly. } 11... g5
{ Only now, when we won an important tempo we are ready to play this move. As a result, the Knight on f5 won't be as stable as it would be after the immediate @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pppp2q1/5pp1/4p3/2B3QN/2P5/PPP3PP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...g5  . }
12. Nf5 Qh7 { Not only is the Knight hanging, but ... d5 is a threat as well. }
13. O-O
{ 13.Bd3  d5  doesn't help because White doesn't have any promising discoveries. }
13... d5 { Winning by force. } 14. Bxd5 { 14.Bd3  e4  is even worse. } 14...
Bxf5 15. Bxb7 Be4
{ We will end up with two pieces for the Rook. Amazingly, it is the White King who will be under attack.  16.Bxa8  Bxa8  17.Rxf6  Nd7  18.Bxg5  Kc8  is White's best hope, but with ... Bc5+ to come soon, we will start the attack. }
