1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bc4
{ The Reversed Stafford Gambit which normally arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nxe5  Nc6  . Heaven for players who like to play for tricks only no matter what the objective strength of the move is. A Mekka for guys who don't care about the result of the game, but they feel the sadistic need to see their rival sweating for at least a few moves. I promise - if Elvis has played chess, then if he'd choose 3. Bc4, there would be no city named Memphis - Stafford it would be. On a serious note, this is a dangerous gambit if you don't know what to do against it. }
3... Nxe4
{ If you are into the safety-first approach, then  3...d5  4.exd5  e4  might be for you. However, the best way to refute this nonsense is to accept it. Before I show you the main ideas behind White's plan, I want to quickly mention two transpositions.   • @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2B1n3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nxe5  d5  is analyzed here @@StartBracket@@#1,  #2,  #3 @@EndBracket@@.   • @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2B1n3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qe2  d5  5.Nxe5  Bc5  is analyzedhere. }
4. Nc3
{ The real gambit. White speeds up the development and hopes for tricks. } 4...
Nxc3
{ 4...Nf6  5.Nxe5  d5  would be a safe way forward.   Similar would be  4...Nc6  transposing to this line of the Four Knights chapter. However, I see no reason not to go for it and refute the gambit. }
5. dxc3
{ This is the first critical moment. White's hope is to lure us into playing  5...d6??  when after  6.Ng5  or  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Bxf7+  we lose the game. }
5... f6
{ Again, a way to bail out to an equal position is  5...c6  6.Nxe5  d5  .   Still, I believe in  5...f6  , and I promise it is worth spending a few trainable lines to get a big advantage. Our primary idea is to build a powerful centre continuing with ... c6 and ... d5. However, White's two primary ideas fight against this plan, so I rather leave it up to you more as a fun fact and as a guideline on what White should find against. Since  6.Nxe5  doesn't work to both  6...Qe7  and  6...fxe5  7.Qh5+  g6  8.Qxe5  Qe7  pinning the Queen, let's see more serious stuff @@StartBracket@@if we can ever get serious about this gambit@@EndBracket@@. }
6. O-O
{ If White wants to play Nh4, it is better to castle first because Nxe5 is an additional threat now. }
6... d6
{ There are also  6...Nc6  or  6...Qe7  , but I think that building a solid pawn centre is the way to go. This is one of those cases where I deliberately go for the theoretically inferior variation, but we will keep an edge and avoid a ton of sharp lines.   6...Nc6  7.b4  is one example of the variation I'd like to avoid.   Going back to  6...d6  , we would love to continue with ... c6 and then at some point ... d5. However, starting with ... d6 is mandatory to avoid Nxe5. In general, losing a tempo like this in positions where we are behind in development is very risky, but here, we are fully ready to parry White's ideas. }
7. Nh4 { This is the plan White usually continues with. } 7... g6
{ We have seen this pattern already. Qh5 is stopped. } 8. f4 d5
{ This move is the reason why I decided to offer 6... d6 as our weapon.   I dislike  8...Qe7  9.f5  Qg7  due to  10.Bd3  . Compared to the position without O-O and ... d6 included, this version is much worse - it should be obvious that castling kingside has been much more useful than ... d6.   8...d5  changes the character of the game entirely. We give back the extra pawn to transform the advantage from positional to a material one. Good news -  8...d5  has never been played over the board, while it has only been played online once - unsurprisingly, this individual's account has been closed already. What a coincidence! }
9. Bxd5 { Now, let me demonstrate the whole point of our plan. } 9... c6
{ No matter where the Bishop goes, we will throw in ... Bc5+ followed by the exchange of Queens and then ... e4. }
10. Bc4 Bc5+
{ Just remember to give this check first to force the King to h1. } 11. Kh1
Qxd1 12. Rxd1 e4
{ We will eventually support the pawn with ... f5. We can also play ... a5 to make sure the Bishop won't be hit with b4. In general, we should be delighted with the pawn structure we have now. All pawn endgames are completely winning and White's 4v3 on the queenside is meaningless. }
