[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "3.Nc3 Four Knights: Rare 4th moves: 4.Nxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet  3.Nc3  constantly, even by the players who after 2...Nc6 wouldn't even think about playing  3.Nc3  . The reason is simple - people usually don't like playing against the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence. Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  .  OK, so with  3... Nc6 we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian or my biggest fear - the mainline Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. First, we will devote our attention to the sidelines on move four. }
4. Nxe5
{ We are seven months from October at the time of this writing, but people don't care and play the Halloween Gambit anyway. I will suggest the most straightforward way of handling it. }
4... Nxe5 { OK, this one we do take. } 5. d4 Nc6
{ I would love to attach an exclam for practical value @@StartBracket@@for faster time controls@@EndBracket@@, but since  5...Ng6  is objectively @@StartBracket@@MUCH@@EndBracket@@ stronger, let's leave it as it is. Trust me on my word - this is the most practical way of playing and if your opponent will see it, he won't play the gambit for the 2nd time against you. Ever. }
6. d5 Bb4
{ This is the move. We give the piece back, but we will end up with a lead in development. This whole sequence is the highest scoring sequence when facing the Halloween Gambit @@StartBracket@@Lichess@@EndBracket@@. }
7. dxc6 Nxe4
{ We threaten to take the c3-Knight and simply want to take on c6 or castle kingside. }
8. Qd4 { Everything else is too cooperative. } 8... Qe7
{ The final move that you need to remember. We are ready to destroy White's pawn structure on c3 and castle kingside.  9.Be3  is best but after  9...O-O  10.Bd3  we play  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  Bd6  with an obvious structural advantage. Trust me, this is how you want to handle the Halloween Gambit unless you want to spend much more time learning its complexities @@StartBracket@@you might, and it will be rewarded for sure, but what for?!@@EndBracket@@. }
