1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet  3.Nc3  constantly, even by the players who after 2...Nc6 wouldn't even think about playing  3.Nc3  . The reason is simple - people usually don't like playing against the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence. Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  .  OK, so with  3... Nc6 we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian or my biggest fear - the mainline Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. First, we will devote our attention to the sidelines on move four. }
4. Bc4 { This is known to be inaccurate for I don't know, 500 years?! } 4...
Nxe4
{ One very common pattern in this course is that not only don't we let our rival transpose to any of his beloved openings like Italian or Scotch, but we also don't let him get the positions that resemble them structurally. For example, if we don't take on e4 here, White can play d3 and the positions will get a lot of Italian taste. Myself being a practitioner of pineapple on pizza, I am not sure I am allowed to talk about any Italian flavours, so we omit these options totally. }
5. Nxe4 { Only this way. } 5... d5 6. Bd3
{ This is the only chance for White to reach equality. } 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6
{ Myself, I have tested  7...Ne7!?  a lot with two points that  8.Nxe5  loses to  8...Qd4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1nppp/8/4p3/4B3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.O-O  loses to  8...f5  with ... e4 to come.   However, after  8.c3  , White should get an edge in the line where he never should get an edge, so I abandoned the concept, having tears in my eyes. }
8. O-O
{ 8.d4  liquidates the centre after  8...exd4  and after  9.O-O  O-O  10.Bg5  , I recommend keeping the pawn structure intact and playing  10...Qd7  . }
8... O-O 9. d3
{ Note that  9.d4?  blunders a pawn due to  9...Nxd4!  10.Nxd4  exd4  when  11.Qxd4??  loses to  11...Bxh2+  . }
9... Bg4 { Next is ... f5 with an attack. } *

