1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet 3. Nc3 constantly, even by the players who, after 2... Nc6, wouldn't even think about playing 3. Nc3. The reason is simple - people usually don't like facing the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence. Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  .  OK, so with  3... Nc6 we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian or my biggest fear - the mainline Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. First, we will devote our attention to the sidelines on move four. }
4. Bb5
{ The so-called Spanish Four Knights. White wants to keep things as simple as possible and get the positions that resemble the Italian or the closed lines of the Ruy Lopez. }
4... Nd4
{ Out of all variations from this course, I have spent the most time deciding on what to offer on the 4th move for us.   • I briefly covered  4...Bd6  , but I quickly rejected it because, after  5.d3  , White can get the type of position I dislike.   • I also checked  4...Bb4  , and I was very close to recommending it. All lines worked well. All but one. This one:  5.O-O  O-O  6.d3  d6  7.Ne2  , when after  7...Ne7  8.c3  Ba5  9.Ng3  c6  10.Ba4  Ng6  11.d4  , White can hope for a small edge. I also pondered @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/1b2P3/2NP1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bxc3  7.bxc3  d6  , but both  8.Re1  and  8.Bg5  look annoying - some slow manoeuvering game, atypical for this repertoire.  We want to play direct chess, and with  4... Nd4! we get it. We directly create the positional threat of ... Nxb5, but there is also ... c6 followed by hitting with ... d5. White has a handful of possibilities here, so let's go through them! }
5. Bc4
{ Finally, we arrive at the line that has the potential to be called the most complicated. I think it is fair to use the word 'potential' because I talk about the 5... Bc5 variation, which has been deeply analyzed by GM Jan Gustafsson in his excellent 1. e4 e5 course. Still, there is no need to enter these territories, especially knowing that the final verdict is a repetition of moves, and both sides must know the jungle of theory. }
5... c6
{ What can be more suitable for faster time controls than only the 4th most popular move and the one that scores 58% for Black?!?! 5... c6 is a multipurpose move. We want to play it anyway to cover d5 but we can also think about striking with ... d5 next. The good news is that the only challenging line for White involves going for the e5-pawn. }
6. Nxe5 { Taking the pawn is critical. } 6... d5
{ We shouldn't waste any time and seize the initiative in the centre. } 7. exd5
Bd6
{ Black's score - 75% out of 514 games @@StartBracket@@Lichess@@EndBracket@@! }
8. Nf3 { Only this way. } 8... Qe7+
{ It is necessary to disrupt White's development before doing anything else. Remember that we are two pawns down! }
9. Kf1 { 9.Be2?  Nxf3+  is unacceptable. } 9... Nxf3
{ A very important capture.  9...Bg4?  10.Be2  leads nowhere. } 10. Qxf3 O-O
{ Black has ideas such as ... Bg4, ... Re8 and ... b5. As a rule of thumb, any Queen trade offer should be met with ... Qd8 followed by ... Re8. The extended line can be found here. }
