[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2.Bc4 Nf6 3.d4 exd4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop's Opening. Before developing the Knights, White moves the Bishop, only to decide on his setup later. There are still some transpositions possible after  2...Nf6  3.Nc3  when we end up in a Vienna Game, but most of the time White will meet  2...Nf6  with  3.d3  . With the Knight still on g1, White can then decide if to play in the spirit of the Italian game with Nf3, maybe ponder some f4 ideas, or go for something else. }
2... Nf6
{ Of course, we develop this Knight first. We want to make sure that White does something about the hanging pawn on e4. Now, I have already mentioned that  3.Nc3  transposes to the Vienna Game after  3...Nxe4  .   I also want to point out that  3.Nf3?!  Nxe4  leads to the Reversed Stafford Gambit.   All the above means that White's decent original options are limited to two - it is either  3.d3  which is the mainline or  3.d4  which leads to the aggressive Urusov Gambit. }
3. d4
{ The so-called Urusov Gambit. An aggressive opening where if Black makes one inaccuracy, the consequences can be deadly. }
3... exd4
{ This one is obvious. The pawn has to be taken. Now, to prove that his previous play made any sense, White has to develop the Knight. }
4. Nf3
{ Only this way. White hopes to lure us into the Scotch Gambit lines after  4...Nc6  or into accepting the gambit with  4...Nxe4  when after  5.Qxd4  , White gets a dangerous initiative. }
4... Bb4+
{ Not only is this the most practical approach, but it is also most probably the best move from the theoretical perspective. We avoid any transpositions, make sure we will get an original position @@StartBracket@@not reachable via any other order@@EndBracket@@ and hold on to the pawn for the time being. }
5. c3 { Played around 10 times more frequently than  5.Bd2  . } 5... dxc3
{ Please pay extra attention to the following variations because White's practical score is quite high, mostly since one mistake on our part can be deadly. }
6. bxc3
{ The best try, hoping for  6...Bc5  7.e5  d5  8.exf6  dxc4  when after  9.Qe2+  Be6  10.fxg7  White has a strong initiative. Even though we are objectively better, I wouldn't dare to touch this variation. }
6... d5 { Simple chess. } 7. exd5
{ The position after  7.cxb4  dxc4  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  is better for us. We are a pawn up and threaten to take another one with ... Nxe4. }
7... Bd6
{ We will castle kingside and play ... Bg4/Bf5 next. The resulting position will be advantageous for us due to the better pawn structure and also because White's light-squared Bishop is weak. The best try for White might be  8.Qe2+  , but after  8...Qe7  9.Qxe7+  Kxe7  , we will play ...Re8 and ...Kf8 with a structural edge. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2.Bc4 Nf6 3.d3 c6 #1/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop's Opening. Before developing the Knights, White moves the Bishop, only to decide on his setup later. There are still some transpositions possible after  2...Nf6  3.Nc3  when we end up in a Vienna Game, but most of the time White will meet  2...Nf6  with  3.d3  . With the Knight still on g1, White can then decide if to play in the spirit of the Italian game with Nf3, maybe ponder some f4 ideas, or go for something else. }
2... Nf6
{ Of course, we develop this Knight first. We want to make sure that White does something about the hanging pawn on e4. Now, I have already mentioned that  3.Nc3  transposes to the Vienna Game after  3...Nxe4  .   I also want to point out that  3.Nf3?!  Nxe4  leads to the Reversed Stafford Gambit.   All the above means that White's decent original options are limited to two - it is either  3.d3  which is the mainline or  3.d4  which leads to the aggressive Urusov Gambit. }
3. d3
{ The 'proper' way to play the Bishop Opening. White defends the pawn and will most probably play 4.Nf3 next. It is an important moment because if we continue in the most stereotypical way with  3...Nc6  or  3...Bc5  , then after  4.Nf3  , we will end up in the Italian Opening! }
3... c6
{ No transpositions for you, sir! Also, it is objectively the best move for Black. We want to exploit the Bishop's placement on c4 by striking with ... d5 and winning a tempo. Also, since the pawn is already on d3, there is no need to worry about any d4 ideas.   Since something like  4.Nc3?!  only creates another target after  4...d5  5.exd5  cxd5  6.Bb3  Bb4  threatening ... d4, we will cover the lines where White prepares to meet ... d5 exclusively. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing the Knight to f3 is the key idea for the opening. White hopes that quick development will prove sufficient for an edge @@StartBracket@@SPOILER ALERT: it won't@@EndBracket@@. }
4... d5 5. Bb3
{ This is the tabiya for the Bishop Opening. The e5-pawn is hanging and White hopes to trick us into  5...dxe4?  6.Ng5!   I hope we are not so naive, so we have three options. We can put the Bishop on d6 immediately, which is the most common choice, we can also play  5...Bb4+  and drop the Bishop back to d6 later, or we can go for something less common and much more venomous! }
5... a5
{ An exclamation mark is purely for the practical value of this move. It is only the 3rd most popular option in over-the-board chess and the 4th online. What convinced me to go for this aggressive approach is the fact that after the other tries, White scores a respected 50%+, while after 5... a5, the score drops to 42%. The big idea behind 5... a5 is to force White into some concessions because of the threat of ... a4. There are four ways to stop it, but in the Quickstarter, we will check two of them. }
6. a3 { A no-nonsense approach, but we can grab space for free. } 6... a4
{ Think about some endgames - the a3-pawn is fixed and White can't really touch the queenside. Going for b3 will allow ... axb3 while c3 will weaken the b3-square permanently. }
7. Ba2 Bd6 8. Nc3 Be6
{ We solidify d5 and force White to keep attacking the centre. } 9. Bg5
{ A common move that fails to the following idea. } 9... d4
{ White can't go for  10.Bxe6?!  due to  10...dxc3  . Therefore, he has to allow ... Bxa2 when we castle kingside and push the queenside pawns up the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2.Bc4 Nf6 3.d3 c6 #2/2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The Bishop's Opening. Before developing the Knights, White moves the Bishop, only to decide on his setup later. There are still some transpositions possible after  2...Nf6  3.Nc3  when we end up in a Vienna Game, but most of the time White will meet  2...Nf6  with  3.d3  . With the Knight still on g1, White can then decide if to play in the spirit of the Italian game with Nf3, maybe ponder some f4 ideas, or go for something else. }
2... Nf6
{ Of course, we develop this Knight first. We want to make sure that White does something about the hanging pawn on e4. Now, I have already mentioned that  3.Nc3  transposes to the Vienna Game after  3...Nxe4  .   I also want to point out that  3.Nf3?!  Nxe4  leads to the Reversed Stafford Gambit.   All the above means that White's decent original options are limited to two - it is either  3.d3  which is the mainline or  3.d4  which leads to the aggressive Urusov Gambit. }
3. d3
{ The 'proper' way to play the Bishop Opening. White defends the pawn and will most probably play 4.Nf3 next. It is an important moment because if we continue in the most stereotypical way with  3...Nc6  or  3...Bc5  , then after  4.Nf3  , we will end up in the Italian Opening! }
3... c6
{ No transpositions for you, sir! Also, it is objectively the best move for Black. We want to exploit the Bishop's placement on c4 by striking with ... d5 and winning a tempo. Also, since the pawn is already on d3, there is no need to worry about any d4 ideas.   Since something like  4.Nc3?!  only creates another target after  4...d5  5.exd5  cxd5  6.Bb3  Bb4  threatening ... d4, we will cover the lines where White prepares to meet ... d5 exclusively. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing the Knight to f3 is the key idea for the opening. White hopes that quick development will prove sufficient for an edge @@StartBracket@@SPOILER ALERT: it won't@@EndBracket@@. }
4... d5 5. Bb3
{ This is the tabiya for the Bishop Opening. The e5-pawn is hanging and White hopes to trick us into  5...dxe4?  6.Ng5!   I hope we are not so naive, so we have three options. We can put the Bishop on d6 immediately, which is the most common choice, we can also play  5...Bb4+  and drop the Bishop back to d6 later, or we can go for something less common and much more venomous! }
5... a5
{ An exclamation mark is purely for the practical value of this move. It is only the 3rd most popular option in over-the-board chess and the 4th online. What convinced me to go for this aggressive approach is the fact that after the other tries, White scores a respected 50%+, while after 5... a5, the score drops to 42%. The big idea behind 5... a5 is to force White into some concessions because of the threat of ... a4. There are four ways to stop it, and we will take a look at all of them. }
6. a4
{ Probably best. All of the nonsense connected with ... a4 is avoided, while the threat of Nxe5 is renewed. }
6... Bb4+
{ A very important intermezzo.  6...Bd6?!  7.exd5  cxd5  8.Bg5  Be6  9.Nc3  and White's army pressurizes our centre. We probably need to play  9...d4  , which is already a concession. }
7. c3 Bd6
{ We wasted one move, but the c3-square is occupied by a pawn, and we don't have to worry about Nc3. }
8. exd5
{ White usually takes, because otherwise we can capture on e4 and reach a stable pawn structure with a solid position for us. }
8... cxd5 9. Bg5 Be6
{ Black has a strong centre. More in-depth analysis can be found here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2.d4 without 3.Qxd4: 3.Nf3 Bb4+ "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ The Centre Game. White usually plays this move to get an open game and focus more on tactics than strategy. I recommend treating this chapter very seriously for two main reasons:  •  2.d4  is the 4th most popular move which is played around once every fifteen games. Not much but also it is not a small number.  • The positions don't resemble anything else and require an unstereotypical approach. We should also be aware that White has three independent options after we play  2...exd4  , and all of them have a bit different flavour. }
2... exd4
{ Nothing else makes sense. Now,  3.Bc4  Nf6  leads to the Urusov Gambit which has been analyzedhere, so let's cover the independent possibilities White has. }
3. Nf3
{ By using this move order, White hopes to lure us into the Scotch after  3...Nc6  . or the Scotch Gambit after  3...Bc5  . We have to say no. }
3... Bb4+
{ The best move, both theoretically, and practically. We don't allow any transpositions and make sure that White will think twice before using this move order against us again. }
4. c3
{ This is the gambit way of handling things. However, we are fully ready to at some point give the pawn back for positional dividends. }
4... dxc3 5. bxc3
{ What amazes me the most is that this is the most common try. } 5... Bc5 6.
Bc4 d6
{ Now, where is White's compensation?! We can safely play ... Nc6 and then either ... Nf6 or ... Nge7. If White plays Qb3, we can go for ... Qe7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2.d4 with 3.Qxd4: 3...Nc6 4.Qe3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ The Centre Game. White usually plays this move to get an open game and focus more on tactics than strategy. I recommend treating this chapter very seriously for two main reasons:  •  2.d4  is the 4th most popular move which is played around once every fifteen games. Not much but also it is not a small number.  • The positions don't resemble anything else and require an unstereotypical approach. We should also be aware that White has three independent options after we play  2...exd4  , and all of them have a bit different flavour. }
2... exd4
{ Nothing else makes sense. Now,  3.Bc4  Nf6  leads to the Urusov Gambit which has been analyzedhere, so let's cover the independent possibilities White has. }
3. Qxd4
{ The Centre Game. It has always reminded me of a Scandinavian with an extra e4 from White. With this approach, White really makes sure that there will be some bare-knuckle fight ahead. OK, fine, let's take the gloves off then and show our opponent our war face. }
3... Nc6
{ We obviously win a tempo on the Queen. White has a few options now. } 4. Qe3
{ Historically, retreating the Queen to e3 has always been the main move. }
4... Nf6
{ This is the tabiya for the Centre Game. White has to decide on his future setup and I believe that only one option guarantees him equality. }
5. Nc3
{ Developing the Knight to c3 has always been the mainline. Still, it allows us to go for the following resource. }
5... Bb4
{ We simply want to continue with ... O-O and then a combination of ... Re8 and ... d5. }
6. Bd2 O-O 7. O-O-O Re8 { This is the tabiya for the 4. Qe3 variation. } 8. Qg3
{ This is how people played this line in the 20th century. Real coffeehouse chess - put the Queen on g3 and hope for some Bh6 ideas to work. }
8... Rxe4
{ I consider this to be the more practical of the two captures available.  8...Nxe4  9.Nxe4  Rxe4  should give White a few more options compared to my chosen line.   After  8...Rxe4  , White can't take  9.Nxe4?  due to  9...Nxe4  and we get the material back with dividends. }
9. Bg5
{ Visibly dangerous, but not so dangerous when you learn the following variation. }
9... Bxc3 10. Qxc3 d5 { I suggest going for the following forcing variation. }
11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. Rxd5 Bg4
{ The point of the whole line. We threaten ... Re1+.   Note that  13...Re1+?!  14.Rd1  Rxd1+  15.Kxd1  Bf5  is not so strong with the White f-pawn being on the starting square because of  16.Nf3  Rd8+  17.Nd2  . }
14. f3 Re1+ 15. Rd1 Rxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Bf5
{ Black is much better due to the better development and a safer King. Next is ... Nb4/Nd4 and ... Rd8+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Petroff 7.Qxe5"]
[Black "7.Qxe5 Qxe5+ 8.dxe5 Nc6 9.f4 Bf5 #1/5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ This is the very first course where I analyze something symmetrical. My general approach is to avoid symmetry and look for imbalances right from the start. However, I was shocked to discover how interesting the line I am going to recommend can get! }
2. Nf3
{ We will start by analyzing the mainline first, and leave the sidelines for the end. }
2... Nf6
{ Don't worry! I'm not suggesting entering the 'proper' Petroff. We will play something a bit more obscure :@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nxe5 { The alternatives on move 3 are analyzed in chapters 7, 8 and 9. }
3... Nxe4
{ In the first chess book that I ever touched, 'Chess Openings' by Theodor Schuster, one of the first openings that have been checked is the so-called Damiano Petroff, starting with the text move  3...Nxe4  . I remember the trap that arises after  4.Qe2  Nf6  5.Nc6+  is the first that I have ever learned, and for almost 20 years, I thought that this opening was simply refuted. Well, it is not! I am far from claiming that this line equalizes because it doesn't. However, I can make a few promises @@StartBracket@@I always keep them!@@EndBracket@@:     • There is only one sequence that leads to an edge for White. White has to play five precise moves to get an edge.  • The vast majority @@StartBracket@@95%+@@EndBracket@@ of players will have no clue what is going on after either  3...Nxe4  or  4.Qe2  Qe7  .  The Damiano Petroff is so neglected by theory @@StartBracket@@and practice@@EndBracket@@ that the chance of surprising your opponent in blitz or rapid is close to 100%.   • Even though the line is absolutely symmetrical, there will be a lot of dynamism going on in the next few moves in most cases.   • Last, it is MUCH more fun to play than it looks! Before I show you what the point behind 3... Nxe4 is, I want to mention that to this day, I played 66 training blitz games with this line, scoring 62% with Black. However, when I was playing this line, I barely knew any theory and I improvised a lot.   OK, let's see what this is all about! By taking on e4, we try to equalize by force by liquidating the centre. Usually, such an approach is preceded by the move 3... d6, making sure that White will retreat the Knight first, and only then do we take on e4. The 3... Nxe4 line is more dynamic. It is objectively worse than 3... d6, but it poses some immediate challenges. By keeping the pawn on d7, we will often play ... d5 in one go, leaving White with one move only to push for an edge.   OK, to be more specific, White can push in a few ways, but only one idea guarantees an edge. }
4. Qe2
{ Usually, White's theory will end here. Sometimes I like to use some bad jokes, but here, I am 100% serious. By playing 4. Qe2, White not only attacks our Knight, but also prepares discovered checks with the e5-Knight. This leaves us with no choice, meaning that the symmetry has to be sustained.   Note that the alternatives to 4. Qe2 will be analyzed in chapter 6. }
4... Qe7
{ Now, if White doesn't take on e4, Black will fully equalize. You can check those non-ambitious tries in chapter6. }
5. Qxe4 { Out of 1219 games, White chose this option in 1178 of them. } 5... d6
{ Now, White faces a threat of ... Qxe5/dxe5 which must be stopped. } 6. d4
{ White's choice in around 90% of games. Sometimes White decides on  6.f4  @@StartBracket@@chapter 5@@EndBracket@@,  and sometimes White simply allows ... Qxe5, which gives us an excellent game with no effort.  6.Nc3  Qxe5  7.d3  Bf5  is one example. }
6... dxe5
{ Now, we are at a crossroads. Out of around 1000 games, White chose to take on e5 with the Queen in 1/3 of them, and with the pawn in 2/3. Since I consider taking with the Queen less accurate, we will start with it. I also truly believe that the following variations will demonstrate the hidden power of our position. }
7. Qxe5 Qxe5+
{ We bank our play on the lead in development. Please don't try something like  7...Be6?  due to  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.Bb5  and we are significantly worse. By taking on e5:  • We get rid of the Queen that was blocking the Bishop and would slow our development down.  • White will be left with the pawn on e5, which will be a target.  • Finally, we will be left with a lead in development, and we exactly know where our pieces are going. The Knight will go to c6 and the Bishop usually to f5. The only lines where the Bishop is developed to d7 are those where White plays Bb5. Then we will follow with queenside castling. You should also look for opportunities to use the c6-Knight to jump to b4. }
8. dxe5 Nc6
{ 8...Bf5  is also possible and is in fact the most popular move for Black, but I think that moving the Knight first has no drawbacks at all. It also fits the general rule of developing the Knights first. After  8...Nc6  , White has three ways of defending the pawn. }
9. f4
{ Two inaccuracies in a row, and White is already worse! It is impossible to get a good position by neglecting development so much. }
9... Bf5
{ Another tempo move! We combine threats to the c2-pawn with queenside castling, when our lead in development will start to tell. }
10. Bd3 { This move is only a temporary solution. } 10... Bxd3 11. cxd3 Nb4
{ White can't cover both d3 and c2.  12.Kd2  O-O-O  doesn't really help. } *

