6... dxe5
{ Now, we are at a crossroads. Out of around 1000 games, White chose to take on e5 with the Queen in 1/3 of them, and with the pawn in 2/3. Since I consider taking with the Queen less accurate, we will start with it. I also truly believe that the following variations will demonstrate the hidden power of our position. }
7. Qxe5 Qxe5+
{ We bank our play on the lead in development. Please don't try something like  7...Be6?  due to  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.Bb5  and we are significantly worse. By taking on e5:  • We get rid of the Queen that was blocking the Bishop and would slow our development down.  • White will be left with the pawn on e5, which will be a target.  • Finally, we will be left with a lead in development, and we exactly know where our pieces are going. The Knight will go to c6 and the Bishop usually to f5. The only lines where the Bishop is developed to d7 are those where White plays Bb5. Then we will follow with queenside castling. You should also look for opportunities to use the c6-Knight to jump to b4. }
8. dxe5 Nc6
{ 8...Bf5  is also possible and is in fact the most popular move for Black, but I think that moving the Knight first has no drawbacks at all. It also fits the general rule of developing the Knights first. After  8...Nc6  , White has three ways of defending the pawn. }
9. f4
{ Two inaccuracies in a row, and White is already worse! It is impossible to get a good position by neglecting development so much. }
9... Bf5
{ Another tempo move! We combine threats to the c2-pawn with queenside castling, when our lead in development will start to tell. }
10. c3 { White has to lose another tempo with the pawn. } 10... O-O-O
{ We safeguarded the King and will usually strike with ... f6 or ... g5 next. In general, we should prefer to go for ... f6 when we can meet exf6 with ... Bc5 followed by ... Rhe8+ with tragic consequences for White. However, since White usually stops this idea, I mention the ... f6 plan more as a fun fact than something we will play. }
11. Bb5 { Let me first show you how dangerous ignoring our idea might get. }
11... f6 { White should allow us to get the pawn back. } 12. exf6 Bc5
{ Trust me or not, the threat of ... Rhe8+ should end the game soon. } *

