{ 8...Bf5  is also possible and is in fact the most popular move for Black, but I think that moving the Knight first has no drawbacks at all. It also fits the general rule of developing the Knights first. After  8...Nc6  , White has three ways of defending the pawn. }
9. Bf4
{ If White wants to defend the pawn directly, this is the way to do it. Our rival avoids creating permanent weaknesses as seen in the previous lines and develops the piece at the same time. Still, everything has a price. The e5-pawn is not as well defended as in the 9. f4 variation, and there is no way to defend it in the long run. }
9... Bf5 { Again, a tempo move. We want to castle queenside next. } 10. c3
O-O-O
{ Not only developing, but also creating the threat of ... Nxe5. What is wonderful is that we don't usually have to prepare ... Nxe5 as long as we can meet Bxe5 with ... Re8. }
11. Bc4
{ This active plan is probably the most interesting. White forgets about the e5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside while eyeing the f7-pawn. It is also interesting that with the text move, White scores highly over 60%, so we will see what this is all about! }
11... Nxe5 { Again this 'trick'. } 12. Bxe5 Re8 13. f4
{ There is one simple reason why this move is bad. White will inevitably lose the dark-squared Bishop, and weakening the g1-a7 diagonal like this is positionally suicidal. A relatively forced line starts now. }
13... f6 14. O-O fxe5 15. fxe5 Bc5+ 16. Kh1 Rhf8
{ This is the reason why I decided to extend the line so much.  16...Rxe5??  17.Rxf5  would be embarrassing. After  16...Rhf8  , the e5-pawn is lost in the long run, resulting in a clear edge for us. We have the Bishop pair and no weaknesses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Petroff 7.Qxe5"]
[Black "7.Qxe5 Qxe5+ 8.dxe5 Nc6 9.Bf4 Bf5 #4/4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ This is the very first course where I analyze something symmetrical. My general approach is to avoid symmetry and look for imbalances right from the start. However, I was shocked to discover how interesting the line I am going to recommend can get! }
2. Nf3
{ We will start by analyzing the mainline first, and leave the sidelines for the end. }
2... Nf6
{ Don't worry! I'm not suggesting entering the 'proper' Petroff. We will play something a bit more obscure :@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nxe5 { The alternatives on move 3 are analyzed in chapters 7, 8 and 9. }
3... Nxe4
{ In the first chess book that I ever touched, 'Chess Openings' by Theodor Schuster, one of the first openings that have been checked is the so-called Damiano Petroff, starting with the text move  3...Nxe4  . I remember the trap that arises after  4.Qe2  Nf6  5.Nc6+  is the first that I have ever learned, and for almost 20 years, I thought that this opening was simply refuted. Well, it is not! I am far from claiming that this line equalizes because it doesn't. However, I can make a few promises @@StartBracket@@I always keep them!@@EndBracket@@:     • There is only one sequence that leads to an edge for White. White has to play five precise moves to get an edge.  • The vast majority @@StartBracket@@95%+@@EndBracket@@ of players will have no clue what is going on after either  3...Nxe4  or  4.Qe2  Qe7  .  The Damiano Petroff is so neglected by theory @@StartBracket@@and practice@@EndBracket@@ that the chance of surprising your opponent in blitz or rapid is close to 100%.   • Even though the line is absolutely symmetrical, there will be a lot of dynamism going on in the next few moves in most cases.   • Last, it is MUCH more fun to play than it looks! Before I show you what the point behind 3... Nxe4 is, I want to mention that to this day, I played 66 training blitz games with this line, scoring 62% with Black. However, when I was playing this line, I barely knew any theory and I improvised a lot.   OK, let's see what this is all about! By taking on e4, we try to equalize by force by liquidating the centre. Usually, such an approach is preceded by the move 3... d6, making sure that White will retreat the Knight first, and only then do we take on e4. The 3... Nxe4 line is more dynamic. It is objectively worse than 3... d6, but it poses some immediate challenges. By keeping the pawn on d7, we will often play ... d5 in one go, leaving White with one move only to push for an edge.   OK, to be more specific, White can push in a few ways, but only one idea guarantees an edge. }
4. Qe2
{ Usually, White's theory will end here. Sometimes I like to use some bad jokes, but here, I am 100% serious. By playing 4. Qe2, White not only attacks our Knight, but also prepares discovered checks with the e5-Knight. This leaves us with no choice, meaning that the symmetry has to be sustained.   Note that the alternatives to 4. Qe2 will be analyzed in chapter 6. }
4... Qe7
{ Now, if White doesn't take on e4, Black will fully equalize. You can check those non-ambitious tries in chapter6. }
5. Qxe4 { Out of 1219 games, White chose this option in 1178 of them. } 5... d6
{ Now, White faces a threat of ... Qxe5/dxe5 which must be stopped. } 6. d4
{ White's choice in around 90% of games. Sometimes White decides on  6.f4  @@StartBracket@@chapter 5@@EndBracket@@,  and sometimes White simply allows ... Qxe5, which gives us an excellent game with no effort.  6.Nc3  Qxe5  7.d3  Bf5  is one example. }
6... dxe5
{ Now, we are at a crossroads. Out of around 1000 games, White chose to take on e5 with the Queen in 1/3 of them, and with the pawn in 2/3. Since I consider taking with the Queen less accurate, we will start with it. I also truly believe that the following variations will demonstrate the hidden power of our position. }
7. Qxe5 Qxe5+
{ We bank our play on the lead in development. Please don't try something like  7...Be6?  due to  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.Bb5  and we are significantly worse. By taking on e5:  • We get rid of the Queen that was blocking the Bishop and would slow our development down.  • White will be left with the pawn on e5, which will be a target.  • Finally, we will be left with a lead in development, and we exactly know where our pieces are going. The Knight will go to c6 and the Bishop usually to f5. The only lines where the Bishop is developed to d7 are those where White plays Bb5. Then we will follow with queenside castling. You should also look for opportunities to use the c6-Knight to jump to b4. }
8. dxe5 Nc6
{ 8...Bf5  is also possible and is in fact the most popular move for Black, but I think that moving the Knight first has no drawbacks at all. It also fits the general rule of developing the Knights first. After  8...Nc6  , White has three ways of defending the pawn. }
9. Bf4
{ If White wants to defend the pawn directly, this is the way to do it. Our rival avoids creating permanent weaknesses as seen in the previous lines and develops the piece at the same time. Still, everything has a price. The e5-pawn is not as well defended as in the 9. f4 variation, and there is no way to defend it in the long run. }
9... Bf5 { Again, a tempo move. We want to castle queenside next. } 10. c3
O-O-O
{ Not only developing, but also creating the threat of ... Nxe5. What is wonderful is that we don't usually have to prepare ... Nxe5 as long as we can meet Bxe5 with ... Re8. }
11. Bc4
{ This active plan is probably the most interesting. White forgets about the e5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside while eyeing the f7-pawn. It is also interesting that with the text move, White scores highly over 60%, so we will see what this is all about! }
11... Nxe5 { Again this 'trick'. } 12. Bxe5 Re8 13. O-O Rxe5 14. Bxf7
{ This is White's idea.  14.Nd2  f6  with ... Bd6 to come leaves us on the better side of equality, having the Bishop pair for free. }
14... Bd3
{ I hesitated a bit between this and  14...Re2  , but I think that my choice is more ambitious. Instead of trying to get the pawn back at once, we speed up our development. }
15. Rd1 Bc5
{ The Bishop is taboo. Only now do we want to play ... Re2, but ... Rf8 is an even bigger threat to parry. White's task of finding the right sequence is pretty challenging. }
16. Na3
{ Otherwise, ... Rf8 would be deadly.  16.b4  Rf8  leaves White with no development and multiple weaknesses. }
16... Be2 17. Re1 Rf8 18. Nc4 { Only this idea saves the day. } 18... Bxf2+
{ I briefly thought about  18...Re7  19.Ne3  Rexf7  20.Rxe2  Rxf2  21.Rxf2  Bxe3  but after  22.Raf1  , White holds. }
19. Kxf2 Rxf7+ 20. Kg1 Ree7
{ The Bishop in an open position guarantees us an edge. What makes matters worse is that White can't play Rd1. }
*

