13. Nd2 { 13.Nc3  Bb4!  followed by ... Bxc3 is excellent for Black. } 13...
Bc5
{ Another point of the move 12...b6. We are ready to meet  14.Bxc5  with  14...Rxd2  when we win at least one pawn.   White's best shot here is  14.Rad1  Bxe3  15.fxe3  Rhe8  16.Nf3  Rxd1  17.Rxd1  Bxf3  18.gxf3  Rxe5  when the engine screams 'DRAW', but we have fewer pawn islands and can hope to outplay our opponent. OK, let's say that out loud. 7.Qxe5 is not the way to go. Black gets excellent chances and positions that are fun to play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Petroff 7.dxe5: Rare 8th moves"]
[Black "7.dxe5 Nc6 8.Bf4 g5 #1/4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5
{ In this and the next two chapters, we will check what is considered to be the mainline for White. By taking with the pawn, White keeps the Queens on the board and leaves us with a bit misplaced Queen on e7. Let's also not forget that our opponent is a pawn up! However, there are positives too! The position of our Queen might not be bad at all. The pawn on e5 is under attack and we are one step closer from castling queenside. }
7... Nc6
{ As you can see, our position is extremely logical and intuitive to play. White faces the threat of ... Qxe5, and to get any advantage at all, he has to give the extra pawn back with  8.Nc3  . We will see that approach in chapter 4. In chapter 3 we will cover what is considered by many sources as a refutation of our concept @@StartBracket@@undeservedly!@@EndBracket@@ and in the current chapter, we will see all the alternatives where White tries to defend the pawn at all costs.. }
8. Bf4
{ We will start our coverage with my favourite move to meet. Since I consider this repertoire to be a perfect weapon for blitz and rapid, I will usually base the statistics on the Lichess database because there is quite a big sample size of games there.   8. Bf4 has been White's choice in 2280 games out of 13 898. This gives us around a 1/6 chance that our rival will play this move. What is absolutely amazing is that the chance that he will blunder on the next move @@StartBracket@@in faster time controls@@EndBracket@@ is around 90%! }
8... g5
{ We attack the Bishop and plan to win the pawn back in the not-so-distant future. }
9. Bg3 { White's choice in 1313 games out of 1509 in Lichess database. } 9...
f5
{ The point! White probably thought that he would use the tricky 'en passant' rule against us, but since the Queen is pinned along the e-file, it won't be an option! Therefore, we will play ... f4 next and win the Bishop.  Do you know what is amazing? If you reach the position after 7. dxe5 Nc6, in around 10-15% of games you will win with this trick! The victims of this trap in my training games are an IM and a GM, so no matter the level, people will fall into it constantly! }
10. Qe2 { White usually tries to create some complications with Qh5 next. }
10... f4 11. Nc3
{ This is the way to prepare fast long castling. I decided to extend the variation to show you that you don’t have to capture the Bishop right away, but you can play: }
11... Qxe5
{ This first, forcing the exchange of Queens and only then going for the Bishop. Black ends up a clear piece up. }
