[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5
{ In this and the next two chapters, we will check what is considered to be the mainline for White. By taking with the pawn, White keeps the Queens on the board and leaves us with a bit misplaced Queen on e7. Let's also not forget that our opponent is a pawn up! However, there are positives too! The position of our Queen might not be bad at all. The pawn on e5 is under attack and we are one step closer from castling queenside. }
7... Nc6
{ As you can see, our position is extremely logical and intuitive to play. White faces the threat of ... Qxe5, and to get any advantage at all, he has to give the extra pawn back with  8.Nc3  . We will see that approach in chapter 4. In chapter 3 we will cover what is considered by many sources as a refutation of our concept @@StartBracket@@undeservedly!@@EndBracket@@ and in the current chapter, we will see all the alternatives where White tries to defend the pawn at all costs.. }
8. Bf4
{ We will start our coverage with my favourite move to meet. Since I consider this repertoire to be a perfect weapon for blitz and rapid, I will usually base the statistics on the Lichess database because there is quite a big sample size of games there.   8. Bf4 has been White's choice in 2280 games out of 13 898. This gives us around a 1/6 chance that our rival will play this move. What is absolutely amazing is that the chance that he will blunder on the next move @@StartBracket@@in faster time controls@@EndBracket@@ is around 90%! }
8... g5
{ We attack the Bishop and plan to win the pawn back in the not-so-distant future. }
9. Bb5
{ This is the best move for White, but the chance of meeting it is quite low @@StartBracket@@less than 1% in faster games I would say@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Bd7
{ The tactical threat of ... gxf4 and the positional threat of ... f5 are renewed. White has only one good move here. }
10. e6
{ 10.Bg3??  f5!  is another version of the trap from the beginning of this chapter.   10.Bd2?!  is a worse version of the previous line because White’s Bishop isn’t doing much on b5, and after  10...f5!  followed by ...O-O-O, we can either focus on capturing on e5 right away or prepare it with moves such as ...a6 and ...Bg7. }
10... Bxe6
{ I hesitated a bit here which capture to go for and my conclusion is that  10...fxe6!?  is interesting, but leaves us with a slightly weakened pawn structure.  10...Qxe6?!  is probably the worst of options since after  11.Qxe6+  fxe6  12.Be3  we are left with a weakened pawn structure and the Queens are off which reduces our counterplay. That's why I decided to keep things a little more complicated and suggest taking with the Bishop. If White just retreats the hanging Bishop to d2 or c1, we will play ... Bd5 or ... Bf5 with an excellent position.   After  11.Be3  O-O-O  we get a good position by simple means.   Finally,  11.Bg3?  is bad as usual since after  11...O-O-O  , ... f5 is coming. }
11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O
{ 12.Be5  has never been played but it is interesting. Black should play  12...Bd5  13.Qe3  Rg8  and then we will castle long and go for the manoeuvre ... Rg6-e6 - that's all you need to know @@StartBracket@@you probably don't even need to know that@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Bd5
{ If you would like to keep things more complicated, then  12...O-O-O!?  13.Be3  Qb4  might suit you. After  14.Qxb4  Bxb4  15.Bxg5  Rd5  16.Be3  Rg8  Black seems to get almost full compensation for the pawn. }
13. Qxe7+
{ 13.Qd4?!  gxf4  14.Qxh8?  loses to  14...Qg5  with ... O-O-O to come next. }
13... Bxe7 14. Bxc7 Bf6 { We equalize by force. } 15. Nc3
{ 15.c3  gives Black a strong initiative after  15...Kd7  16.Bg3  h5  17.h3  h4  18.Bh2  g4!  19.hxg4  h3!  when White is under huge pressure. }
15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 f6
{ The presence of opposite-coloured Bishops makes White's extra pawn irrelevant. Next is ... Kf7 followed by ... Rhe8. }
