[White "2) Petroff 7.dxe5: Rare 8th moves"]
[Black "7.dxe5 Nc6 8.f4 Bg4 #1/6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5
{ In this and the next two chapters, we will check what is considered to be the mainline for White. By taking with the pawn, White keeps the Queens on the board and leaves us with a bit misplaced Queen on e7. Let's also not forget that our opponent is a pawn up! However, there are positives too! The position of our Queen might not be bad at all. The pawn on e5 is under attack and we are one step closer from castling queenside. }
7... Nc6
{ As you can see, our position is extremely logical and intuitive to play. White faces the threat of ... Qxe5, and to get any advantage at all, he has to give the extra pawn back with  8.Nc3  . We will see that approach in chapter 4. In chapter 3 we will cover what is considered by many sources as a refutation of our concept @@StartBracket@@undeservedly!@@EndBracket@@ and in the current chapter, we will see all the alternatives where White tries to defend the pawn at all costs.. }
8. f4
{ Defending e5 with the pawn is more direct but as usual, it has two major disadvantages:   • It doesn't contribute to development.   • The g1-a7 diagonal has been weakened. }
8... Bg4
{ A very strong move that can be chosen by a process of elimination. We need to castle queenside as fast as possible to prove our compensation. That means that we should develop the Bishop in the first place. The question that remains is: where?   • f5 and h3 don't seem to be the right squares in this specific position.   • On e6, the Bishop would be prone to the f5 ideas in the future and the tension between the Black Queen and the e5-pawn would be disrupted.   • Finally, we play ... Bd7 only in the case of Bb5, so the choice is obvious.   Now, ... Bg4 is not only the kind of move that we play because there is no better alternative. The Bishop is really well placed on g4, covering some squares around the White King. Combine it with some ideas on the g1-a7 diagonal together with ... O-O-O when ... Rd1 becomes a real option and you have a ready recipe for a disaster for White. By no means do I claim that we are better or even fully equal, but White really has to be careful. }
9. h3
{ This is one example of how disastrous things might turn out for our opponent after only one mistake. }
9... Qh4+
{ Game over. The King will be caught in the net, for example,  10.Kd2  Bb4+  with ... O-O-O to come. }
