8. f4
{ Defending e5 with the pawn is more direct but as usual, it has two major disadvantages:   • It doesn't contribute to development.   • The g1-a7 diagonal has been weakened. }
8... Bg4
{ A very strong move that can be chosen by a process of elimination. We need to castle queenside as fast as possible to prove our compensation. That means that we should develop the Bishop in the first place. The question that remains is: where?   • f5 and h3 don't seem to be the right squares in this specific position.   • On e6, the Bishop would be prone to the f5 ideas in the future and the tension between the Black Queen and the e5-pawn would be disrupted.   • Finally, we play ... Bd7 only in the case of Bb5, so the choice is obvious.   Now, ... Bg4 is not only the kind of move that we play because there is no better alternative. The Bishop is really well placed on g4, covering some squares around the White King. Combine it with some ideas on the g1-a7 diagonal together with ... O-O-O when ... Rd1 becomes a real option and you have a ready recipe for a disaster for White. By no means do I claim that we are better or even fully equal, but White really has to be careful. }
9. Bb5
{ This move would be excellent in the case of @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppp1qppp/2n5/4P3/4QP2/8/PPP3PP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Be6  , but here, it basically leads to a lost position. }
9... O-O-O
{ White can't castle kingside due to ... Qc5+ and taking on c6 loses to ... Rd1+. White can only prolong the game. }
10. Nc3 Nd4 { ... Bf5 is amongst many threats at our disposal. } 11. Bd3 Bf5
{ More complex is  11...Qh4+  , but I like the simplicity of our chosen path. }
12. Qe3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Qh4+
{ Please remember this theme. Usually, this check works well when White doesn't have the Bishop on f1. That means that we can always meet g3 with ... Qh3. }
14. g3 Qh3
{ The problem for White is that even if granted two moves here, he can't castle queenside due to ... Nb3+. Next, we will play ... Qg2 or simply develop the dark-squared Bishop to b4 or c5. }
