{ A very strong move that can be chosen by a process of elimination. We need to castle queenside as fast as possible to prove our compensation. That means that we should develop the Bishop in the first place. The question that remains is: where?   • f5 and h3 don't seem to be the right squares in this specific position.   • On e6, the Bishop would be prone to the f5 ideas in the future and the tension between the Black Queen and the e5-pawn would be disrupted.   • Finally, we play ... Bd7 only in the case of Bb5, so the choice is obvious.   Now, ... Bg4 is not only the kind of move that we play because there is no better alternative. The Bishop is really well placed on g4, covering some squares around the White King. Combine it with some ideas on the g1-a7 diagonal together with ... O-O-O when ... Rd1 becomes a real option and you have a ready recipe for a disaster for White. By no means do I claim that we are better or even fully equal, but White really has to be careful. }
9. Be2 { A decent idea, trying to lure us into a positional trap. } 9... f5
{ What I dislike about  9...Bxe2  is that after  10.Qxe2  f6  White can play  11.O-O  fxe5  12.f5!  O-O-O  13.c3  stopping ... Nd4 when I find it unpleasant to play this position with Black. After  9... f5, a more or less forced line starts. }
10. Qe3
{ White should keep the Queen close to the centre.  10.Qc4?  O-O-O  with ... g5 to come would enable Black to strike hard. The tactical issue is that  11.Bxg4  is no good due to  11. ..Qh4+!   Now you can see why White needs the Queen on e3. }
10... O-O-O 11. Bxg4
{ 11.O-O  Qc5!  would give Black excellent compensation even being a pawn down. Ideas connected with ... g5 should hand over the initiative to us and leave us with an edge. A sample line goes  12.Bxg4  fxg4  13.Nc3  Nd4!  with a strong initiative. }
11... fxg4 { But not  11...Qh4+?!  12.Qf2  . } 12. Nc3 Qh4+ 13. g3
{ 13.Qg3??  Qxg3+  14.hxg3  Nb4  is awful for White.   Better is  13.Qf2?!  , but after  13...Qxf2+  14.Kxf2  Bc5+!  Black is better, especially since  15.Be3??  Rd2+  is unacceptable. Best is @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/ppp3pp/2n5/2b1P3/5Pp1/2N5/PPP2KPP/R1B4R w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Kg3  , but after  15...h5  , Black has superb compensation. }
13... Qh3
{ I'd love to end the line here and say that Black has excellent compensation, but there is one forcing sequence we need to remember. }
14. Bd2
{ If White castles queenside, we will be left with no compensation. Therefore, the following variation has to be played. }
14... Bc5 { Step one! } 15. Qxc5 { 15.Qe4  Bf2+  is very risky. } 15... Rxd2
{ Step two! } 16. Kxd2 Qg2+ 17. Kd3
{ 17.Ne2??  Rd8+  is lethal especially after  18.Kc3  Qf3+  . } 17... Rd8+ 18.
Kc4 b6
{ If not for this move, we would be lost. We attack the Queen and prepare ... Na5+. }
19. Qb5
{ 19.Rhg1?  looks smart but backfires due to  19...Na5+!  20.Qxa5  Qc6+  . }
19... Na5+ { The simplest path to a draw. } 20. Kb4 Rd4+ 21. Ka3 Nc4+ 22. Kb3
Na5+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Petroff 7.dxe5: Rare 8th moves"]
[Black "7.dxe5 Nc6 8.f4 Bg4 #5/6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5
{ In this and the next two chapters, we will check what is considered to be the mainline for White. By taking with the pawn, White keeps the Queens on the board and leaves us with a bit misplaced Queen on e7. Let's also not forget that our opponent is a pawn up! However, there are positives too! The position of our Queen might not be bad at all. The pawn on e5 is under attack and we are one step closer from castling queenside. }
7... Nc6
{ As you can see, our position is extremely logical and intuitive to play. White faces the threat of ... Qxe5, and to get any advantage at all, he has to give the extra pawn back with  8.Nc3  . We will see that approach in chapter 4. In chapter 3 we will cover what is considered by many sources as a refutation of our concept @@StartBracket@@undeservedly!@@EndBracket@@ and in the current chapter, we will see all the alternatives where White tries to defend the pawn at all costs.. }
8. f4
{ Defending e5 with the pawn is more direct but as usual, it has two major disadvantages:   • It doesn't contribute to development.   • The g1-a7 diagonal has been weakened. }
8... Bg4
{ A very strong move that can be chosen by a process of elimination. We need to castle queenside as fast as possible to prove our compensation. That means that we should develop the Bishop in the first place. The question that remains is: where?   • f5 and h3 don't seem to be the right squares in this specific position.   • On e6, the Bishop would be prone to the f5 ideas in the future and the tension between the Black Queen and the e5-pawn would be disrupted.   • Finally, we play ... Bd7 only in the case of Bb5, so the choice is obvious.   Now, ... Bg4 is not only the kind of move that we play because there is no better alternative. The Bishop is really well placed on g4, covering some squares around the White King. Combine it with some ideas on the g1-a7 diagonal together with ... O-O-O when ... Rd1 becomes a real option and you have a ready recipe for a disaster for White. By no means do I claim that we are better or even fully equal, but White really has to be careful. }
9. Nc3
{ In my opinion, this is the most accurate move. White keeps h3 overprotected, making ... Qh4+ checks unattractive, covering d1 and simply developing the piece.   Note that  9.Be3  O-O-O  10.Nc3  Qb4  just transposes to 9. Nc3. }
9... O-O-O
{ The most flexible move. We have ideas such as ... Rd4, ... Nd4 or even ... f5. }
10. Be3
{ Nothing else makes sense. If White moves the light-squared Bishop, we can switch back to the ... Qh4 plan. }
10... Qb4
{ It might look counterintuitive to offer the Queen trade when being a pawn down, but it will be a recurring theme in similar positions. We threaten ... Qxb2 as well as ... Nd4.   I'd love to suggest the more dynamic  10...f5  , but after  11.Qa4  g5  White has the annoying  12.Ba6  . }
11. Qxb4 { The most natural move but harmless. } 11... Nxb4 12. Rc1 Bf5
{ The c2-pawn falls, and Black equalizes. } *

