{ The most flexible move. We have ideas such as ... Rd4, ... Nd4 or even ... f5. }
10. Be3
{ Nothing else makes sense. If White moves the light-squared Bishop, we can switch back to the ... Qh4 plan. }
10... Qb4
{ It might look counterintuitive to offer the Queen trade when being a pawn down, but it will be a recurring theme in similar positions. We threaten ... Qxb2 as well as ... Nd4.   I'd love to suggest the more dynamic  10...f5  , but after  11.Qa4  g5  White has the annoying  12.Ba6  . }
11. Rb1 { White tries to achieve the Queen trade on favourable terms. } 11...
Qxe4
{ We should be OK with that. Even though it looks like we play into White's hands, we will claim that Rb1 was a waste of time and the Knight on e4 is misplaced. }
12. Nxe4 Nb4 { There is only one sensible way of defending c2. } 13. c3 Nd3+
{ 13...Nc2+?  14.Kf2  Nxe3  15.Kxe3  would be a big mistake. We have no initiative and as a result, no compensation. }
14. Bxd3 Rxd3 15. Kf2 { Otherwise ... Bf5 would be strong. } 15... Be7
{ In this case, we should keep the Bishop on g4 for the time being. The reason for that is simple. We will play ... Be7 anyway, play ... Rhd8 anyway, while if White wants to chase our Bishop, he will be forced to make some concessions.   15...Bf5?  16.Ng3  sees White consolidating. }
16. h3 Bf5
{ Only now. The difference is that  17.Ng3??  Bh4!  creates an eternal pin. This line wouldn't work with the white pawn on h2. }
17. Kf3 Rhd8
{ We took over control of the d-file. Next should be ... Be6 followed by ... f5/f6 and ... Bd5 ideas. We have excellent compensation. }
*

[Event "?"]
