1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6
8. Bb5
{ There are a few things I love about this move:   • It is White's most popular move according to all databases but the correspondence one.   • Many sources claim that it gives White a @@StartBracket@@huge@@EndBracket@@ advantage due to one forcing line that we will analyze at the end of this chapter.   • In fact, it gives White no advantage at all, and Black's play is straightforward and easy to understand. }
8... Bd7
{ First things first, as usual, we meet Bb5 with ... Bd7. What is lovely is that we will play a combination of ... O-O-O, ... a6 and ... Nxe5 next and White can do nothing about that. OK, White has a few ways to try to disrupt our play but if you learn a few patterns, you are good to go! }
9. O-O
{ This is a very modest idea, castling into safety and preparing to keep the e5-pawn. }
9... O-O-O { ... Nxe5 is a threat that is very difficult to parry. } 10. Bf4
{ This is one of the worst timings for this idea. It shouldn't sound too bad when I tell you that this is the 2nd most common try for White! What I find amusing is that Black has no less than three promising ways to go forward, but I decided to go for the big fish here! }
10... a6
{ The most ambitious. First,  10...Nxe5??  11.Qxe5!  is embarrassing, when we lose the piece.   Second, I find  10...Qb4  11.Nc3  to be impractical when we have to play  11...Qxb2  to prove our previous move made sense.   Finally, I thought about  10...g5  when we want to set our favourite trap, but after  11.e6!  Qxe6  12.Qxe6  Bxe6  13.Bxg5  Rd5  14.Bf6  Rg8  we 'only' have full compensation. Still, the chance that your rival will meet  10...g5  with  11.Bg3  is quite high so it is possible that  10...g5  might be an interesting alternative way to go.  Since after  10...g5  White has a clear way to equality, with  10...a6  we fight for more! }
11. Ba4 f5
{ The correct order.  11...g5  once again allows  12.e6  with unclear consequences. But why did we play ... a6 first to play ... f5 next? Why not ... f5 right away?! Check the comment to Black's next move for an answer! }
12. Qe3 h6
{ Without ... a6 and Ba4 included, White would have Bxc6 followed by Qxa7 here. The threat of ... g5 basically forces White to go for  13.e6  Qxe6  14.Qxe6  Bxe6  15.Bxc6  bxc6  when we have a perfect version of this pawn structure. Our Bishop pair should dominate the endgame, and we are certainly better. Let me show you one more trick. }
13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Qa7 { This one might look scary. } 14... b6
{ White can win the a6-pawn, but we will steamroll the kingside with ... g5 next. }
