11. Bxc6
{ Taking on c6 is positionally suicidal. White is too undeveloped and his kingside too weak to part with one of the active pieces. }
11... Bxc6
{ White is already in trouble with ...g5 coming:  •  12.Qc4??  or  12.Qe1??  allows  12...Bb5   •  12.Qe2?  f5  with ...g5 next is basically indefensible for White. Our initiative on the kingside is too strong.   Relatively best is  12.Qf5+  when after  12...Bd7  ,  we will continue with either ...g5 or ...Qb4, depending on where White puts the Queen. }
12. Qe3
{ This is a bad and obvious move, but since the punishment is beautiful, let’s see it! }
12... g5 { Out of the blue. } 13. Bxg5 Rg8
{ If the previous move was out of the blue, then this one is out of the yellow and red at the same time. We can safely say it is out of the orange. }
14. Bxe7 Rxg2+ 15. Kh1 Rxf2+ { We take everything. } 16. Kg1 Rg2+ 17. Kh1 Rg3+
{ In fact, any move along the g-file besides ...Rg1 wins. } 18. Rf3
{ Or  18.Qf3  Bxf3+  19.Rxf3  Rd1+  20.Rf1  Rxf1#  . } 18... Rd1+ 19. Qg1
{ You can choose between ... Bxf3 or which Rook to place on g1. I’d go for: }
19... Rgxg1# *

