{ Another try is  10...g5  but here, having the Queen defended, White can even try  11.Bg3  with an edge.   By playing  10...Qb4  , we hit the b2-pawn and prepare to exchange Queens. }
11. Qxb4 { Taking on b4 plays into our hands. } 11... Nxb4
{ The position is so nice for us that recapturing with the Bishop is equally good. }
12. Bxd7+ Rxd7 13. Rc1 Bc5 { We simply develop. } 14. O-O Re8
{ Next is ... Bd4 and ... Nc6 when the e5-pawn can't be defended. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Petroff 8.Bb5 "]
[Black "8.Bb5 Bd7 9.Nc3 O-O-O #3/5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6
8. Bb5
{ There are a few things I love about this move:   • It is White's most popular move according to all databases but the correspondence one.   • Many sources claim that it gives White a @@StartBracket@@huge@@EndBracket@@ advantage due to one forcing line that we will analyze at the end of this chapter.   • In fact, it gives White no advantage at all, and Black's play is straightforward and easy to understand. }
8... Bd7
{ First things first, as usual, we meet Bb5 with ... Bd7. What is lovely is that we will play a combination of ... O-O-O, ... a6 and ... Nxe5 next and White can do nothing about that. OK, White has a few ways to try to disrupt our play but if you learn a few patterns, you are good to go! }
9. Nc3
{ This is the start of the line that was considered a refutation of our concept. Fortunately, the current state of theory claims that it doesn't guarantee White anything. }
9... O-O-O 10. Bf4
{ This is the tabiya of the 8.Bb5 variation. White is ready to dodge two of our main concepts:  •  10...Nxe5??  doesn't work because the b5-Bishop is defended.  •  10...a6?  is wrong due to  11.Be2  and we have zero compensation.  • I'd also add that  10...g5  leads nowhere due to  11.Bg3  f5??  12.exf6!  . }
10... Qb4
{ Another try is  10...g5  but here, having the Queen defended, White can even try  11.Bg3  with an edge.   By playing  10...Qb4  , we hit the b2-pawn and prepare to exchange Queens. }
11. O-O-O { The widely considered 'refutation'. } 11... Qxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe5
{ Again we see this trick. It usually works whenever White has an undefended Bishop. }
13. Bxd7+ Nxd7 14. Ng5
{ I can't recall the concrete source, but I remember seeing an opening book that ended the analysis here by claiming that White is simply much better because f7 can't be defended. One thing we have to agree with - f7 can't be defended. However, what about the unprotected Bishop on f4?! Maybe we can exploit its position in some way?! }
14... Be7
{ The point of the whole line. If not for this variation, the whole concept of starting with 3... Nxe4 would be much less appealing. }
15. Rhe1
{ Before we see what happens if White takes on f7, let me quickly show you the correct response when White finishes development. }
15... Rde8
{ Next is ... h6 when the f7-pawn is taboo as long as we can meet Nxf7 with ... Rhf8. }
