1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6
8. Bb5
{ There are a few things I love about this move:   • It is White's most popular move according to all databases but the correspondence one.   • Many sources claim that it gives White a @@StartBracket@@huge@@EndBracket@@ advantage due to one forcing line that we will analyze at the end of this chapter.   • In fact, it gives White no advantage at all, and Black's play is straightforward and easy to understand. }
8... Bd7
{ First things first, as usual, we meet Bb5 with ... Bd7. What is lovely is that we will play a combination of ... O-O-O, ... a6 and ... Nxe5 next and White can do nothing about that. OK, White has a few ways to try to disrupt our play but if you learn a few patterns, you are good to go! }
9. Nc3
{ This is the start of the line that was considered a refutation of our concept. Fortunately, the current state of theory claims that it doesn't guarantee White anything. }
9... O-O-O 10. Be3
{ Placing the Bishop on e3 is not too common, but we need to know how to react. There are two traps we need to avoid.   10...Qxe5??  11.Bxc6  loses a piece.   10...Nxe5?  11.O-O-O  is suddenly superb for White. }
10... Qb4
{ In general, I'd like to recommend playing in the same style as in the previous lines.   10...a6  11.Ba4  is possible, but I dislike that White can meet  11...Qb4  with  12.e6  forcing  12...Bxe6  13.Bxc6  Qxb2  . Engines scream 'DRAW', but it seems impractical. }
11. O-O-O
{ Note that in this case, we can meet  11.e6  with  11...Bxe6  12.Bxc6  bxc6  , the point being that after  13.Qxc6  , we have  13...Bd5  and since we haven't included ... a6, there is no hanging pawn on a6. }
11... Qxe4 { We should already know that. } 12. Nxe4 Nxe5
{ Just remember the following trick. } 13. Bxd7+ Rxd7
{ 13...Nxd7?  allows  14.Ng5  . } 14. Rxd7 Kxd7
{ The same story.  14...Nxd7  15.Ng5  is sub-optimal.   After  14...Kxd7  ,  15.Rd1+  Kc8  16.Ng5  gives White nothing because we have  16...Be7  and f7 is protected. }
