[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Petroff 8.Nc3"]
[Black "8.Nc3 Qxe5 9.Bf4 Qxe4+ #1/3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6
8. Nc3
{ Giving the pawn back is the only way for White to get an advantage. As a result, we will get a very symmetrical position with an extra tempo for White. Let's start with some statistics:   • In the Mega Database, White chose 8. Nc3 191 times out of 612 games which is an equivalent of around 30%.   • The number increases if we take a look at the 2000+ database. 8. Nc3 has been White's choice in 57 games out of 137, which increases the percentage to around 40%.   • However, what should interest us the most is the Lichess database, with big sample sizes and with information on how people usually react in blitz! After a quick look, we get a realistic number of 2330 games out of 13 917, which equals around 17%.   Long story short, the chance that someone will play 8. Nc3 against you when he is unprepared equals 1/6. If you wonder how things are looking on my level @@StartBracket@@around 2650-2700 blitz, 2700-2800 bullet@@EndBracket@@, I faced 8. Nc3 in 12 games out of 27. OK, let's leave the probability alone. In the previous chapters, I demonstrated that Black has nothing to be afraid of when White tries to hold on to the pawn. That means that the pawn has to be sacrificed. Since playing a pawn down with the Queen on e7 isn't really my deepest dream, let's restore the material equilibrium! }
8... Qxe5 { Now, to get an advantage, White has to take on e5. } 9. Bf4
{ I just want to show you that we can easily counter this 'active' move. Note that tries such as  9.Bb5  are harmless due to the simple  9...Qxe4+  10.Nxe4  Bf5  . Usually, the side that captures the opponent's Queen will benefit from that because the Knight will be unstable in the centre. }
9... Qxe4+ 10. Nxe4
{ It looks quite nice for White, especially when we consider White's temporary lead in development and the hanging c7-pawn. However, we can get a good game with a simple counterattack. }
10... Bf5
{ This is what I've meant when I said that the side with the Knight in the centre will face some issues because the Knight is unstable. Tempting might be  10...Bb4+?  11.c3  Ba5  , but after  12.O-O-O  White is significantly better. }
11. Bd3 O-O-O { Simple. We defend the pawn and safeguard the King. } 12. Nd6+
{ Tempting, but wrong. } 12... Bxd6 13. Bxf5+ Kb8
{ We will play ... Rhe8+ next after most moves but one. } 14. Be3
{ 14.Bxd6  Rhe8+  15.Kd2  Rxd6+  16.Bd3  Nb4  will leave us with a slight edge in the endgame. }
14... Nb4
{ A combination of ... g6 followed by ... f5 or simply ... Nd5 leaves us with a strong initiative. White will be forced to part with one of the Bishops or commit to some serious concessions. }
*

