11. Bg3
{ It is a funny position because it seems that we even might have a lead in development since both sides have only two minor pieces developed and it is Black to move, but things are not so simple:   • White's pieces are much more stable than ours.   • White has a positional threat of Nb5/Ne4. Since we can't prevent it, we will maximize the potential of our position before White manages to get our Bishop.   • Another useful option for White is that he will castle queenside and finish development quickly.   OK, these are the advantages of White's position. I spent some time finding the way to somehow prove that there are also some disadvantages, and I managed to find one - the Bishop on g3 might turn into a target. }
11... h5
{ We use Harry to create some havoc in our opponent's position. With ... h4 being a threat, White has to react. I promise that even if White will miraculously know how to get into the position after 11. Bg3, he will use some time to meet 11... h5. What I find absolutely amazing and heart-warming is that White's most obvious moves here won't give him much. }
12. h3
{ I wouldn't say that this way of meeting ... h4 is bad, but it definitely gives us some trumps on the kingside. }
12... h4
{ Fixing White's pawn structure should be considered a success. We should anticipate that the White King will go to the queenside, which means that the kingside pawns will be a little vulnerable. }
13. Bh2 Bf5 { We might even force the queenside castling. } 14. O-O-O
{ Be careful! Bxe5 followed by Re1 is a threat so we don't have time for ... a6. }
14... O-O-O
{ We are ready to play ... a6 and stop Nb5. That would result in an edge for us even because we have more space on the kingside. }
15. Nb5 { Now or never. } 15... f6
{ This is the recurring theme for this variation. We deal with the fact that White will take the d6-Bishop with the Knight, and we build a barrier on the dark squares. }
16. Nxa7+ { Going for this pawn is harmless. } 16... Kb8 17. Nb5 Bc5
{ White faces issues with the f2-pawn and moving it forward loses instantly to ... Be3+. }
18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Bg1 Re8
{ ... Nf3 is a big threat that is uneasy to parry. Black has excellent compensation. After the most natural  20.Be2  we have  20...Nc6  and again, White faces huge problems with coordination. }
*

