{ This is the recurring theme for this variation. We deal with the fact that White will take the d6-Bishop with the Knight, and we build a barrier on the dark squares. }
16. Nxd6+ { The Bishop has to be taken. } 16... Rxd6
{ We take on d6 with the Rook for purely strategic reasons. Note that we will be left with an isolated pawn on d6 no matter what. If we leave White with both Rooks, the d6-pawn will be a little bit harder to defend. However, if we exchange a pair of Rooks, the pawn will be simply guarded by the King.  Also, I'd like to add that we allow White to weaken our pawn structure with Nxd6 ONLY IN POSITIONS WHERE WE HAVE THE PAWN ON h4. That will allow us to play ... g5 and ... Ke7 in the future. }
17. Rxd6 cxd6 18. Be2 g5
{ Next is ... Kc7 or ... Kd7. It looks like White should have an edge due to the Bishop pair and a better pawn structure, but it is not the case:   • We will place the King on c7 or d7 and develop the Rook to c8.   • The Knight on e5 is a monster   • The Bishop on f5 is also strong and together with the Rook on c8, it can force concessions.   • We can also think about playing ... Kd7-e6 followed by ... a6 and ... b5 to play on the queenside, but I would be a bit careful with this idea.   • On the contrary, White's position looks beautiful, but I have no clue what our rival should be doing. I also doubt if White has any edge at all @@StartBracket@@it is microscopic if it is there@@EndBracket@@. }
