14. Nb5 { Again, without the Black pawn on h4, we shouldn't allow Nxd6. } 14...
Bxb5 { The Knight has to be eliminated. } 15. Bxb5+ Kf8
{ Very important, very strange, and very unstereotypical all at once! Why not the more natural ... Ke7? Our main plan in this position should be to play ... g6 and hide the King on g7 when we coordinate our pieces quite nicely. The Knight on e5 is solid and basically untouchable since whenever White plays f4, the g4-square is permanently weakened @@StartBracket@@thanks ... h5!@@EndBracket@@.   The tactical issue with  15...Kf7  is that after something like  16.c3  g6  , White has  17.Bxe5!  when we can't go for  17...Bxe5?  due to  18.Rd7+  Ke6  19.Rg7  with threats such as Rxg6, Rd1 and Bc4+. We are busted!   That means that we have to recapture with the pawn and after  17...fxe5  18.Bc4+  Kf6  19.Bd5  Rab8  20.Be4  , White dominates the endgame and there is a lot of suffering awaiting us.   So the idea behind  15...Kf8!  is to avoid the Bishop check from c4 and the Rook check from d7. That means that instead of going for ... g6 and ... Kg7, our idea is to play ... g6 followed by ...Rh7-e7, then ... Rd8 and ... Nf7 to exchange the Bishops. Amazingly, White can't stop that. I am serious, remember ... g6, ... Rh7-e7, ... Rd8 and ... Nf7 and life will be good. That's everything you need to know. Let me only show you one more idea. }
16. Rhe1
{ 16.Bxe5  Bxe5  17.Rd7  threatening Bc4 should be met with  17...Re8  planning ... Re7. }
16... g6 17. Bxe5 { Otherwise ... Rh7-e7 etc. } 17... Bxe5 18. Rd7
{ White threatens Bc4. } 18... Rg8
{ Just in time to dodge Bc4. ... Rg7 is next, and we are OK. } *

