{ The only route for an edge. } 9... Nxe5
{ It is this position that offers White an edge. There are two ways to get it - Bf4 or Nb5. After anything else, we can develop the light-squared Bishop and castle queenside. Note that something like  10.Nd5?  is a shot in the dark due to  10...Bd6  and the Knight is misplaced on d5. }
10. Nb5
{ A less popular brother of 10. Bf4. The positions here will be much more symmetrical and the pawn structure will usually be untouched. White banks his play on the c7-weakness, and we need to be precise to get a playable position. }
10... Bb4+
{ With a simple idea of playing ... Ba5 next. White has two ways of dealing with this check. }
11. c3 { I think that blocking with the pawn is inaccurate. } 11... Ba5
{ We are ready to hit the Knight with ... a6 when White's operation would be a time loss. }
12. Bf4 f6
{ Of course, we need to keep the Knight on e5 to make sure c7 won't be hit from too many directions. Let me show you three different ways for White to go forward and how to tackle them. }
13. Bxe5
{ Taking on e5 gives White a structural advantage, but we get the Bishop pair and rather free play. }
13... fxe5
{ Next is ... Be6 and ... a6/c6 followed by ... Bb6, ... Rf8 and castling queenside. Our Bishop pair fully compensates for the weak e-pawn. }
