[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Petroff 8.Nc3"]
[Black "8.Nc3 Qxe5 9.Qxe5+ Nxe5 10.Nb5 Bb4+ #5/9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6
8. Nc3
{ Giving the pawn back is the only way for White to get an advantage. As a result, we will get a very symmetrical position with an extra tempo for White. Let's start with some statistics:   • In the Mega Database, White chose 8. Nc3 191 times out of 612 games which is an equivalent of around 30%.   • The number increases if we take a look at the 2000+ database. 8. Nc3 has been White's choice in 57 games out of 137, which increases the percentage to around 40%.   • However, what should interest us the most is the Lichess database, with big sample sizes and with information on how people usually react in blitz! After a quick look, we get a realistic number of 2330 games out of 13 917, which equals around 17%.   Long story short, the chance that someone will play 8. Nc3 against you when he is unprepared equals 1/6. If you wonder how things are looking on my level @@StartBracket@@around 2650-2700 blitz, 2700-2800 bullet@@EndBracket@@, I faced 8. Nc3 in 12 games out of 27. OK, let's leave the probability alone. In the previous chapters, I demonstrated that Black has nothing to be afraid of when White tries to hold on to the pawn. That means that the pawn has to be sacrificed. Since playing a pawn down with the Queen on e7 isn't really my deepest dream, let's restore the material equilibrium! }
8... Qxe5 { Now, to get an advantage, White has to take on e5. } 9. Qxe5+
{ The only route for an edge. } 9... Nxe5
{ It is this position that offers White an edge. There are two ways to get it - Bf4 or Nb5. After anything else, we can develop the light-squared Bishop and castle queenside. Note that something like  10.Nd5?  is a shot in the dark due to  10...Bd6  and the Knight is misplaced on d5. }
10. Nb5
{ A less popular brother of 10. Bf4. The positions here will be much more symmetrical and the pawn structure will usually be untouched. White banks his play on the c7-weakness, and we need to be precise to get a playable position. }
10... Bb4+
{ With a simple idea of playing ... Ba5 next. White has two ways of dealing with this check. }
11. Bd2 { This is the correct approach. } 11... Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Kd8
{ OK, both Kings are a bit loose, but it is White who has the initiative. If given a move, we would play ... Re8 or ... Bd7 and gradually untangle. White's only advantage in this position is time. If our rival plays too slowly, we will equalize. }
13. f4
{ I understand the desire to win a tempo on our Knight, but it is beneficial to use the Rook to do so. Still, I understand White's reasoning. To develop the Bishop on an active square, the Knight has to be removed from e5. If White plays Re1 @@StartBracket@@the best move@@EndBracket@@, then getting the Rooks to d1 and e1 becomes problematic. }
13... Ng4
{ Unlike in the 13. Re1 variation we will analyze in a second, here, we can play more aggressively. The main idea behind ... Ng4 is to disrupt White's development as much as possible and also to play ... Nf2-e4 combined with ... Re8. White's only hope for an edge is to fight against the ... Nf2 plan, and it can be done only by covering the e4-square in some way. }
14. Bc4 { 14.Re1  Bd7  will lead to the same thing after  15.Bc4  f5  . } 14...
Bd7
{ We simply develop, indirectly defend against Bxf7, and can ponder ideas connected with ... Bxb5 followed by ... c6. Our main plan, however, is to play ... f5 to gain eternal control over e4 and then somehow plant the Knight there. After we play ... f5, we can play ... c6 since we no longer have to worry about Nd6 forking our pawns. }
15. Rae1
{ 15.Rhe1  is the desired move, but it drops the pawn due to  15...Nxh2  . }
15... f5
{ Next is a combination of ... c6 and ... Nf2/Nf6 followed by ... Ne4+. The King will find a perfect position on c7, and then we can develop the Rooks. We are fine. }
