13. Re1
{ This is the move that poses the most problems. I've spent plenty of time @@StartBracket@@I mean Stockfish did@@EndBracket@@ to find the correct setup for Black, and I think I succeeded  (I mean Stockfish did)  . }
13... Nd7
{ I think that we can choose this move by a process of elimination.   •  13...Ng4  worked well in the 13. f4 variation, but here, after the simple  14.Bc4  , the placement of our Knight makes no sense, especially since  14...Nxf2??  15.Rhf1  is unacceptable.   •  13...Ng6  14.h4  with h5 to come is also suboptimal.   • Finally,  13...f6  14.f4  leaves us with the same issue, and the inclusion of f4 and ... f6 certainly helped White.  After  13... Nd7, our setup might look passive, but it is temporary. We want to play ... Nb6 and ... Bd7 next, when we gradually develop our pieces. The f7-pawn will always be defended with ... Rf8 just in case. }
14. Bc4
{ Otherwise, we would play ... Nb6 stopping Bc4 and then play ... Bd7. } 14...
Rf8
{ Since I consider this position to be quite optimistic for White, let's take a look at a few examples. }
15. Re3
{ With a straightforward plan of doubling the Rooks or going for Rd1 followed by Kc1 next. Sometimes the Rook can also play along the 3rd rank. }
15... Nb6
{ ... Bd7 followed by ... c6/a6 is next when we will gradually bring the pieces into the game. White's advantage in a practical game is symbolic. }
