{ With a simple idea of playing ... Ba5 next. White has two ways of dealing with this check. }
11. Bd2 { This is the correct approach. } 11... Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Kd8
{ OK, both Kings are a bit loose, but it is White who has the initiative. If given a move, we would play ... Re8 or ... Bd7 and gradually untangle. White's only advantage in this position is time. If our rival plays too slowly, we will equalize. }
13. Re1
{ This is the move that poses the most problems. I've spent plenty of time @@StartBracket@@I mean Stockfish did@@EndBracket@@ to find the correct setup for Black, and I think I succeeded  (I mean Stockfish did)  . }
13... Nd7 14. h4
{ A proposition of GM Sethuraman. White pushes the h-pawn to grab space on the kingside, ponder going for h5-h6 or even go for the Rook lift via the 3rd rank. }
14... Nc5
{ After spending some time on this position, I decided that this is the most promising plan. Our idea is to play  15.--  a6!  16.Nc3  Re8!  when we will exchange one pair of Rooks and reach equality.  17.Bc4  isn't dangerous thanks to  17...Be6  .   Note that if we play  14...a6?!  immediately, White can play  15.Nc3  and meet  15...Re8?!  with  16.Bc4!   I also thought about  14...Nb6  but then  15.Bd3  with a combination of Re3 and h5-h6 looks quite annoying. We can untangle the queenside but after  15...Bd7  16.h5  c6  17.Nd4  ,  White has both h6 and Nf5 coming which looks sub-optimal, for example,  17...h6  18.Re3  with ideas such as Rf3/Rg3 - avoid this line. }
15. Re5
{ I don't think anything else makes sense.   15.h5  a6  16.Nc3  h6  with ... Re8, ... Be6 or ... Ne6 to come next, we have a decent position. }
15... Nd7
{ And calmly back. We give White the option of repeating moves, but then we make a draw from a slightly inferior position. }
16. Rg5
{ 16.Re3  a6  followed by ... Re8 plays into our hands.  Something like  17.Nc3  Re8  18.Rg3  g6  19.h5  Nf6  20.hxg6  hxg6  21.Bc4  Be6  gives White only a symbolic advantage. }
16... g6
{ We are fully ready to play ...a6/c6, ... Re8 or ... Nf6 next. White has only one way to maintain the initiative. }
17. Bc4
{ 17.h5?!  Nf6!  threatening ... Ne4+ hands over the initiative to us. } 17...
Rf8
{ We can safely end the line here. We will play a combination of ... a6 and ... c6, usually going for both moves followed by ... Kc7. Then we can look for the initiative on the queenside with ... b5. Even though White's position is certainly a shade better, we should be doing fine. }
