1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. f4
{ This way of defending the Knight is much less logical, but it has some venom. The d-pawn will stay in the starting blocks and White might get a dangerous pawn majority if we don't play actively. I consider this line to be a pure pleasure to play with Black, even though White might hope to get a theoretical advantage out of the opening. }
6... dxe5 7. Qxe5
{ As usual, taking with the Queen is harmless, but this time for different reasons. }
7... Be6
{ A strong novelty.  7...Qxe5  8.fxe5  Nc6  is also OK, but after  9.c3  Nxe5  10.d4  with Be3 to come White has a shade of an edge. After my suggested choice, we want to play ... Nc6 as quickly as possible and follow it up with queenside castling. White is already struggling in my opinion. }
8. f5 { First, this doesn't work. } 8... Bxf5 { Pin for a win. } *

