1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. f4
{ This way of defending the Knight is much less logical, but it has some venom. The d-pawn will stay in the starting blocks and White might get a dangerous pawn majority if we don't play actively. I consider this line to be a pure pleasure to play with Black, even though White might hope to get a theoretical advantage out of the opening. }
6... dxe5 7. fxe5 f5
{ 7...f6  will eventually win the pawn back, but even if we do that, we will be left with an isolated pawn on e5. My suggested move is more dynamic.   Note that  7...Nc6?  8.d4  is very poor for us. We need to play more dynamically. }
8. Qf4 { Allowing us to win space for free is risky. } 8... g5 9. Qe3 Nc6
{ There is only one way to defend the pawn. Note that taking on e5 immediately is kind of a threat, but I would say that ... f4! first and only then ... Nxe5/Qxe5 is the way to go. }
10. d4 Be6
{ I like this simple idea a lot. We develop the queenside and prepare ... f4 combined with ... O-O-O next with full pressure on White's position. Castling kingside looks extremely risky for our rival, especially when we have a pawn majority on that side of the board. Our position plays by itself. I just want to show you what might happen if White tries to neglect development and build a big pawn centre. }
11. c4 O-O-O 12. d5 Bxd5 13. cxd5 Rxd5 { It is impossible to survive this. } *

