1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. d4
{ It is tough to believe that any other move than  5.Qxe4  makes any sense. Still, White players choose not to take the Knight from time to time @@StartBracket@@20% of games in total@@EndBracket@@, so even a very short coverage should leave you prepared. }
5... d5
{ I briefly thought about  5...d6  which would transpose into the mainline that we have analyzed in the first chapters of the course, but first, I don't feel fancy granting this option to White, and second, White has the extra option in the form of  6.Nd3  .   So  5...d5  we go. We will analyze a few options for our opponent. }
6. Nd2
{ The key to understanding how to handle such moves is that we should never ease our opponent's development unless it is necessary or we immediately benefit from that. }
6... Nd6
{ Simple. Next is ... Bf5 followed by ... Nd7. If you are into a fianchetto, you might also try ... g6 and ... Bg7.  6...Bf5?  would be a grave error due to  7.g4  .   Note that  6...Nd7  transposes tothis variation, but giving White this option via this move order is a crime. }
