[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. d4
{ It is tough to believe that any other move than  5.Qxe4  makes any sense. Still, White players choose not to take the Knight from time to time @@StartBracket@@20% of games in total@@EndBracket@@, so even a very short coverage should leave you prepared. }
5... d5
{ I briefly thought about  5...d6  which would transpose into the mainline that we have analyzed in the first chapters of the course, but first, I don't feel fancy granting this option to White, and second, White has the extra option in the form of  6.Nd3  .   So  5...d5  we go. We will analyze a few options for our opponent. }
6. c4 { Hitting the centre with the pawn is the most direct plan. } 6... f6
{ In the previous variation, we had a very similar position where this idea didn't work with the colours reversed. However, the extra move c4 only makes matters more difficult for White. }
7. Qh5+ { Amazingly, trying to copy our strategy doesn't work here. } 7... g6
8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. Qxh8 Bf5
{ The key is not to go for the Rook, but to play ... Nc6 and castle queenside next with an enormous lead in development. The move c4 makes matters difficult for White because there are plenty of lines when we can throw the ... Qb4+ check. Another problem is that after ... Nc6, there is no good way to defend the d4-pawn, for example,  10.Be2  Nc6  and what now?! }
10. cxd5 Nd7
{ Again, we don't want to take the Rook. Castling queenside is usually next. }
11. Be2 { Only here do we have to change plans. } 11... Qb4+
{ 11...O-O-O??  12.O-O  sees White consolidating. } 12. Nd2 O-O-O
{ Castling kingside is stopped and the d4-pawn is hanging. We can also increase pressure with ... Re8. White is in deep trouble. }
