[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Bc4
{ Developing the Bishop to c4 is a mistake seen very often on lower levels. I know, hitting f7 is tempting, but it is just a waste of tempo. }
4... d5 5. Qe2 { Not very popular, but it requires precision. } 5... Bc5
{ We would like to take the Bishop, but we should develop the kingside first. Now,  6.O-O  O-O  is excellent for Black, who can play ... Re8 next and White's pieces are really awkwardly placed @@StartBracket@@it seems like White will have to spend a tempo for each of these pieces@@EndBracket@@. }
6. d3 { This is tricky because there is only one route to an advantage. } 6...
Bxf2+ 7. Kf1 Bb6 { We save the Bishop and everything is good. } 8. Bb3 Qe7
{ The final accuracy. We attack the Knight and prepare to castle short, especially since  9.Bxd5  Nf2  wins material. White might try  10.Bxf7+  Kf8  11.Rg1  , but  11...Ng4!  wins on the spot. Trickier is @@StartFEN@@rnb2k1r/ppp1qBpp/1b6/4N3/8/3P4/PPP1QnPP/RNB2K1R w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nc3  planning Nd5  but after  11...Nc6!  , Black is hugely on top. }
*

