[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Petroff: Rare 4th moves"]
[Black "4.d3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. d3
{ Amongst all 4th move alternatives, moving the d-pawn either one or two squares forward is the only way to keep the initiative. }
4... Nf6 { We can basically premove ... d5 next. } 5. d4
{ 5.Be2  d5  will soon force White to play d4 after we go for ...O-O ...Bd6 and ...Nbd7, so it makes sense to play this move immediately and decide the light-squared Bishop's future later. }
5... d5
{ Note that  5...d6  6.Nf3  d5  is a direct transposition to the Exchange French - not welcome here @@StartBracket@@or anywhere@@EndBracket@@. After  5...d5  , we should just play ... Bd6 and ... O-O followed by some Knight move to target the e5-Knight. }
6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O
{ The only question that remains is how do we evaluate the e5-Knight's presence. Is it strong or might it turn into a target? The plan that I would like to recommend should indicate that the 2nd option might be true! A rule of thumb in this position is straightforward:   • You should play ... c5 followed by ... Nc6 against most moves from White.   • You switch to ... Nc6 right away only in the lines where White covers e5 with the piece, meaning Bf4 or Re1. The reason for that is that We shouldn't let White meet ... c5 with dxc5, when we are left with an isolated pawn on d5.   The only exception is line  8.f4  c5!  when we don't care about structural weaknesses when White has permanently weakened the kingside. }
*

