1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. d4
{ I think that this is the most promising alternative to  4.Qe2  . White puts the d-pawn where it belongs right away. }
4... d5
{ We should do exactly the same. The d-pawn will land on d5 sooner or later and it is questionable if the Knight's presence on e5 is bad or not. Therefore, we ignore it and grab a fair share of space. It also fits our strategy of playing symmetrically, only to break the symmetry to our benefit later. }
5. Bd3 Nd7
{ First things first, this is the direct transposition to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.d4  Nxe4  4.Bd3  d5  5.Nxe5  Nd7  variation which will be the main topic of the next two chapters. }
