{ 11.Qg3?!  h4  only helps us. } 11... Qe7 12. f4
{ Otherwise, we get the pawn back. } 12... Be6
{ I thought about  12...Qe6  , but after  13.Qxe6+  fxe6  14.Kf2  g5  15.Nc3  Bc5+  16.Be3  Bxe3+  17.Kxe3  gxf4+  18.Kxf4  Bxg2  19.Rhg1  , White should be able to claim equality. The point of  12... Be6 is not only to attack the Queen but to play ... Qb4 next. }
13. Qf3 { Allowing us to execute our plan is risky. } 13... Qb4+ 14. c3
{ 14.Nc3  O-O-O  also gives us more than enough compensation. } 14... Qb6
{ White has trouble hiding the King and completing development. We can simply castle queenside while Be3 is impossible due to ... Qxb2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Petroff 3.d4 without 6.Nxd7"]
[Black "3.d4 without 6.Nxd7: 5.Nxe5 Nd7 6.Qe2 Nxe5 #3/3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ This central strike is the 2nd big mainline in the Petroff. White ignores our e5-pawn for the time being and strikes at the centre, hoping that his extra tempo will give him either the advantage or the initiative. }
3... Nxe4
{ I think that allowing  3...exd4  4.e5!  is not something we have to agree on. Taking on e4 is much simpler, especially since we use this move against  3. Nxe5 as well, and some transpositional options are possible. }
4. Bd3
{ This is the big mainline of the 3. d4 Nxe4 system. White wins a tempo by attacking the Knight, and will decide how to recapture on e5 later. }
4... d5
{ A way to surprise your opponent is  4...Nc6!?  when after  5.Bxe4  d5  we will win the piece back with a good position. Unfortunately, I didn't find a satisfactory solution to  4...Nc6  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  Nc5  7.Bc4  which looks pleasantly better for White. }
5. Nxe5
{ 5.dxe5  Nc5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  d5  5.Bd3  Nc5  variation. }
5... Nd7
{ The only move not to fall into some trouble. I dislike  5...Bd6  due to  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  when  7...c6  8.Nc3  gives White a very strong initiative.  5... Nd7 is simpler and better. }
6. Qe2
{ I don't think that putting the Queen on e2 is a good move, but it requires some precision. }
6... Nxe5
{ Surprisingly,  6...Qe7?!  runs into  7.Nxf7!  Qxf7  8.f3  while  7...Kxf7?!  8.Qh5+  is extremely risky for Black. }
7. Bxe4
{ 7.dxe5?!  Nc5!  is simply better for Black, when the Bishop pair should tell in the future. }
7... dxe4 8. Qxe4 { 8.dxe5?!  Qd4!  isn't what White wants. } 8... Be6
{ A strong pawn sacrifice. White has two ways to take the Knight. } 9. dxe5 Bd5
{ We start targetting the light squares. } 10. Qg4 h5 11. Qh3
{ 11.Qg3?!  h4  only helps us. } 11... Qe7 12. f4
{ Otherwise, we get the pawn back. } 12... Be6
{ I thought about  12...Qe6  , but after  13.Qxe6+  fxe6  14.Kf2  g5  15.Nc3  Bc5+  16.Be3  Bxe3+  17.Kxe3  gxf4+  18.Kxf4  Bxg2  19.Rhg1  , White should be able to claim equality. The point of  12... Be6 is not only to attack the Queen but to play ... Qb4 next. }
13. Qc3 { White stops ... Qb4 and plans to castle short. } 13... O-O-O
{ The simplest. I also thought about  13...Qh4+  14.Qg3  Qxg3+  15.hxg3  Bc5  , but if I have a choice to be a pawn down with Queens on the board or without them, I prefer the first option. }
14. O-O Bf5
{ Next is ... Rh6 when our Rook will go to c6 or g6 next. Black has superb compensation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Petroff 3.d4 without 6.Nxd7"]
[Black "3.d4 without 6.Nxd7: 5.Nxe5 Nd7 6.Nc3 Bb4 #1/6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ This central strike is the 2nd big mainline in the Petroff. White ignores our e5-pawn for the time being and strikes at the centre, hoping that his extra tempo will give him either the advantage or the initiative. }
3... Nxe4
{ I think that allowing  3...exd4  4.e5!  is not something we have to agree on. Taking on e4 is much simpler, especially since we use this move against  3. Nxe5 as well, and some transpositional options are possible. }
4. Bd3
{ This is the big mainline of the 3. d4 Nxe4 system. White wins a tempo by attacking the Knight, and will decide how to recapture on e5 later. }
4... d5
{ A way to surprise your opponent is  4...Nc6!?  when after  5.Bxe4  d5  we will win the piece back with a good position. Unfortunately, I didn't find a satisfactory solution to  4...Nc6  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  Nc5  7.Bc4  which looks pleasantly better for White. }
5. Nxe5
{ 5.dxe5  Nc5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  d5  5.Bd3  Nc5  variation. }
5... Nd7
{ The only move not to fall into some trouble. I dislike  5...Bd6  due to  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  when  7...c6  8.Nc3  gives White a very strong initiative.  5... Nd7 is simpler and better. }
6. Nc3
{ This active option is the final alternative to 6. Nxd7 which is the mainline. White simply attacks the Knight and speeds up his development. The good news is that we have a relatively forcing option that ends up in a relatively balanced position. }
6... Bb4
{ We create an annoying pin and White has only one way to avoid problems. Note that  6...Nxe5  7.dxe5  Bb4  will eventually lead to the same thing, but starting with  6...Bb4  reduces White's options to the minimum. }
7. O-O Nxe5
{ A mandatory inclusion.  7...Nxc3?!  8.Qh5!  gives White an edge. } 8. dxe5
Nxc3
{ We have to grab the pawn. Otherwise, White would enjoy a significant edge without even giving up material. }
9. bxc3 Bxc3
{ White can either remove the Rook from attack or stop us from castling. } 10.
Ba3
{ I don't trust this approach. White might get decent compensation, but Black will be able to keep the extra exchange and eventually castle short. }
10... Bxa1 { We take everything. } 11. Qxa1 Be6
{ A very important move, stopping all e6 options from White.   White controls the dark squares, but it is only a temporary thing. Our plan should go as follows: We start with ... a6 to cover the b5-square, and then we continue with ... b6 and ... c5.   It is necessary to start with ...a6 because the immediate  12.--  b6  allows  13.Bb5+  Bd7  14.e6!  with a crushing attack.  Another idea for Black is to prepare ... c5 with ... Rc8, but once again, watch out for the Bb5+ ideas. I think that White's best chance is to hit the b7-pawn either with the Rook or the Queen.   Before I show you those,  12.f4?  g6  leads nowhere and only helps Black because it weakens the King, and in case of some Qb2 lines, we have an additional option of playing ... c6, not fearing Qxb7 due to ... Qb6 check.. }
12. Rb1 { The most obvious plan. } 12... a6
{ I think that sacrificing the b7-pawn is the best way forward. It also fits our strategy of preparing ... b6 and ... c5. }
13. Rxb7 Qc8
{ We will play ... c5 and ... O-O next. White still has to prove compensation. }
*

