{ A way to surprise your opponent is  4...Nc6!?  when after  5.Bxe4  d5  we will win the piece back with a good position. Unfortunately, I didn't find a satisfactory solution to  4...Nc6  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  Nc5  7.Bc4  which looks pleasantly better for White. }
5. Nxe5
{ 5.dxe5  Nc5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  d5  5.Bd3  Nc5  variation. }
5... Nd7
{ The only move not to fall into some trouble. I dislike  5...Bd6  due to  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  when  7...c6  8.Nc3  gives White a very strong initiative.  5... Nd7 is simpler and better. }
6. Nc3
{ This active option is the final alternative to 6. Nxd7 which is the mainline. White simply attacks the Knight and speeds up his development. The good news is that we have a relatively forcing option that ends up in a relatively balanced position. }
6... Bb4
{ We create an annoying pin and White has only one way to avoid problems. Note that  6...Nxe5  7.dxe5  Bb4  will eventually lead to the same thing, but starting with  6...Bb4  reduces White's options to the minimum. }
7. O-O Nxe5
{ A mandatory inclusion.  7...Nxc3?!  8.Qh5!  gives White an edge. } 8. dxe5
Nxc3
{ We have to grab the pawn. Otherwise, White would enjoy a significant edge without even giving up material. }
9. bxc3 Bxc3
{ White can either remove the Rook from attack or stop us from castling. } 10.
Rb1 { This is more popular, but we can get a good position by simple means. }
10... O-O 11. Bxh7+ { What else?! } 11... Kxh7 12. Qd3+ Kg8 13. Qxc3 a5
{ I like this plan. In the opposite-coloured Bishop middlegames, it is most of the time useful to put the pawns on the colours of our rival's Bishop. Not only do we control the b4-square and prevent some Rb4 lifts to the kingside, but we also prepare to play ... Ra6 next @@StartBracket@@shoutout to all the people who own my Budapest course!@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Qg3
{ Before doing anything else, White decides to hit us on the dark squares. }
14... Ra6
{ A strong move, stopping Bh6 and preparing ... Rc6 or ... Rg6. Don't forget that White has a bit weaker pawn structure, especially that a2 and c2 are weak. }
15. Bg5 { There is only one way to parry both Bxd8 and Bf6. } 15... Qd7
{ Planning to meet  15.Bf6?  with  15...Qg4!  We can continue with ... Rc6 or ... Rg6 combined with ... Qf5 next. }
16. f4 Qf5
{ It is important to stop f5 first. Only now do we want to continue with ... Rg6 or ... Rc6. Black has excellent chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Petroff 3.d4 with 6.Nxd7"]
[Black "3.d4 with 6.Nxd7: 6...Bxd7 7.Nd2 Nxd2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ This central strike is the 2nd big mainline in the Petroff. White ignores our e5-pawn for the time being and strikes at the centre, hoping that his extra tempo will give him either the advantage or the initiative. }
3... Nxe4
{ I think that allowing  3...exd4  4.e5!  is not something we have to agree on. Taking on e4 is much simpler, especially since we use this move against  3. Nxe5 as well, and some transpositional options are possible. }
4. Bd3
{ This is the big mainline of the 3. d4 Nxe4 system. White wins a tempo by attacking the Knight and will decide how to recapture on e5 later. }
4... d5
{ A way to surprise your opponent is  4...Nc6!?  when after  5.Bxe4  d5  we will win the piece back with a good position. Unfortunately, I didn't find a satisfactory solution to  4...Nc6  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  Nc5  7.Bc4  looks pleasantly better for White. }
5. Nxe5
{ 5.dxe5  Nc5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  d5  5.Bd3  Nc5  variation. }
5... Nd7
{ The only move not to fall into some trouble. I dislike  5...Bd6  due to  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  when  7...c6  8.Nc3  gives White a very strong initiative.  5... Nd7 is simpler and better. }
6. Nxd7
{ After a few twists and turns, we arrive at the variation that is considered to be the mainline of 3. d4. White exchanges the loose Knight on e5 and will try to prove that Black's Knight on e4 is a liability. }
6... Bxd7 7. Nd2 { This is as unambitious as it can get. } 7... Nxd2
{ 7...f5  is a way to muddy the waters a little, but I personally hate to give up control over the e5-square for eternity like this. }
8. Bxd2 Qe7+
{ It is crucial to throw this check. Nepomniachtchi didn't do it in his match against Carlsen, and he fell into some trouble after  8...Bd6  9.O-O  when castling kingside is suboptimal due to Qh5. }
9. Be3 { 9.Qe2  O-O-O  is completely equal. } 9... Qb4+ 10. Qd2
{ 10.c3  Qxb2  followed by ... Bd6 and ... O-O gives White hopes for equality, but not more than that. }
10... Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 Bd6 { We will castle short and play ... Rfe8. Equality. }
*

