{ After a few twists and turns, we arrive at the variation that is considered to be the mainline of 3. d4. White exchanges the loose Knight on e5 and will try to prove that Black's Knight on e4 is a liability. }
6... Bxd7 7. O-O
{ This is what you will see in over 80% of games that feature 6. Nxd7. White simply castles and will decide on his setup next. }
7... Bd6
{ White has all kinds of plans here - Nc3, Nd2, Re1, c4 or even Qh5. All of them have a different flavour, so let's quickly take a look at them! }
8. Qh5
{ If White wants to go for material gains, this is the way to do it. The d5-pawn is hanging and we are not in time to defend it. One example is  8...c6?!  9.Bxe4  dxe4  10.Nc3  and e4 should fall. }
8... O-O
{ If we have to give up a pawn, let's speed up our development and sacrifice it right away! }
9. Qxd5 Bc6
{ As you can see, White is forced to waste some more time with the Queen @@StartBracket@@and more to come!@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Qh5 { 10.Qf5  g6  is the same - the Queen will go to h3 anyway. } 10... g6
11. Qh6 { Risky. } 11... Re8
{ We will kick the Queen from the kingside by playing ... Bf8 next. As a result, there will be no pieces defending the White King! }
12. Be3 Bf8 13. Qh3
{ 13.Qf4  Bd6  14.Qh6  Bf8  should end with perpetual. or you can try to be more ambitious with  13...h5!? }
13... h5
{ We threaten ... Bd7 followed by ... Bg4 and ... Bd6. The Queen is in trouble and so is our rival. }
