{ A way to surprise your opponent is  4...Nc6!?  when after  5.Bxe4  d5  we will win the piece back with a good position. Unfortunately, I didn't find a satisfactory solution to  4...Nc6  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  Nc5  7.Bc4  looks pleasantly better for White. }
5. Nxe5
{ 5.dxe5  Nc5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  d5  5.Bd3  Nc5  variation. }
5... Nd7
{ The only move not to fall into some trouble. I dislike  5...Bd6  due to  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  when  7...c6  8.Nc3  gives White a very strong initiative.  5... Nd7 is simpler and better. }
6. Nxd7
{ After a few twists and turns, we arrive at the variation that is considered to be the mainline of 3. d4. White exchanges the loose Knight on e5 and will try to prove that Black's Knight on e4 is a liability. }
6... Bxd7 7. O-O
{ This is what you will see in over 80% of games that feature 6. Nxd7. White simply castles and will decide on his setup next. }
7... Bd6
{ White has all kinds of plans here - Nc3, Nd2, Re1, c4 or even Qh5. All of them have a different flavour, so let's quickly take a look at them! }
8. c4
{ This is by far the most common move, but I decided to analyze it first @@StartBracket@@before 8. Nc3@@EndBracket@@ because I think that covering it is easier. Also,  8.Nc3  is a stronger move, so that's why the order is as it is! OK,  8.c4  undermines the Knight, but we can play as dynamically as possible! }
8... O-O
{ Black's choice in less than 10% of games! Almost everyone plays  8...c6?!  allowing  9.cxd5  cxd5  10.Nc3  with an annoying pressure towards our centre. We shouldn't let White combine c4 and Nc3 so easily!   Now, since  8...O-O!  9.Nc3?!  allows  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  dxc4  , when White will be left with three pawn islands, we can hope for an edge. The fact that we castled instead of wasting time with the c-pawn is crucial.  That's why White has to either take on d5 or push the pawn. }
9. cxd5 f5
{ The most dynamic option, keeping the Rook on f8 and preparing ... Qh4. } 10.
Nc3 Qf6
{ Only this move secures full equality. We will use the trick connected with meeting a double capture on e4 with ... Bxh2+. }
11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxh2+
{ Normally I would probably just mention this variation in the text but I think that it is worth adding it since  12...Qh4  looks tempting, but White has  13.f4! }
13. Kxh2 Qh4+ 14. Kg1 Qxe4 15. Qb3
{ Only this move requires a precise reaction. } 15... Rf5
{ A very strong concept. We want to take on d5 next while we also preserve the options of building up on the kingside with ... Raf8. Note that White can't benefit from d6+ as long as we can meet it with ... Be6. }
*

