14. c4
{ This pawn break is the main plan for White. Our rival threatens cxd5 followed by Qf3 when we experience huge issues with d5. }
14... Be8 15. Qh3
{ A very dangerous move that I initially missed, but during the process of double-checking things I realized that MVL chose this idea against Gelfand in their game from the 2009 World Cup. }
15... dxc4
{ Now, if White takes on c4, the game will resemble what we have seen in the previous line, and what we will see in the upcoming ones. }
16. Bxf5
{ This one is dangerous. White attacks the h7-pawn and there are two obvious ways of dealing with it, but only one is correct. }
16... h6
{ This is a necessary move.   Boris chose  16...g6?!  but after  17.Bg4  ,  White will play Bh6, exploiting Black's weaknesses.  The best chance is to play  17...Bf7  , but after  18.g3  ,  White has a much better position. A combination of Re3, f4 and Bh6 is coming next.   After  16...h6  ,  Black defends against mate and if White moves the dark-squared Bishop, ... Bxh2+ will be played. }
17. Be6+ { This is the only line that requires different handling. } 17... Bf7
18. Bxh6
{ Only this way.  18.Bxf7+?  Qxf7  19.Be3  Qd5  leads to a huge advantage for Black. ... Rae8 and ... b5 are next. }
18... gxh6 19. Qxh6
{ The position requires a lot of precision, but fortunately, there is basically one single line we need to know. }
19... Bxh2+ { This is a mandatory inclusion. } 20. Kh1
{ Meeting  20.Qxh2  is simple.  20...Qxh2+  21.Kxh2  Bxe6  22.Rxe6  Rxf2  23.Rxc6  Rxc2  leads to a series of exchanges. White can double the Rooks on the 7th rank, but the material is too reduced to create anything. }
20... Qf4
{ There is also  20...Bf4  ,  but it is more complex. The text move is simple, especially that if White takes on h2, it transposes to the previous comment. In general, we will force the exchange of Queens. }
21. Bxf7+ Rxf7 { 21...Qxf7??  22.Re6  is game over. } 22. Qg6+
{ The only move to maintain balance. } 22... Kf8
{ The simplest.   22...Rg7?!  23.Re8+  Rxe8  24.Qxe8+  Kh7  25.Qh5+  and White ends up a pawn up.   22...Kh8  is possible, but allows some annoying Rook lifts.  With 22... Kf8, we threaten to play ... Rf6 and ... Rh6 next. }
23. Re4 Qf6 { White can no longer avoid the exchange of Queens. } 24. Qxf6 Rxf6
25. Kxh2 Rxf2
{ It is tough to imagine any other result other than a draw. Just remember one trick. }
26. Kg3 Rf6 { 26...Rxc2??  27.Rf1+  leads to mate. } *

