11. Re1
{ The most common plan, keeping all the options open and developing the Rook where it belongs anyway. }
11... c6
{ We should play flexibly as well. Now is the time when White has to commit to something, especially since we have the idea of ... b5 hanging in the air. We don't really want to rush with it, but when we play ... b5, White won't be able to play c4 ever, and both c-pawns will be fixed. }
12. Bg5
{ Almost exclusively played. It also makes the most sense, so we look only at this idea. Note that in this specific order,  12.Rb1  is wrong due to  12...b5!  instead of ... b6. }
12... Qc7
{ White has two promising plans at his disposal - either strike with the c-pawn or transfer the Rook to the kingside/double the Rooks on the e-file. }
13. Re3 { White threatens Rh3 and plans Rae1. } 13... Rf7
{ The Rook covers the 7th rank and we are ready to meet Rh3 with ... g6. } 14.
Rae1
{ After  14.c4  , which has been a choice in a few correspondence games only, we don't have the usual ... Be8 followed by ... dxc4, but we have  14...c5!  which works very well in this specific setup. After  15.cxd5  , strong is  15...c4  followed by ... Raf8 and an initiative on the kingside. }
14... b5
{ White has more active pieces, but we have a nice grip on the queenside. Next is ... Raf8 and ... a5-a4. I can't see how can White improve his position. }
