{ In the final chapter devoted to the Petroff, we will take a look at all major sidelines on move three. Starting from the next chapter,  where we analyze  3.Nc3  , we will switch our attention to all tries from White that don't lead to the Petroff.  We start by covering one of the least ambitious options for White. It is probably still more aggressive than doing it after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d3  , when only real cowards can play like this, for example, Plichta - Khamidov 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@, 1st Irena Warakomska Memorial 2017. }
3... d5
{ My philosophy of targetting the sidelines is to choose a decent variation that should immediately surprise your opponent. The mainline goes  3...Nc6  when we will play ... d5 next, but when someone plays d3, he usually plans to continue with g3, Bg2 and so on. }
4. exd5 { Taking on d5 is critical. } 4... Qxd5
{ What I always strive for in the first moves of the game @@StartBracket@@especially in faster time controls@@EndBracket@@ is some kind of imbalance. In this case, we expose our Queen, but we grab space and have a lead in development. }
5. Nc3 { This is by far the most natural and the most popular move. } 5... Bb4
{ The point of our previous play. We pin the Knight and are ready to part with the Bishop to weaken our opponent's pawn structure. }
