1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Qe2
{ I am certain there are better ways of defending the e4-pawn. } 3... Bc5
{ There is nothing wrong with  3...Nc6  either, but then, White will get a position that resembles the Philidor or the King's Indian Attack. After  3...Bc5  , if White doesn't grab the pawn, we will play a combination of ... O-O and ... d5 when the centre will be opened for our pieces. }
4. Nxe5 O-O
{ White's position is already critical. ... Re8 and ... d5 are coming. There is only one way not to fall into immediate trouble. }
5. c3
{ Two examples of what other moves might cause:   5.Nd3?  Bb6  6.Nc3  d5  7.e5  Nc6  and White can't even finish development.   5.d3?  Re8  6.Nf3  d5  is also horrible. }
5... Re8 6. d4 Bf8
{ We will play ... d5 or ... c5 next, targetting White's centre. There are also ideas connected with ... d6 and ... Nxe4. }
