1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bc4
{ The Reversed Stafford Gambit which normally arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nxe5  Nc6  . Heaven for players who like to play for tricks only, no matter what the objective strength of the move is. A Mekka for guys who don't care about the result of the game, but they feel the sadistic need to see their rival sweating for at least a few moves. I promise - if Elvis had played chess, then if he'd choose 3. Bc4, there would be no city named Memphis - Stafford it would be. On a serious note, this is a dangerous gambit if you don't know what to do against it. }
3... Nxe4
{ If you are into the safety-first approach, then  3...d5  4.exd5  e4  might be for you. However, the best way to refute this nonsense is to accept it. Before I show you the main ideas behind White's plan, I want to quickly mention two transpositions.   • @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2B1n3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nxe5  d5  has been analyzed here @@StartBracket@@#1,  #2,  #3 @@EndBracket@@.   • @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2B1n3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qe2  d5  5.Nxe5  Bc5  has been analyzed here. }
4. Nc3
{ The real gambit. White speeds up the development and hopes for tricks. } 4...
Nxc3
{ 4...Nf6  5.Nxe5  d5  would be a safe way forward.   Similar would be  4...Nc6  transposing to this line of the Four Knights chapter. However, I see no reason not to go for it and refute the gambit. }
5. dxc3
{ This is the first critical moment. White's hope is to lure us into playing  5...d6??  when after  6.Ng5  or  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Bxf7+  we lose the game. }
5... f6
{ Again, a way to bail out to an equal position is  5...c6  6.Nxe5  d5  .   Still, I believe in  5...f6  , and I promise it is worth spending a few trainable lines to get a big advantage. Our primary idea is to build a powerful centre continuing with ... c6 and ... d5. However, White's two main ideas fight against this plan, so I rather leave it up to you more as a fun fact and as a guideline on what White should find against. Since  6.Nxe5  doesn't work to both  6...Qe7  and  6...fxe5  7.Qh5+  g6  8.Qxe5  Qe7  pinning the Queen, let's see more serious stuff @@StartBracket@@if we can ever get serious about this gambit@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nh4 { White creates the threat of Qh5+. } 6... g6
{ The only way to parry it successfully. } 7. f4
{ As you can see, play here is very fast compared to the other lines. } 7...
Qe7
{ This is the correct way of defending against f5. We also create the threat of ... exf4 and stop White from castling kingside due to ... Qc5+. }
8. f5 Qg7 { The point. } 9. O-O
{ This is too slow. We can build up the c6-d5 pawn structure, but first, we need to strengthen the centre. }
9... Nc6
{ Next is ... Ne7 followed by either ... c6 and ... d5, or just ... d6. Black consolidates. }
