1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet  3.Nc3  constantly, even by the players who after 2...Nc6 wouldn't even think about playing  3.Nc3  . The reason is simple - people usually don't like playing against the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence. Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  .  OK, so with  3... Nc6 we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian or my biggest fear - the mainline Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. In this chapter, we will devote our attention to the sidelines on move four. }
4. Bc4 { This is known to be inaccurate for I don't know, 500 years?! } 4...
Nxe4
{ One very common pattern in this course is that not only don't we let our rival transpose to any of his beloved openings like Italian or Scotch, but we also don't let him get the positions that resemble them structurally. For example, if we don't take on e4 here, White can play d3 and the positions will get a lot of Italian taste. Myself being a practitioner of pineapple on pizza, I am not sure I am allowed to talk about any Italian flavours, so we omit these options totally. }
5. Bxf7+
{ White often goes for this, hoping that the King will be misplaced. It won't.   Also wrong is  5.O-O?  Nxc3  6.dxc3  and here, I like  6...h6  ,  stopping any Ng5/Bg5 ideas and preparing to play ... d6 next. White has no compensation. }
5... Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 { We will push the e-pawn after all moves but one. } 7.
Neg5+ Kg8
{ ... h6 is next and the placement of White's Knights is already very awkward. Our King is very safe on g8 and nothing compensates for White's loss of time. }
