{ 8.d4  liquidates the centre after  8...exd4  and after  9.O-O  O-O  10.Bg5  , I recommend keeping the pawn structure intact and playing  10...Qd7  . }
8... O-O 9. d3
{ 9.d4?  fails to  9...Nxd4!  10.Nxd4  exd4  and  11.Qxd4??  Bxh2+  is curtains. }
9... Bg4 { Next is ... f5 with an attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 3.Nc3 Four Knights: Rare 4th moves"]
[Black "4.g3 d5 #1/3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet  3.Nc3  constantly, even by the players who after 2...Nc6 wouldn't even think about playing  3.Nc3  . The reason is simple - people usually don't like playing against the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence. Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  .  OK, so with  3... Nc6 we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian or my biggest fear - the mainline Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. In this chapter, we will devote our attention to the sidelines on move four. }
4. g3 { The Glek Variation. White simply wants to get a game. } 4... d5
{ If you are OK with the Italian type of positions, you might try  4...Bc5  , but I prefer the central strike. }
5. exd5 Nxd5
{ Even the Reversed Belgrade Gambit  5...Nd4  is not so bad here. Still, the text is simpler and stronger. }
6. Bg2
{ White threatens Nxe5 or some O-O followed by Nxd5 and Re1 ideas, so we should release the tension. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6
{ Simple. We overprotect e5 and don't mind White playing d4 at any point. } 8.
O-O O-O
{ A plan that we will use constantly is ... h6 followed by developing the light-squared Bishop. It is necessary to play ... h6 after White touches the d-pawn to stop any Bg5/Ng5 nonsense. }
9. d4 h6 { We stop Bg5/Ng5 and prepare to play ... Qf6 next. } 10. Re1 Qf6
{ Again, keeping the tension. We shouldn't worry about dxe5 since White will be left with two weak pawns on the c-file. We want to continue with ... Re8 and ... Bf5/Bg4. ... Rb8 is often a useful move as well to defend the b7-pawn in advance and step out from the h1-a8 diagonal. }
*

