[White "10) 3.Nc3 Four Knights: Rare 4th moves"]
[Black "4.a3 d5 #1/4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet  3.Nc3  constantly, even by the players who after 2...Nc6 wouldn't even think about playing  3.Nc3  . The reason is simple - people usually don't like playing against the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence. Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  .  OK, so with  3... Nc6 we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian or my biggest fear - the mainline Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. In this chapter, we will devote our attention to the sidelines on move four. }
4. a3
{ As stupid as it looks, this move is very sneaky. If we don't strike in the centre, White will use an extra tempo to play d4 under better circumstances - we won't have ... Bb4. }
4... d5 { We accept the challenge. } 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5
{ What we have on the board is the Reversed Scotch Four Knights with the extra a3 for White. I doubt it is useful, though. }
6... Nxc3
{ We need to exchange the Knights to be able to put the Bishop on d6. } 7. bxc3
Bd6 8. d4 { 8.O-O  O-O  will soon transpose. } 8... exd4 9. Qe2+
{ White sometimes throws this 'disruptive' check, but it only helps Black in my opinion. We will have a better pawn structure, so the endgames should be excellent. }
9... Qe7 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. cxd4 Rd8
{ An important move, developing the Rook and clearing the route for the King. ... Kf8 can be played if necessary. Note that White should never take on c6 because it will involve suffering on the light squares for eternity. We have fewer pawn islands and can count on an edge. }
*

