[White "10) 3.Nc3 Four Knights: Rare 4th moves"]
[Black "4.a3 d5 #3/4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet  3.Nc3  constantly, even by the players who after 2...Nc6 wouldn't even think about playing  3.Nc3  . The reason is simple - people usually don't like playing against the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence. Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  .  OK, so with  3... Nc6 we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian or my biggest fear - the mainline Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. In this chapter, we will devote our attention to the sidelines on move four. }
4. a3
{ As stupid as it looks, this move is very sneaky. If we don't strike in the centre, White will use an extra tempo to play d4 under better circumstances - we won't have ... Bb4. }
4... d5 { We accept the challenge. } 5. Bb5
{ If someone plays 4. a3,  this is most probably the follow-up he will go for. Since Nxe5 is threatened, we have to react. }
5... Nxe4
{ As tempting as  5...d4  might look, after  6.Ne2  the Knight will be transferred to g3, and White will get a very good position after d3, O-O, and so on. I myself dislike playing against this pawn structure, and since in this course we virtually never get pawn structures with a closed centre, we should open it instead! }
6. Nxe5 Qf6
{ This is another case where I deliberately go for the theoretically secondary move just to ensure your peace and joy.  6...Qg5  7.Nxc6  Qxg2  leads to a mess that is advantageous for Black if you know what to do, but in faster time controls, I would go for  6...Qf6  .  We attack the Knight, we threaten mate, we defend the c6-Knight - what more do we expect from one move?! }
7. Nf3
{ 7.Nd3?  misplaces the Knight and after  7...Bd6  with ... O-O to come, Black is clearly in the driver's seat. White can't develop the queenside easily. Note that  8.Nxd5?  Qh4  with ... O-O to come leads to a very strong attack for Black. The further point is that  9.g3??  Nxg3  10.fxg3  Bxg3+  is game over. }
7... Be6
{ Next is ... Bd6 when we will choose the side for castling later @@StartBracket@@short in most cases@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Qe2
{ 8.O-O  is too cooperative when after  8...Bd6  9.Re1  O-O!  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Rxe4  Bd5  we get an excellent Marshall-like compensation. }
8... Bd6
{ This is the reason why I love the 6... Qf6 line. We give up the pawn for immediate compensation. }
9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Qxe4 O-O 11. d3
{ 11.O-O  Bf5  is too risky. White not only has to worry about the kingside, but the c2-pawn needs protection as well. }
11... Rfe8 { We have superb compensation. Even ... Bb3 is threatened. } *

