[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 3.Nc3 Four Knights with 4.d4"]
[Black "3.Nc3 Four Knights with 4.d4: 5.Nxd4 Nxe4 6.Nxc6 Nxc3 #1/3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet 3. Nc3 constantly, even by the players who, after 2... Nc6, wouldn't even think about playing 3. Nc3. The reason is simple - people usually don't like facing the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence.  Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  . OK, so with  3...Nc6  we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian, or my biggest fear - the Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. }
4. d4
{ I hate the Scotch - both in chess and when I enjoy a nice evening with friends. I am more of a Kentucky guy, both when eating or drinking. Still, White manages to reach the Four Knights Scotch with the text move, but the good news is that we avoided the 'proper' Scotch. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4
{ Recapturing on d4 has always been and I assume will always be the mainline. }
5... Nxe4
{ A perfect weapon for faster time controls @@StartBracket@@should be OK for classical as well@@EndBracket@@. Black's score here is higher @@StartBracket@@55% for us@@EndBracket@@ than after any other move, and there are tons of ways for White to mess up quickly. I also don't fancy entering 5... Bb4 when the tendencies of the resulting positions are quite drawish. Before I show you the theory of 5... Nxe4, I want to assure you - we don't sacrifice a piece here. }
6. Nxc6
{ This is the simple way for White to get a decent position and get the pawn back. }
6... Nxc3 7. Nxd8 Nxd1 8. Nxf7
{ Anything else leaves us with a clear extra pawn. } 8... Kxf7
{ Please, don't get tempted by  8...Nxf2??  when after  9.Nxh8  Nxh1  10.Be3  , White will play Bc4 and castle queenside with a huge, almost decisive edge. Our Knight isn't getting out from h1, I am not sure if the same can be said about the h8-Knight. }
9. Kxd1
{ Taking immediately is inaccurate. Still, more than 2/3 of online games feature this capture! }
9... d5
{ We can stop Bc4 and continue with ... Bf5, ... Bc5 and eventually ... c6, ... Rhe8 when our position seems easier to play. Sometimes ... c5 followed by ... b5 with a fast pawn storm will be possible as well. White's King is a bit misplaced on d1, while our is very stable on f7. }
