7. Bd3
{ If White wants to sacrifice the pawn, this is a more active way of doing it. }
7... Nxd4
{ We need to move the Knight for the 2nd time and our developed pieces are placed rather clumsily. Still, a pawn is a pawn and we will hold on to it as Gollum to the ring. }
8. O-O d5
{ It is possible to play  8...Ne6  as well and the lines will often transpose to each other, but starting with ... d5 is more critical, especially since White often makes mistakes. }
9. Nc3 { This is what people usually choose. } 9... c6
{ We solidify the centre and will continue with ... Ne6, ... Bd7 and then choose the side for castling. }
10. Re1 Ne6 11. f4 g6
{ We discourage f5 and can confidently look into the future. Our positional threat is ... f5! when White will be left with no compensation at all. }
