{ White safeguards the Bishop and prepares ideas connected with Qh5+, c4 and Bf5. }
12... Bg7
{ Very important. Tempting might look  12...Bd7??  but after  13.Bf5!  O-O-O  14.Qxd5  White has a winning position!   Note that after 12... Bg7, we are ready to castle kingside, but we should watch out for two tricks:  • If we castle too early, we might run into Qh5.  • Whenever White plays c4, we should meet it with ... d4, closing the centre. }
13. f4
{ White's compensation looks rather dangerous, so I suggest the following liquidating resource.   Note that  13.Bf5  is not so dangerous here. We can castle kingside or play  13...Kf7  , or even  13...a5  preparing to defend the Knight with ... Ra6 - this is the line I like the most. }
13... Qf7
{ It is necessary to start by moving the Queen.  13...O-O?  14.Qh5  is awkward. }
14. f5 O-O 15. fxe6 Bxe6
{ ... Rae8 and ... f5 are our main ideas. White still has compensation, but there is nothing concrete and a pawn is a pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 3.Nc3 Four Knights with 4.d4"]
[Black "3.Nc3 Four Knights with 4.d4: 5.Nxd4 Nxe4 6.Nxe4 Qe7 #7/17"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ An invitation to the Four Knights variation which we will choose to accept! What amuses me is that you will meet 3. Nc3 constantly, even by the players who, after 2... Nc6, wouldn't even think about playing 3. Nc3. The reason is simple - people usually don't like facing the Petroff and that is why we will devote some time to this line. }
3... Nc6
{ A 'Petroffian' way of playing would be  3...Bb4  , but I don't like it for one simple reason. I think I am with the majority of people when I say that I don't really fancy playing against the Berlin Defence.  Well, after  3...Bb4  this is exactly what we have, even being a tempo down. Also, I doubt that Black equalizes after  4.Nxe5  . OK, so with  3...Nc6  we are fine with transposing to the Four Knights. Fortunately, no transpositions to the Ruy Lopez, Italian, or my biggest fear - the Scotch are planned. White has plenty of options here, so let's check them. }
4. d4
{ I hate the Scotch - both in chess and when I enjoy a nice evening with friends. I am more of a Kentucky guy, both when eating or drinking. Still, White manages to reach the Four Knights Scotch with the text move, but the good news is that we avoided the 'proper' Scotch. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4
{ Recapturing on d4 has always been and I assume will always be the mainline. }
5... Nxe4
{ A perfect weapon for faster time controls @@StartBracket@@should be OK for classical as well@@EndBracket@@. Black's score here is higher @@StartBracket@@55% for us@@EndBracket@@ than after any other move, and there are tons of ways for White to mess up quickly. I also don't fancy entering 5... Bb4 when the tendencies of the resulting positions are quite drawish. Before I show you the theory of 5... Nxe4, I want to assure you - we don't sacrifice a piece here. }
6. Nxe4 { A much more ambitious approach compared with 6. Nxc6. } 6... Qe7
{ This is the trick. We will get the piece back because White can't protect both Knights simultaneously. That means that White will have to bank his play either on getting the pawn back or strive for compensation. }
7. Bd3
{ If White wants to sacrifice the pawn, this is a more active way of doing it. }
7... Nxd4
{ We need to move the Knight for the 2nd time and our developed pieces are placed rather clumsily. Still, a pawn is a pawn and we will hold on to it as Gollum to the ring. }
8. O-O d5
{ It is possible to play  8...Ne6  as well and the lines will often transpose to each other, but starting with ... d5 is more critical, especially since White often makes mistakes. }
9. Bc4
{ Nobody has ever tested this over the board, but I can see eight examples on Lichess, so let's devote a single line to see how to handle this strange move. }
9... Nf3+
{ Since taking one of the hanging pieces with the d-pawn runs into Qxd4, while taking on e4 with the Queen runs into Re1, we throw more wood into the fire! }
10. Qxf3
{ 10.gxf3  dxe4  is fully equal. Just remember to meet  11.Re1  with  11...Qf6  . }
10... Qxe4 { But not  10...dxe4?  11.Qg3  with a strong initiative for White. }
11. Bxd5 Qxf3 12. Bxf3 Be7
{ Next is ... c6 and ... Be6 followed by castling short. If White advances the a-pawn to a5, we should play ... a6. }
