[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 2.Nc3 Vienna"]
[Black "2.Nc3 Vienna: 3.f4 d5 4.exd5 Nxd5 5.Nxd5 Qxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ Starting from this chapter, we take a look at all of White's alternatives to  2.Nf3  . The first in line is the Vienna Game. People have played like this for at least 500 years, but even in 2022, there are top players who employ this opening occasionally. }
2... Nf6
{ This is the correct Knight. We should limit White's options to the minimum, even if it potentially looks a bit inconsistent on our part to avoid the symmetry in the opening! OK, we avoid symmetry, but on the other hand, we play the same exact move we would play against 2.Nf3.  Why  2...Nf6  then? The reason for that is relatively simple. We are 100% sure that the Knight belongs on f6, while I am uncertain if I want to commit the Knight to c6 yet. White has a handful of options now, so let's check them out!  Before we do that, I just want to mention that  3.Nf3  Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.a3  Nc6  4.Nf3  d5  transpose here,  or here respectively. }
3. f4
{ Usually, when someone thinks about the Vienna Game, this is the line that comes to mind first. White immediately strikes at our pawn in the style of the King's Gambit. }
3... d5 { We should counterattack in the centre immediately. } 4. exd5
{ This sideline is inconsistent and incorrect. White has hit the e5-pawn, so he should take it. }
4... Nxd5
{ As a result, the centre has opened up in our favour, because White has weakened the kingside. }
5. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ White decides to exchange everything, but note how stable our Queen on d5 is. There is no Knight on b1 to jump to c3, so we can proceed with ... Nc6 or ... e4, depending on White's next move. }
6. fxe5 Nc6 { The strongest.  6...Qxe5+?!  is good enough only for equality. }
7. Nf3 Bg4 8. Be2 O-O-O
{ We are ready to take on e5 with the Knight. If  9.O-O  , then  9...Bc5+  10.Kh1  Rhe8  with perfect development. The e5-pawn will be ours sooner or later. }
*

