3. f4
{ Usually, when someone thinks about the Vienna Game, this is the line that comes to mind first. White immediately strikes at our pawn in the style of the King's Gambit. }
3... d5 { We should counterattack in the centre immediately. } 4. fxe5
{ This is the right way of handling White's position. } 4... Nxe4
{ This is the tabiya for the 3. f4 variation. We will check four of White's most common options. }
5. Nxe4 { Taking on e4 is too cooperative. } 5... dxe4
{ At first glance, it might look like the position is symmetrical, but note that White lacks the f-pawn while we don't have the d-pawn, and White doesn't have the queenside Knight while we don't have the kingside one. It works in our favour for three reasons:   • Both the c8-Bishop and the Queen are free to join the battle.   • White's kingside is permanently weakened.   • The e4-pawn stops the White Knight from entering the fight via the most natural square f3, while our Knight from b8 can easily join the action and attack e5. }
6. d4
{ Otherwise, we would be able to play a combination of ... Nc6 and ... Bc5 when the e5-pawn would simply fall. }
