{ This is the correct Knight. We should limit White's options to the minimum, even if it potentially looks a bit inconsistent on our part to avoid the symmetry in the opening! OK, we avoid symmetry, but on the other hand, we play the same exact move we would play against 2.Nf3.  Why  2...Nf6  then? The reason for that is relatively simple. We are 100% sure that the Knight belongs on f6, while I am uncertain if I want to commit the Knight to c6 yet. White has a handful of options now, so let's check them out!  Before we do that, I just want to mention that  3.Nf3  Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.a3  Nc6  4.Nf3  d5  transpose here,  or here respectively. }
3. f4
{ Usually, when someone thinks about the Vienna Game, this is the line that comes to mind first. White immediately strikes at our pawn in the style of the King's Gambit. }
3... d5 { We should counterattack in the centre immediately. } 4. fxe5
{ This is the right way of handling White's position. } 4... Nxe4
{ This is the tabiya for the 3. f4 variation. We will check four of White's most common options. }
5. Qf3
{ This is a better way of targetting the Knight. White hopes that we will release the tension, but fortunately, we don't have to do it! }
5... Nc6
{ The counterattack secures us at least equal chances. Not only is ... Nxe5 threatened, but ... Nd4 and ... Nb4 are also there. }
6. Bb5
{ Before doing anything else, White is obliged to pin our Knight. However, we can now transform the position into something very comfortable for us. }
6... Nxc3 7. dxc3
{ 7.bxc3  Qh4+  8.g3  Qe4+  allows the same sequence, but with White's pawn structure being weakened - three pawn islands instead of two that arise after  7.dxc3  . }
7... Qh4+ 8. g3 Qe4+
{ We force the exchange of Queens, leaving White with a weak pawn on e5. Since the c2-pawn is hanging as well, White has to play  9.Qxe4  dxe4  10.Ne2  , but after  10...Bd7  , we already threaten to take on e5, and I really like our position. }
