1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ Starting from this chapter, we take a look at all of White's alternatives to  2.Nf3  . The first in line is the Vienna Game. People have played like this for at least 500 years, but even in 2022, there are top players who employ this opening occasionally. }
2... Nf6
{ This is the correct Knight. We should limit White's options to the minimum, even if it potentially looks a bit inconsistent on our part to avoid the symmetry in the opening! OK, we avoid symmetry, but on the other hand, we play the same exact move we would play against 2.Nf3.  Why  2...Nf6  then? The reason for that is relatively simple. We are 100% sure that the Knight belongs on f6, while I am uncertain if I want to commit the Knight to c6 yet. White has a handful of options now, so let's check them out!  Before we do that, I just want to mention that  3.Nf3  Nc6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.a3  Nc6  4.Nf3  d5  transpose here,  or here respectively. }
3. Bc4
{ This move defines the 2nd big part of the Vienna Game. It might resemble the Italian a bit, but the Knight on c3 changes everything. }
3... Nxe4
{ Both  3...Nc6  and  3...Bc5  are probably a shade more accurate, but in faster time controls, taking on e4 should work much more efficiently.  Also, both 3... Nc6 and 3... Bc5 are too 'Italianish'  . Most 'normal' moves score around 52-54% for White, While after  3...Nxe4  , the score drops down to 48% for our rival! }
4. Bxf7+ { As usual, this tempting option is bad. } 4... Kxf7 5. Nxe4 d5
{ White misplaced our King, but we got a big centre, the Bishop pair, and the Knight is forced to lose time. }
6. Qf3+ Kg8
{ We can simply continue with ... Nc6 next. Please, please, PLEASE don't take on e4 immediately because it runs into Qb3 CHECK and we should call it a day. }
7. d4
{ This might look like a misclick, but in fact, White sets up a cunning trap  7...dxe4??  8.Qb3+  and game over!   Note that  7.Ne2?  is played with the same idea. We should be playing  7...Nc6  and develop normally. }
7... exd4
{ Next is ... Nc6 or ... c5 with a big advantage. Just remember that we don't threaten to take on e4 yet. We will threaten to take the Knight after we play ... h6 though. }
