5. Bb3
{ Dropping the Bishop back is more ambitious. White threatens Nb5, which we should never allow. }
5... Be7
{ 5....Nc6  6.Nb5!  leads to the so-called Frankenstein-Dracula Gambit, but we shouldn't enter such crazy positions. Also, the chosen move is simply stronger and scores higher. }
6. Nf3 Nc6 { In this case, we don't have to rush with castling. } 7. Nxe5 g6
{ This move secures us better chances. We break the communication between White's kingside pieces. }
8. Nxc6 { This inclusion is mandatory to get a decent position. } 8... dxc6
{ As usual, we capture from the centre and plan to castle kingside next. } 9.
Qf3 O-O 10. O-O Nf5 { Next is ... Nd4 with an excellent game for Black. } *

