{ The only move to cause some difficulties. White threatens fxe5 and forces some reaction. This is the only case in the whole course when I give you two options. }
4... e4 { This is the tricky way to do it. } 5. d3
{ Unfortunately, there is this move. } 5... cxd5 6. dxe4 dxe4 7. Nc3
{ Not  7.Qxe4+  @@StartBracket@@which is the most common move@@EndBracket@@  because once again we get a very strong initiative - put the Knights on f6 and c6 next, castle short and exploit White's weakened kingside and lag in development. }
7... f5 8. Nf3
{ With Ne5 to come, I consider our position to be a bit unpleasant and objectively better for White. I don't have problems giving my rival an edge in the Damiano Variation, but doing it in the King's Gambit is a crime. Still, more often than not White will misplay the position and take on e4 with the Queen, either on move 5 or 7. }
8... Nc6 9. Ne5 Be6
{ And after  10.Be3  , White seems a little bit better and more importantly, our position isn't too easy to play. }
