{ The @@StartBracket@@in@@EndBracket@@famous King's Gambit. Even though many sources claim that the opening has been refuted, it is still the 2nd most popular move in over-the-board chess, while it is a very close contender for the 2nd place in online chess as well.   For ages, the King's Gambit has been considered the most challenging way of meeting 1... e5. Only during the Steinitz times, it started to change and top players started employing other openings.   Nowadays, it is popular on all levels, so no matter what is yours, you should be ready to meet it @@StartBracket@@especially in faster time controls@@EndBracket@@. We should also expect a boost in popularity after the 2021 World Championship challenger Ian Nepomniachtchi published a course on this opening here on Chessable. }
2... d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit. There are two things that can be said about Black's 2nd move before I share with you my reasoning behind 2... d5.   • It is widely known that the theoretical 'refutation' of the opening is  2...exf4  when Black either holds on to the pawn or gets a better position on equal material terms.   • In the 17th, 18th, and 19th centuries, declining the King's Gambit was widely considered to be a shameful behaviour. If someone didn't play  2...exf4  , he immediately lost any respect and whenever he visited any pastry shop, the owner would put raisins in his cheesecake. As you can see, we are now cowards who don't follow the theoretical recommendations.  To understand my decision, let me mention what the statistics are. White's score after  2...exf4  is 54% @@StartBracket@@Lichess@@EndBracket@@ while after  2...d5  it is a mere 48%, which drops to a rather pathetic 40% after  3.exd5  c6!?  which is my suggestion. Remember that we want a weapon that forces our rivals to think as early as possible. And even though we won't get an advantage out of the opening if our rival plays accurately, I am highly recommending my chosen variation for faster time controls. }
3. exd5
{ The only challenging move. Now,  3...e4?!  has been considered for some time to be a nice follow-up to 2...d5, but nowadays, it is refuted by  4.d3  Nf6  5.dxe4  Nxe4  6.Nf3  Bc5  7.Qe2  with a significant edge for White.   Best is  3...exf4  , which gives Black a rather easy game, but still, the  3...exf4  line is definitely something your rival will expect, while I doubt he will expect our next move. }
3... c6
{ I was amazed to discover that this move is in fact good even from a theoretical perspective. It doesn't offer an edge, but it offers a good game with many pitfalls for our opponent! }
4. Qe2
{ The only move to cause some difficulties. White threatens fxe5 and forces some reaction. This is the only case in the whole course when I give you two options. }
4... cxd5
{ Taking on e5 is the critical approach. We don't give ourselves the pleasure of going for the line with traps, but we continue in the most solid way available. }
5. Qxe5+ { Very risky. } 5... Be7
{ We will play ... Nf6 and ... Nc6 with a tremendous initiative for Black. I just want to point out the following trick. }
6. Qxg7 Bf6 7. Qg3 Bh4 *

