{ The Bishop's Opening. Before developing the Knights, White moves the Bishop, only to decide on his setup later. There are still some transpositions possible after  2...Nf6  3.Nc3  when we end up in a Vienna Game, but most of the time White will meet  2...Nf6  with  3.d3  . With the Knight still on g1, White can then decide if to play in the spirit of the Italian game with Nf3, maybe ponder some f4 ideas, or go for something else. }
2... Nf6
{ Of course, we develop this Knight first. We want to make sure that White does something about the hanging pawn on e4. Now, I have already mentioned that  3.Nc3  transposes to the Vienna Game after  3...Nxe4  .   I also want to point out that  3.Nf3?!  leads to theReversed Stafford Gambit after  3...Nxe4!  .   All the above means that White's decent original options are limited to two - it is either  3.d3  which is the mainline or  3.d4  which leads to the aggressive Urusov Gambit. }
3. d4
{ The so-called Urusov Gambit. An aggressive opening where if Black makes one inaccuracy, the consequences can be deadly. }
3... exd4
{ This one is obvious. The pawn has to be taken. Now, to prove that his previous play made any sense, White has to put the Knight on f3. }
4. Nf3
{ Only this way. White hopes to lure us into the Scotch Gambit lines after  4...Nc6  or into accepting the gambit with  4...Nxe4  when after  5.Qxd4  , he gets a dangerous initiative. }
4... Bb4+
{ Not only is this the most practical approach, but it is also most probably the best move from the theoretical perspective. We avoid any transpositions, make sure we will get an original position @@StartBracket@@not reachable via any other order@@EndBracket@@ and hold on to the pawn for the time being. }
5. Bd2
{ Objectively not bad, but allowing this exchange is inconsistent. One can't play a gambit and focus on getting the pawn back only to land in a worse position. }
5... Bxd2+
{ Even  5...Bc5  isn't out of the question, but I like the simplicity of the text move. }
6. Nbxd2 { A necessity. } 6... Nc6
{ I hesitated a bit here, also considering  6...O-O  but I dislike that after  7.O-O  the only benefit of using this move order is that we can play  7...c5  when White gets good practical compensation.   Since  6...O-O  allows  7.Nxd4  as well, developing the Knight first should be the way to go.   With  6...Nc6  , we defend the pawn and prepare to castle next. }
7. e5
{ Not too great, but our handling should be different from the similar variation we have analyzedhere. }
7... Ng4
{ 7...d5?  8.Bb5  is excellent for White. Note that with the example given above, we didn't have the Knight on c6 yet, making Bb5 unattractive. }
8. O-O O-O
{ We will take the e5-pawn with the g-Knight either with or without ... Re8 included. }
*

