{ The Bishop's Opening. Before developing the Knights, White moves the Bishop, only to decide on his setup later. There are still some transpositions possible after  2...Nf6  3.Nc3  when we end up in a Vienna Game, but most of the time White will meet  2...Nf6  with  3.d3  . With the Knight still on g1, White can then decide if to play in the spirit of the Italian game with Nf3, maybe ponder some f4 ideas, or go for something else. }
2... Nf6
{ Of course, we develop this Knight first. We want to make sure that White does something about the hanging pawn on e4. Now, I have already mentioned that  3.Nc3  transposes to the Vienna Game after  3...Nxe4  .   I also want to point out that  3.Nf3?!  leads to theReversed Stafford Gambit after  3...Nxe4!  .   All the above means that White's decent original options are limited to two - it is either  3.d3  which is the mainline or  3.d4  which leads to the aggressive Urusov Gambit. }
3. d3
{ The 'proper' way to play the Bishop Opening. White defends the pawn and will most probably play 4.Nf3 next. It is an important moment because if we continue in the most stereotypical way with  3...Nc6  or  3...Bc5  , then after  4.Nf3  , we will end up in the Italian Opening! }
3... c6
{ No transpositions for you, sir! Also, it is objectively the best move for Black. We want to exploit the Bishop's placement on c4 by striking with ... d5 and winning a tempo. Also, since the pawn is already on d3, there is no need to worry about any d4 ideas.   Since something like  4.Nc3?!  only creates another target after  4...d5  5.exd5  cxd5  6.Bb3  Bb4  threatening ... d4, we will exclusively cover the lines where White prepares to meet ... d5. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing the Knight to f3 is the key idea for the opening. White hopes that quick development will prove sufficient for an edge @@StartBracket@@SPOILER ALERT: it won't@@EndBracket@@. }
4... d5 5. Bb3
{ This is the tabiya for the Bishop Opening. The e5-pawn is hanging and White hopes to trick us into  5...dxe4?  6.Ng5!  .   I hope we are not so naive, so we have three options. We can put the Bishop on d6 immediately, which is the most common choice, we can also play  5...Bb4+  and drop the Bishop back to d6 later, or we can go for something less common and much more venomous! }
5... a5
{ An exclamation mark is purely for the practical value of this move. It is only the 3rd most popular option in over-the-board chess and the 4th online. What convinced me to go for this aggressive approach is the fact that after the other tries, White scores a respected 50%+, while after 5... a5, the score drops to 42%. The big idea behind 5... a5 is to force White into some concessions because of the threat of ... a4. There are four ways to stop it, and we will take a look at all of them. }
6. Nc3
{ I consider this move to be one of the two options that give White a good position @@StartBracket@@or not a worse position, to be precise@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bb4
{ With a double threat of ... d4 and ... a4. White has only one solution. } 7.
a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 a4
{ As a result of our little operation, we weakened White's pawn structure, but at the cost of the Bishop. }
9. Ba2 Qc7
{ This is the correct way of defending e5. We keep the Knight on b8 for the time being hoping that it can jump to c6 in the future. I also thought about  9...dxe4  , but concluded that after  10.Nxe5  O-O  11.O-O  Nbd7  White has a few promising options,  12.Nxf7  being one of them. }
10. O-O O-O
{ We do plan to play ... dxe4 and ... Nbd7 next. If White takes on d5, he improves our pawn structure and frees the c6-square for the Knight. If White allows ... dxe4, he will be left with doubled pawns on the c-file. }
*

