{ Probably best. All of the nonsense connected with ... a4 is avoided, while the threat of Nxe5 is renewed. }
6... Bb4+
{ A very important intermezzo.  6...Bd6?!  7.exd5  cxd5  8.Bg5  Be6  9.Nc3  and White's army pressurizes our centre. We probably need to play  9...d4  , which is already a concession. Note that  9...Bc7  10.Qe2  Nc6  11.O-O-O  with d4 or/and Bxf6 to come is excellent for White. }
7. c3 Bd6
{ We wasted one move, but the c3-square is occupied by a pawn, and we don't have to worry about Nc3. }
8. exd5
{ White usually takes, because otherwise we can capture on e4 and reach a stable pawn structure with a solid position for us. }
8... cxd5 9. Bg5 Be6 { We have seen something like this already. } 10. Na3
{ This is the only way to apply some more pressure. We weakened the b5-square and White will exploit it by putting the Knight there. }
10... Nbd7
{ There are also setups connected with ... Nc6 and ... h6, but I like this one the most. It looks the most intuitive to play.  10...Nc6  11.Nb5  Bb8  12.d4  e4  13.Nd2  O-O  14.f3  is an example of a line that I dislike. }
11. Nb5 Bb8
{ The plan that I'd like to implement after we castle kingside is ... Ra6!? followed by ... Nc5 and ... Bf5. The Rook is quite useful on the 6th rank. }
12. d4
{ 12.O-O  O-O  doesn't change much. White has to play d4 sooner or later to avoid being worse. }
12... e4 13. Nd2 h6
{ An important move, gaining us control over the f4-square. } 14. Bh4
{ 14.Be3?  Ng4  is not what White wants. } 14... Bf4
{ We will usually castle followed by ... Nb6 or even ... g5. We have excellent counterplay. Note that whenever White plays c4, we should take.   Also,  14...Bf4  is designed to fight against f3, for example,  15.f3?  O-O  16.fxe4  g5  17.Bf2  Bxd2+  with ... Nxe4 to come and a big advantage for Black. The Bishop's Opening is a challenging one, but after following my suggested lines, we should be doing very well! }
