[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) 2.d4 without 3.Qxd4"]
[Black "2.d4 without 3.Qxd4: 3.c3 Ne7 #1/3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ The Centre Game. White usually plays this move to get an open game and focus more on tactics than strategy. I recommend treating this and the next chapter very seriously for two main reasons:  •  2.d4  is the 4th most popular move that is played around once every fifteen games. Not much but also it is not a small number.  • The positions don't resemble anything else and require an unstereotypical approach. We should also be aware that White has three independent options after we play  2...exd4  , and all of them have a bit different flavour. }
2... exd4
{ Nothing else makes sense. Now,  3.Bc4  Nf6  leads to the Urusov Gambit which has been analyzed in the previous chapter starting fromthis variation so let's cover the independent possibilities White has. }
3. c3
{ The Danish Gambit. White hopes to sacrifice a pawn or two to speed up his development. The good news is that there is more than one good way of meeting this, but the one I will suggest is extremely rare and unknown. On average, Black's next move is played once every thousand games! }
3... Ne7
{ A perfect weapon to surprise your rival. Both  3...dxc3  and  3...Qe7  are theoretically better, but impractical for faster time controls. The main idea behind  3...Ne7  is to push ... d5 and recapture with the Knight. }
4. Bc4
{ White might ignore our hanging pawn and develop the Bishop hoping to discourage us from playing ... d5. }
4... d5 { I don't feel discouraged at all. } 5. exd5 Nxd5
{ We want to play ... Nb6 next when if White plays Bb3, we can even consider ... d3 to hold on to the pawn for the time being. }
6. Qxd4 Qe7+
{ An important check. We step out from the d-file and plan to play ... Nb6 next. }
7. Ne2 Nb6
{ ... Nc6 ... Bf5 and ... O-O-O are coming with an advantage for Black. Our pieces are more active and White's c3-pawn would prefer to be on c2. }
*

