1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ The Centre Game. White usually plays this move to get an open game and focus more on tactics than strategy. I recommend treating this and the next chapter very seriously for two main reasons:  •  2.d4  is the 4th most popular move that is played around once every fifteen games. Not much but also it is not a small number.  • The positions don't resemble anything else and require an unstereotypical approach. We should also be aware that White has three independent options after we play  2...exd4  , and all of them have a bit different flavour. }
2... exd4
{ Nothing else makes sense. Now,  3.Bc4  Nf6  leads to the Urusov Gambit which has been analyzed in the previous chapter starting fromthis variation so let's cover the independent possibilities White has. }
3. Nf3
{ By using this move order, White hopes to lure us into the Scotch after  3...Nc6  . or the Scotch Gambit after  3...Bc5  . We have to say no. }
3... Bb4+
{ The best move, both theoretically, and practically. We don't allow any transpositions and make sure that White will think twice before using this move order against us again. Also, against theUrusov Gambit, we have used a similar pattern. }
4. Bd2
{ Blocking with the Bishop might be OK, but there is no way we will ever be in any sort of trouble after the following exchange. }
4... Bxd2+ 5. Nbxd2 { Objectively, this is the best move, but it is rare. }
5... Nc6
{ Just remember that with the White Knight on d2, we don't play ... c5. We want to play ... Nf6 followed by ... O-O and ... d5 instead resulting in at least equality for us. }
