{ By using this move order, White hopes to lure us into the Scotch after  3...Nc6  . or the Scotch Gambit after  3...Bc5  . We have to say no. }
3... Bb4+
{ The best move, both theoretically, and practically. We don't allow any transpositions and make sure that White will think twice before using this move order against us again. Also, against theUrusov Gambit, we have used a similar pattern. }
4. Bd2
{ Blocking with the Bishop might be OK, but there is no way we will ever be in any sort of trouble after the following exchange. }
4... Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 { This is what is played in the majority of games. } 5... c5
{ With the Queen on d2, it works like a charm! This is the only move to maintain an advantage. Anything else not only loses it but gives White an undeserved edge! }
6. c3 Nf6
{ Just in time with the countershot. We plan ... O-O and ... d5 next. } 7. e5
{ Or  7.Bd3  d5!  with an advantage for us. } 7... Ne4
{ This is the biggest disadvantage of having the Queen on d2. We can jump to e4 and win an important tempo. Next is ... d5 followed by ... O-O and ... Nc6. Only one variation needs precision. }
8. Qf4 d5 9. exd6 O-O { The Knight is taboo due to ... Re8. } *

