[Round "?"]
[White "16) 2.d4 without 3.Qxd4"]
[Black "2.d4 without 3.Qxd4: 3.Nf3 Bb4+ #5/13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ The Centre Game. White usually plays this move to get an open game and focus more on tactics than strategy. I recommend treating this and the next chapter very seriously for two main reasons:  •  2.d4  is the 4th most popular move that is played around once every fifteen games. Not much but also it is not a small number.  • The positions don't resemble anything else and require an unstereotypical approach. We should also be aware that White has three independent options after we play  2...exd4  , and all of them have a bit different flavour. }
2... exd4
{ Nothing else makes sense. Now,  3.Bc4  Nf6  leads to the Urusov Gambit which has been analyzed in the previous chapter starting fromthis variation so let's cover the independent possibilities White has. }
3. Nf3
{ By using this move order, White hopes to lure us into the Scotch after  3...Nc6  . or the Scotch Gambit after  3...Bc5  . We have to say no. }
3... Bb4+
{ The best move, both theoretically, and practically. We don't allow any transpositions and make sure that White will think twice before using this move order against us again. Also, against theUrusov Gambit, we have used a similar pattern. }
4. c3
{ This is the gambit way of handling things. However, we are fully ready to at some point give the pawn back for positional dividends. }
4... dxc3 5. Nxc3
{ The correct way of handling things. White will gradually prepare kingside castling, when we will be advised to take on c3 immediately.   Now, in practice, Black often takes on c3 right away, which makes no sense to me. It is MUCH more practical to target White's centre. }
5... Nf6
{ Objectively best is  5...Nc6  , but it transposes to the accepted version of the Danish Gambit where White has excellent practical compensation for the pawn. I would avoid it in classical chess, not to mention faster time controls. }
6. Bc4 { The most common guest in online chess practice. } 6... Nxe4
{ This time, the difference in the evaluation of this variation compared to the others is too big not to go for it! Because the position might quickly become tricky, I decided to devote three lines to it. }
7. O-O
{ Castling is too slow and should play into our hands if you meet it correctly. }
7... Bxc3 { Again this theme. } 8. bxc3 O-O
{ We want to play ... Nf6 followed by ... d5 or ... c6 followed by ... d5. Only the following sequence needs some sort of memorization @@StartBracket@@it is by far the most common sequence in practice@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Re1 Nf6
{ There is one fine middlegame rule that when you are behind in development, you should in general keep the active pieces on the board. }
10. Bg5 d5 { We give up one pawn for relative peace. } 11. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ White can win the d5-pawn, but we still have one extra soldier. } *

