{ This move offers White the best chances to get a good game. } 7... Nxe4
{ I hesitated about  7...O-O  but there is this line that goes  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Bd3  Nxe4  10.Qf4  Re8  11.O-O  Nc5  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Qf5+  Kg8  14.Qxc5  Qf6  when we should be fine, but there is absolutely no way to talk about any advantage at all. }
8. Nxc6 { Otherwise, we would play ... Nxd4 followed by ... O-O. } 8... dxc6
{ We offer the exchange of Queens, but our pieces are ready for the resulting pawn structure.   If you prefer something calmer, then  8...Nxd2  9.Nxd8  Nxf1  10.Nxf7  Kxf7  11.Kxf1  d6  is fully equal. }
9. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Next are ... Nd6 and ... Be6 with an extra pawn for Black. It is not the prettiest pawn ever, but still, a pawn is a pawn. The King will usually be hidden on d7 to connect the Rooks. }
