[White "17) 2.d4 with 3.Qxd4"]
[Black "2.d4 with 3.Qxd4: 3...Nc6 4.Qe3 Nf6 #9/11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4
{ The Centre Game. White usually plays this move to get an open game and focus more on tactics than strategy. I recommend treating this chapter very seriously for two main reasons:  •  2.d4  is the 4th most popular move which is played around once every fifteen games. Not much but also it is not a small number.  • The positions don't resemble anything else and require an unstereotypical approach. We should also be aware that White has three independent options after we play  2...exd4  , and all of them have a bit different flavour. }
2... exd4 3. Qxd4
{ The Centre Game. It has always reminded me of a Scandinavian with an extra e4 from White. With this approach, White really makes sure that there will be some bare-knuckle fight ahead. OK, fine, let's take the gloves off then and show our opponent our war face. }
3... Nc6
{ We obviously win a tempo on the Queen. White has a few options now. } 4. Qe3
{ Historically, retreating the Queen to e3 has always been the main move. Still, it should be more than fine for us to enter this variation. }
4... Nf6
{ This is the tabiya for the Centre Game. White has to decide on his future setup and I believe that only one option guarantees him equality. }
5. Nc3
{ Developing the Knight to c3 has always been the mainline. Still, it allows us to go for the familiar resource. }
5... Bb4
{ We simply want to continue with ... O-O and then a combination of ... Re8 and ... d5. }
6. Bd2
{ This is almost exclusively played. White prepares fast long castling. } 6...
O-O 7. O-O-O Re8
{ We should consider this position a tabiya for the 4. Qe3 variation. White's centre is under pressure and our rival has a few different ways of handling this position. }
8. Qf4
{ A very interesting way of handling the variation. The main exponent of it is GM Ian Nepomniachtchi. White steps away from the e-file and prepares to develop with Nge2. }
8... Bxc3 { We should pick up the gauntlet and go for the pawn. } 9. Bxc3 Rxe4
{ But not  9...Nxe4?  10.Bc4  with superb compensation. } 10. Qg3 d5
{ With a subtle idea of ... d4. } 11. f3 Re6
{ That's everything you need to know. The Rook goes to d6 next and we want to push ... d4. }
*

