O-O 7. O-O-O Re8
{ We should consider this position a tabiya for the 4. Qe3 variation. White's centre is under pressure and our rival has a few different ways of handling this position. }
8. Bc4
{ This is the final option we will cover. White plays as actively as possible, which means we shouldn't go for any pawn grabs and focus on developing instead. }
8... d6
{ With ideas such as ... Be6, ... Ne5 or even ... Bxc3 followed by ... Nxe4 @@StartBracket@@should work when we have the pawn on d6 already@@EndBracket@@, we should have an excellent game. }
9. f3 { 9.Nf3  Be6  is also better for Black. } 9... Ne5
{ We start something on the queenside. We will play ... c6 followed by ... d5/b5 after all moves but one. }
10. Bb3 a5
{ Next are ... c6, ... b5 and ... a4 with a pawn storm. White's kingside offensive hasn't even started. }
