1. e4 e5 2. Bb5
{ The so-called Portuguese variation. I don't believe in the Ruy Lopez without ... Nc6. }
2... Nf6 { We want to play ... c6 next. } 3. d4
{ This is the only consistent approach. } 3... exd4 4. e5 Qe7
{ We have to pin the pawn to maintain an edge. } 5. Qxd4 Nc6
{ Very simple. White has to take on c6 as otherwise, e5 will fall. } 6. Bxc6
dxc6
{ We have seen countless examples throughout the course that whenever possible, we should capture from the centre. We open up the light-squared Bishop and avoid isolating the a-pawn, as it would be the case after ... bxc6. }
7. Nf3 Nd5
{ We will have to move the Knight anyway, so let's do it immediately. } 8. O-O
Bf5 { Next is ... Qd7/Qc5 followed by long castling. } *

