1. e4 e5 2. Ne2
{ Not too aggressive, but players such as Moiseenko, Ivanchuk, and Van Foreest tested it so far. }
2... Nf6
{ Even in such obscure lines, it is mandatory to be alert! 2... Nc6 3. d4! and we end up in a Scotch after 3... cxd4   4.Nxd4  . }
3. d4 { White has to play this move to avoid falling into a worse position. }
3... Nxe4 4. f3 { 4.dxe5?  Bc5  is great for us. } 4... Ng5
{ In this case, with the White pawn being on f3 instead of f4, we shouldn't play  4...Nd6?!  due to  5.dxe5  Nf5  6.Nbc3  and White might even be slightly better. }
5. dxe5 Ne6
{ A string move, sidestepping the f4-f5 ideas. They are not too strong now, when we not only can put the Knight on c5 in one go  (just in case)  , but even more importantly, some additional ... Qh4 options are available as well. Also, whenever the centre gets opened, we should consider exchanging the dark-squared Bishops with ... Bc5, when the Knight's presence on e6 is helpful.  After 5... Ne6, we will play ... Nc6 and ... Be7, followed by ... d6 or ... d5. }
