1. e4 e5 2. Qh5
{ The final option we will cover is the Scholar's Mate attempt. Since our rival wants to end the game in 4 moves, I think it makes sense to end the theoretical section with this provocative Queen sortie. Since I promised practical lines where our opponents would be forced to think on their own quickly, this variation is no exception! }
2... Nc6 3. Bc4 { Please, don't allow Qxf7 and life will be good. } 3... g6
{ All of our opponent's dreams have just been ruined. } 4. Qf3
{ Again, don't blunder mate on f7. } 4... f5
{ You might as well play the standard  4...Nf6  , but White should be ready for that. By playing  4...f5  , we strike back immediately and raise the stakes. }
5. exf5 { This is how the vast majority of the games continue. Good! } 5... Nd4
{ We will either take on c2 or play ... d5.   After  6.Qd5  we can play both ... Qe7 followed by ... Nf6 or ... Qf6 followed by ... Ne7.   Also note that after  6.Qg3  we shouldn't enter the greedy mode, but start with  6...Qe7!  to defend the hanging pawn first, and only then think about going for the c2-pawn. }
*

