1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. Qxe5 Qxe5+
8. dxe5 Nc6 9. Bb5 Bd7
{ Theoretical Chapter and Variation@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@:  Chapter: 1@@EndBracket@@ Petroff 7.Qxe5   Variation: 7.Qxe5 Qxe5+ 8.dxe5 Nc6 9.Bb5 Bd7 #1/3 🡆 #3/3 }
10. Nc3 O-O-O
{ The great news is that no matter what White does, Black will always be able to get the pawn back with the ... Nxe5 trick. OK, maybe not after  11.f4?!  but after  11...Nb4!  I wouldn't like to be in White's shoes. }
11. Be3 Nxe5 12. Bxd7+
{ A common mistake in faster time controls. As a result, White won't be able to castle long. }
12... Rxd7 13. O-O Nc4
{ Black is already considerably better. White faces issues with keeping the queenside together. Both ... Nxe3 and ... Nxb2 are threatened, while ... Bb4 is also a very promising idea. }
14. Bc1
{ Maybe better was  14.Nd1  , but after  14...Nxe3  15.Nxe3  Bc5  16.Rfd1  Rhd8  , White faces a difficult defence. }
14... Bb4
{ Black is ready to continue with ... Bxc3 or ... Re8/Rd8 next. White can't untangle. }
15. Ne4 Re8 16. Ng3 g6
{ Some other moves were more accurate, but I wanted to restrict the Knight. }
17. b3 Bc3 { The immediate  17...Nd2  was equally good. } 18. Rb1 Nd2 19. Bxd2
Rxd2
{ My advantage has transformed. The White Knight is doing nothing and the c2-pawn has to fall. }
20. Rfc1 Bd4 { This wins material. } 21. Rd1
{ 21.Nh1  Ree2  is only a temporary solution for White. } 21... Bxf2+ 22. Kf1
Rxc2 { White threw the towel. } *

