[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Andriasian, Zaven vs. Ponkratov, Pavel / PRO League Stage Chess.com INT rapid (10) / 13.03.2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6
8. Nc3 Qxe5 9. Bf4
{ As shown in the theory section@@StartBracket@@#1, #2 and #3@@EndBracket@@, not taking on e5 eases Black's task tremendously. }
9... Qxe4+ 10. Nxe4 Bf5 { Always active. } 11. Bd3 O-O-O 12. O-O-O Bg6
{ We have followed this variation. With the pawn structure being symmetrical, Black equalized comfortably. White correctly sees that Black threatens to play ... Nb4, but there is a 2nd option that is MUCH harder to spot. }
13. a3
{ The best move for White was  13.Rhe1  , planning to meet  13...Nb4  with  14.Bc4  . }
13... Rd4
{ White loses material. It is either the Knight on e4 or the Bishop on f4 that will be taken, usually with the help from the move ... f5. }
14. Rhe1 f5 15. Ng3
{ Andriasian decides to set up a tough resistance, but it is too late! } 15...
Rxf4 16. Bxf5+ { A nice trick, hoping for some back rank mate ideas. } 16...
Rxf5 { The only move to maintain a winning advantage. } 17. Nxf5 Bc5
{ 17...Bxa3  was probably stronger and simpler. } 18. Ne3 Re8
{ I like  18...Rf8  trying to provoke  19.f3  when after  19...Bd6  , White faces issues with the kingside. }
19. Ng4 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 h5
{ The exchange of Rooks should in general help White, but in this specific case, White can't activate the Rook in any way. Black will always be able to cover all the entry squares. }
21. Ne3 b6 22. Rd1 Be4 23. g3 Ne5 24. b4 Bxe3+
{ Probably the simplest. Since the resulting endgame is technically winning, Ponkratov's decision should be considered as correct given the 'rapid' circumstances. However, purists would probably prefer to see  24...Be7  , keeping the Bishop pair. }
25. fxe3 Ng4 26. h4 Bf5 27. Rf1 g6
{ This is the formation Ponkratov played for. Now, the e3-pawn is weak, but there is also a permanent weakness on g3. }
28. Kd2 Kd7 29. c4 Kd6 30. Rf4 Nf6
{ ... Ne4 is coming. White shouldn't be able to save this. The rest is a matter of technique. }
31. Rd4+ Ke5 32. Ke2 Ne4 33. Kf3
{ 33.Rd5+  with Rd8 to come was most probably the best practical chance. }
33... Nd6 34. Rd5+ Ke6 { Now, c4 falls. } 35. Kf4
{ 35.Rd4  c5  36.bxc5  bxc5  37.Rf4  isn't really a solution. The Rook is basically trapped. }
35... Nxc4 36. e4 Bg4
{ This also wins, but it doesn't win the beauty prize!   36...Bxe4!!  Ok, this is impossible to find in the game with faster time control, but it really gives you a WOW effect.  37.Kxe4  Nd6+  38.Kd4  Nf5+  39.Ke4  Nxg3+  40.Kd4  Nf5+  41.Ke4  Nd6+  42.Kd4  c5+!  The first point.  43.bxc5  Nf5+  44.Ke4  Ng3+  45.Kd4  Ne2+  46.Kc4  b5+  The 2nd point. Beautiful. }
37. a4 Nd6 38. Rg5 Kf7 39. Rd5 Bd7 40. b5 Be6
{ Black will now move around with his pieces combining attacks on a4 and e4. Also, ... Nb7-c5 is coming. }
41. Rd3 { This eases Black's task. } 41... Nxe4
{ The rest is straightforward. } 42. Rd8 Nc5 43. Ra8 Ke7 44. Rxa7 Kd6 45. a5
Bc4 46. Kg5 Bxb5 47. axb6 cxb6 48. Kxg6 Be2 49. Kg5 b5 50. Kf4 b4 51. Ke3 Bg4
52. Kd4 b3 53. Kc3 Bd1 54. Ra8 Ne4+ 55. Kb2 Ke5
{ It wasn't too late to mess up after  55...Nxg3??  56.Rd8+  . } 56. Rg8 Nc5
57. Kc1 Bg4 58. Kb2 Na4+ { Clever! } 59. Kxb3 Be6+ 60. Kxa4 Bxg8 61. Kb4
{ Note that this position would also be winning with the dark-squared Bishop instead of the light-squared one. White is not in time to reach the h1-square. }
61... Ke4 62. Kc3 Kf3 63. Kd2 Kxg3 64. Ke1 Kxh4 65. Kf1 Kg3 66. Kg1 h4 67. Kh1
h3 68. Kg1 Bc4 69. Kh1 Bd5+ 70. Kg1 h2+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
