[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bocharov, Ivan vs. Afanasiev, Nikita / Moscow op-A 17th (7) / 26.02.2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. f4 f5 7. Qe3 dxe5 8.
fxe5 Nc6 9. d4
{ What shocks me is that if I am not mistaken, this has been a classical game. How did that saying go? 'Always look for checks and captures first'. }
9... Qh4+ 10. g3 Qxd4
{ Theoretical Chapter and Variation@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@:  Chapter: 5@@EndBracket@@ Petroff 6.f4   Variation: 6.f4 dxe5 7.fxe5 f5 8.Qe3 Nc6 }
11. Qxd4 Nxd4 12. Bd3 Be6
{ Black misses a golden opportunity here.  12...Nf3+  13.Kf2  Be6!!  would be almost crushing. }
13. Kf2 Bc5 14. Be3 O-O-O 15. Rd1 Bb6
{ White managed to avoid a disaster but Black is considerably better. The e5-pawn is a weakness that can't stay in the middle of the board forever. It is basically doomed and White should bank his play on getting activity, instead of trying to hold to the poor guy at all costs. }
16. Nc3 Nc6 17. Bxb6 axb6 18. Re1 g5
{ Afanasiev has a perfect blockade, so he correctly pushes the kingside majority. }
19. Rad1 h5 20. h4
{ This is a decisive strategic mistake. It was mandatory to allow the Black pawn to h4. }
20... gxh4 21. gxh4 Rd4
{ I assume this is what White has missed. There is no way to protect both weak pawns. }
22. Rh1 Nxe5 23. Be2 Rf4+ 24. Ke3 Rb4
{ Threatening not only ... Rxb2 but more importantly, ... f4+ followed by ... f3. }
25. Rd4 Rxb2 26. Ra4 Kb8 27. Kd2 { Sneaky, trying to trap the Rook with Kc1. }
27... Nc6 28. Re1 Nb4 29. Bd1 Nxa2 { Nicely calculated. } 30. Nxa2
{ 30.Rxe6  Rd8+!  was the point. } 30... Rxa2 31. Rxa2 Bxa2 32. Re5 Rd8+ 33.
Kc1 Rd4 34. Rxf5 Rxh4 35. Bxh5 c6
{ Despite the reduced material, Black wins easily. } 36. Rg5 Bd5 37. Bg4 Rh1+
38. Kb2 Rg1 39. Rg6 b5 40. Kc3 Ka7
{ Since the Bishop endgame leaves White no illusions after ... c5 and ... b4, White resigned. }
