[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Karpov, Anatoly vs. Larsen, Bent / Interpolis-04 Tilburg (3) / 21.09.1980"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Qe2 Nxe5 7. Bxe4 dxe4
8. Qxe4 Be6 9. Qxe5 Qd7
{ We have analyzed this position in this variation. White won a pawn but Black has full compensation for it. Next follows queenside castling. }
10. O-O O-O-O { White has to spend a tempo on defending the d4-pawn now. } 11.
Be3
{ The only sensible way to do that. Placing the Rook on d1 makes no sense while  11.c3?  just blocks the c3-square and the Knight doesn't have natural developing squares. }
11... Bb4
{ This is an extremely powerful plan. Despite being a pawn down, Larsen correctly evaluates that exchanging the dark-squared Bishop for the Knight will give him not only eternal compensation, but a huge initiative in the middlegame. }
12. Nc3
{ The problem for White is that there aren't too many options available. Placing the pawn on c3 is sub-optimal, while Black was ready to play ... Rde8, followed by a pawn storm on the kingside. }
12... f6 13. Qg3 Bxc3
{ The big strategic point. As a result, Black will have a very strong initiative on the light squares, while White can't do much on the dark squares. Therefore, Black plays kind of a piece up for the moment. }
14. bxc3 h5 { Simple. The h-pawn wants to knock at White's kingside's door. }
15. h4 g5
{ And now the g-pawn follows. Black's attack should be impossible to parry, even for Karpov. }
16. f3 Rdg8 { All of Black's pieces participate in the attack. } 17. Rf2 Qc6
{ It was possible to play ... g4 right away as well. } 18. Bd2 g4 19. f4
{ Karpov banks his play on the blockade. However, even though the attack is temporarily stopped, the dark-squared Bishop won't be able to do anything productive. }
19... Bc4 { Larsen plans to double the Rooks on the e-file. } 20. d5
{ If nothing happens, White will be dominated. Therefore, Karpov tries to do something. }
20... Bxd5 21. f5 Re8 22. a3
{ A small improvement. The pawn won't be hanging. } 22... Re4
{ Larsen continues to improve his position. } 23. Re1 Rhe8 24. Rxe4 Rxe4 25.
Kh2 Qc5 26. Bf4 Re1
{ Black's plan is to take White's queenside pawns one by one without allowing any counterplay. }
27. Bd2 Ra1 28. Qe3 Qd6+
{ Exchanging the Queens and taking on a3 would give White decent practical chances to hold. }
29. Rf4
{ Now, it is a different story.  29.Qf4  Qxf4+!  30.Bxf4  Rxa3  and the Bishop is not in time to take the f6-pawn. }
29... b6 30. c4 Bxc4 31. Qd4 Qxd4 32. Rxd4 Bb5
{ The Bishop will be transferred to d7 next. White also can't save the a3-pawn. }
33. Bh6 Rxa3 34. Bg7 Bd7 35. Rf4 Ra5 36. Bxf6 Bxf5
{ The simplest. White won't be able to dream about saving the game without the exchange of Rooks. The rest is straightforward. }
37. c3 Be6 38. Kg3 Rd5 39. Re4 Kd7 40. Be5 Rd2 41. Kf4 Rxg2 42. Kg5 Rc2 43.
Kxh5 g3
{ Making sure there won't be any issues on the kingside. Also, Black will win the last remaining queenside pawn. }
44. Bxg3 Rxc3 45. Be5 Rc4 46. Re3 Bd5 47. Ra3 Ke6 48. Bg3 Kf5 49. Kh6 a5 50.
Kg7 Kg4 51. Kf6 a4 52. Re3 Bf3 53. Be1 Rc1 54. Re7 Kh3 55. Bd2 Rc4 56. Re3 Kg2
57. Be1 Rc1 58. Bd2 Rd1 59. Bc3 c5 60. Re7 b5 { Here they come. } 61. Be5 a3
62. Rh7 b4 63. h5 b3 64. h6 b2 65. Rg7+ Kf2 66. Bg3+ Ke3
{ A very one-sided performance by the Danish legend. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bologan, Viktor vs. Sakaev, Konstantin / SRB-chT 1st League Kragujevac (1) / 01.09.2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. dxe5 Nc5 6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8.
Be3 c6 9. c4 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nbd7
{ This is where we ended the trainable line. White has a 4v3 majority on the kingside, but the e5-pawn might turn into a weakness. }
11. Qc2 Qc7
{ The best move, threatening ... Nxe5 and preparing ... Nb6 or ... Ne6. Also, the d8-square is freed for the Rook. }
12. Be2
{ I think that this is the first step in the wrong direction. The Bishop was pretty active and should be kept on the a2-g8 diagonal. Of course, White stops ... Nxe5 due to Bxc5, but still, Black gets a more pleasant game. }
12... Ne6 { White can't really defend the pawn anymore. } 13. Bd3
{ 13.Qe4?!  f5!  and  13.Qc3?!  Nb6  planning ... Nd5 are both excellent for Black. }
13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Bxh7+ Kh8 16. Bd3
{ Bologan managed to maintain material equality, but it should be obvious that eliminating the central pawn should be considered a success for Black. OK, his King's position is weakened, but there is no way to exploit that. }
16... Bd6 17. g3 Nc5 18. Bxc5 Qxc5 19. Nc3 Bg4
{ Black has a slight edge thanks to the Bishop pair. } 20. Rae1 Rae8 21. Qb3
Rxe1 22. Rxe1 Bc8
{ A mistake. Black shouldn't play so passively. Instead of that,  22...f5  planning to meet  23.Qxb7??  with  23...Qd4!  and ... Bc5 next would give Black a winning attack. }
23. Qd1 Bc7 24. Qf3 g6 { The position is around balanced now. } 25. Qf6+ Kg8
26. Bc2 { Bologan plays with fire.  26.Bxg6  should be preferred. } 26... Bd8
{ Sakaev kicks the intruder from his backyard and once again gets a better position. }
27. Qf3 Kg7 28. Bb3 Qf5 29. Qe2 Bb6
{ White hold on, but now, he makes a fatal mistake. } 30. Rd1 Re8
{ A nice way of activating the Rook!  31.Qxe8??  Qxf2+  32.Kh1  Qf3#  is the point. }
31. Bc2 Qf6 32. Be4
{ Black makes the biggest mistake of the game and accepts a draw!  32...Bd4  with ... b5 to come would be crushing. Maybe the fact that it was a team competition was influenced in some way. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
