[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Vachier Lagrave, Maxime vs. Giri, Anish / Meltwater Tour Final chess24.com INT rapid / 03.10.2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. dxe5 d5 5. Nbd2 Qd7 6. Qe2 Nc5
{ We followed this line. Again we have a discussion if the e5-pawn is strong or weak. I am sure that what is weak in the presence of the White Queen on e2. It blocks the development of the kingside and will have to move again. }
7. h4
{ OK, now in 2022 such moves are more common in tournament practice than bad jokes in my courses. }
7... b6 { I like this idea. Giri combines ... Ne6 with ... Ba6. } 8. h5 Ne6 9.
Nb3 Ba6 10. Qd1 Bxf1 11. Kxf1 c5
{ Black already has an advantage. The queenside majority moves up the board which can't be said about White's majority. }
12. c3 Nc6 13. Qe2 Be7 14. h6 g6
{ An even more aggressive treatment with  14...g5  and ... Rg8 followed by ... O-O-O was also possible. }
15. Bd2 O-O
{ I think that this is the first step in the wrong direction. The King looks safer on the queenside, and since it was a rapid game, I would also in general prefer to avoid having the King close to the pawn on h6 which can be treated as an unwanted nail. }
16. Re1 Rae8
{ Anish obviously wants to open up the f-file. Another option was to strive for ... a5-a4. }
17. c4 f6 18. Qd3 d4 19. exf6 Bxf6
{ White awaits a tough defence. A long-term problem is that the pawn endgames are lost. Also, there are issues with the King. All Black has to do is to open up the e-file for his Rook. }
20. Nc1 Ned8 { Very strong! ... Nf7 combined with ... Rxe1+ is coming. } 21.
Bf4 Rxe1+ 22. Kxe1 Nb4 23. Qb3 d3 24. a3 Ne6
{ Even stronger was  24...Qg4  but it is virtually impossible to see  25.Bg3  Bg5  26.axb4  Rxf3  27.gxf3  d2+  in a rapid game. }
25. Be3 Nc2+ 26. Kd2 Ncd4 27. Qxd3 Qc6
{ Black lost a pawn but opened up the d-file for the Rook. White is still in trouble. }
28. Bxd4 cxd4
{ This move throws away a big part of the advantage.  28...Nxd4  29.Nxd4  Qxg2!  was crushing. }
29. Re1
{ Returning the favour.  29.Nb3  , discouraging ... Nc5 should be preferred. }
29... Nc5 30. Qc2 Bg5+ { A very strong idea, probably missed by MVL. } 31. Kd1
{ 31.Nxg5  Rxf2+  32.Ne2  Qxg2  with ... Qxg5 or ... d3 to come is game over. After  32.Re2  Rxe2+  33.Nxe2  Qxg2  , the Knight on g5 is simply trapped and ... d3 is threatened as a bonus! }
31... Rxf3
{ Winning was  31...d3  32.Nxd3  Nxd3  33.Qxd3  Rd8  34.Nd4  and now either  34...Qf6  or  34...Qxg2  . }
32. gxf3 d3 33. Nxd3 Qxf3+ 34. Qe2 Qxd3+ 35. Qxd3 Nxd3 36. Re8+
{ White has enough counterplay to secure a draw. } 36... Kf7 37. Ra8 Nxb2+ 38.
Kc2 Nxc4 39. Rxa7+ Kg8 40. Rg7+ Kh8 41. Rc7 Nxa3+ 42. Kb3 Bxh6 43. Kxa3 Bf4 44.
Rb7 Bd6+ 45. Kb3 Bc5 { Black has enough extra pawns to hold this. } 46. f3 h5
47. Rd7 h4 48. Rd2 Kg7 49. Kc4 Kf6 50. Kd3 Kf5 51. Ke2 g5 52. Kf1 g4 53. fxg4+
Kxg4 54. Kg2 Kf4 55. Kh3 Ke3 56. Rb2 Kd3 57. Rxb6 Bxb6 58. Kxh4 *

