[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Goryachkina, Aleksandra vs. Ju, Wenjun / Wch Rapid (Women) St. Petersburg (10) / 28.12.2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. O-O Nxe5 7. dxe5 Nc5 8.
f4 Nxd3 9. Qxd3 g6 10. Be3 c6
{ We have followed this theoretical variation. White gave up the light-squared Bishop to get a lead in development and hope to get some attacking chances. }
11. Nc3 b6
{ I would still bet my money on ... Bf5 followed by ... h5, but I think it is worth taking a look at Ju Wenjun's plan. She wants to play ... Bg7, castle kingside and then ... Bb7 followed by ... c5. }
12. Ne2 Bg7 13. Ng3
{ The best way to handle the position was  13.Nd4  , planning to meet  13...c5  with  14.Nb5  and Nd6 next. }
13... O-O 14. c3 c5 15. Rad1
{ A wrong square. The Rook should be placed on e1 to play f5 next. Now, Black gets an advantage by simple means. }
15... Bb7 16. Rf2 Qc7 17. Rfd2 a5
{ A typical strategy. The side with a majority should push it up the board. }
18. Bf2 f6 { And now from the other direction. White's position falls apart. }
19. exf6 Rxf6 20. f5 { A necessity, trying to generate some counterplay. }
20... Raf8 21. fxg6 hxg6 22. Re1 Qc6
{ ... d4 is coming cooner or later when White will face lethal threats on the light squares. }
23. Be3 Re6 24. Ree2 d4 { Now, everything is ready for this pawn thrust. } 25.
cxd4 cxd4 26. Rc2
{ 26.Bxd4  Bxd4+  27.Qxd4  Qxg2+!  ends the game on the spot. } 26... Qd5 27.
Bc1 Rfe8 28. Rxe6 Rxe6 29. h3 Rc6
{ Simple. Chinese GM decides that she will exchange the Rooks and combine threats to the White King with attacking the queenside pawns. Without the Rooks on the board, White won't have any counterplay. }
30. Nf1 Rxc2
{ 30...Ba6!  31.Qd1  Bxf1!  is a wonderful pattern. Now, taking the Rook allows a mate in one while  32.Kxf1  Qf5+  33.Rf2  Qb1  ends the game as well. }
31. Qxc2 d3 32. Qf2 Bd4 33. Ne3 Qc6
{ There was nothing to worry about after  33...Qxa2  . } 34. Bd2 Bxb2 35. Qg3
Bd4 36. h4 Kh7 37. Kh1 Qd7 38. Ng4 Bg7 { Black has everything under control. }
39. Qf4 Qf5 40. Qg3 Bc6 41. Ne3 Qe4 42. Qf2 Qe6 43. a3 Qf6 44. Qxf6
{ I think that exchanging Queens equals resignation. } 44... Bxf6 45. Nc4 Bd4
46. Kh2 Bd5 47. Ne3 Be6 48. g4 Bc5 49. a4 Bd7 50. Kg3 Bxa4 51. Kf4 Bc6 52. Nc4
a4 { Here they come. } 53. Be3 a3 54. Bxc5 bxc5
{ White can't catch both pawns. } *

