[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Wang, Hao / FIDE Chess.com Grand Swiss Douglas (10) / 20.10.2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Nc3 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Bb4 8.
O-O Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Rb1 O-O 11. Bxh7+ Kxh7 12. Qd3+ Kg8 13. Qxc3 b6
{ In the theoretical section,  I recommend playing  13...a5  to both stop Rb4 and prepare ... Ra6. Even though I think that Wang Hao's plan is objectively a little bit too slow, I still think that this game has a huge instructive value regarding how to handle these opposite coloured Bishops middlegames. }
14. Qg3
{ With a deadly threat of Bh6. As you can see, Black doesn't have ... Ra6 now. }
14... Qd7 15. Rb4 { White should start with  15.h3  to cover the g4-square. }
15... Qf5 16. Rh4
{ This is the start of the wrong plan. White's attacking chances on the kingside are not too huge, and moves like this might often involve losing too much time. }
16... Re8
{ Not only preparing to take on e5, but more importantly, planning both ... Re6 or ... Qg6. Note how important and typical is the strategy of putting the major pieces on the light squares in this specific pawn structure  @@StartBracket@@and the one with ... a5 instead of ... b6 played as well@@EndBracket@@. }
17. f4
{ White's strategy is based on pushing the f-pawn. This option is temporarily blocked, but give White one move to play Qf3, and the g-pawn will start looking in our direction. }
17... Re6
{ White's attack is stopped, and now Anand is reminded that he has a weak pawn structure on the queenside. It is shocking how quickly White's position might fall apart. }
18. Qf3 Qe4 { Wang Hao makes sure that there will be no attack going on. } 19.
Qxe4 dxe4 20. Rg4 Ba6
{ 20...Rxe5  would lead to a drawish position, but I assume Wang Hao sensed blood and wanted to fight for more. Indeed, Black's position seems easier to play, and the g4-Rook has problems getting back into the game. }
21. Re1 Rd8 22. Rg3 Rc6 23. f5 Rd5 24. e6
{ The first inaccuracy. It was better to go for something like  24.h4  when after  24...Rxe5  25.Bb2  Rxf5  26.Rxe4  White has enough compensation. }
24... Rxf5 25. Ra3
{ But this is playing with fire. Mandatory was  25.Bh6  Rxe6  26.Rxg7+  with decent chances to defend. }
25... Bc4 26. exf7+ Bxf7 27. c3 a5 28. Rxe4
{ This is what Anand banket this position on. } 28... Rcf6
{ After  28...Rcf6  there is no way to prevent ... Rf1.  29.Re1  Bc4!  only prolongs the game. But note that  28...Bc4?  would allow  29.Rf4  and White still can continue. Note how misplaced the White Rook was in this game. It went back and forth to the kingside and queenside. As you can see, White's temporary activity might turn into a double-edged sword. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Guseinov, Gadir vs. Gledura, Benjamin / EU-chT 23rd Terme Catez (4.1) / 15.11.2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Nxd7 Bxd7 7. O-O Bd6 8.
c4 O-O 9. cxd5 f5 10. Nc3 Qf6
{ In this position, we have analyzed three options for White - 11. Nxe4 11. Qc2 and 11. Ne2. However, let's see what happens after a rare idea Guseinov went for. }
11. Qf3 Ng5
{ We have already seen this pattern. The Queen is asked some questions and Black is fully ready to play ... f4 with an attack. }
12. Bxg5 Qxg5 13. Bb5
{ A smart idea, provoking the exchange of Bishops. Black should keep the Bishop though because his compensation for the pawn is based on the Bishop pair. }
13... Bc8
{ Just like that! Maybe it is not visible at the moment, but you will see how effortlessly Gledura will be able to create an attack on the kingside. It is understandable, though. White has virtually no pieces defending the kingside @@StartBracket@@the Queen will be politely asked to go away soon@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Rad1 a6 15. Ba4
{ I would prefer to keep the Bishop closer to the kingside by playing  15.Be2  . }
15... Qh6 16. Qh3
{ The most practical decision, although Black will end up being much better.  16.h3  is Stockfish's first line, but after  16...g5  it seems impossible to hold something like this. }
16... Qxh3 17. gxh3 b5 18. Bb3 Bd7
{ White has an extra pawn, but his pawn structure is ruined and Black has a powerful pair of Bishops. }
19. Rfe1 Rfe8
{ 19...Rf6  planning ... Rg6/Rh6 was possible, but I assume Gledura didn't like some sort of exchange sacrifice after Re5 or Re6. }
20. Kg2 Rxe1 21. Rxe1 Re8 22. Rxe8+ Bxe8
{ Objectively, White's chances to save this position should have increased without the Rook's presence. However, doing it in practice is a different story. }
23. a4 Kf7 24. axb5 axb5
{ Guseinov exchanges one pair of pawns which should increase his defensive chances. The general rule is that whenever you defend an inferior endgame, you should exchange as many pawns as you can. }
25. Bc2 Kf6 26. Bd3
{ I think that this is the first step in the wrong direction. White should play  26.h4  to stop ... Kg5. }
26... b4 27. Nb5 Kg5
{ The problem for White is even though he can eliminate one of the Bishops, his position is difficult. Holdable with precise defence, but difficult. }
28. Nxd6 cxd6 29. h4+
{ This is the final mistake. Allowing the King to f4 is game over. It was necessary to play either  29.Kg3  ,  29.Kf3  to stop the King from coming to f4, or  29.f3  to be able to meet  29...Kf4  with  30.Kf2  . }
29... Kf4 30. f3 Bh5 31. Kf2
{ 31.Be2  Ke3  32.Bd1  f4  is a beautiful example of domination. } 31... Bxf3
32. Bxf5 { This is what Guseinov hoped for. } 32... h6 33. Be6 Bh5
{ Gledura will simply play ... Ke4 next. } 34. Bg8 Ke4 35. Kg3 Kxd4 36. Kf4 g6
{ Black will collect the b-pawn next. White has no counterplay. } 37. Be6 Kc4
38. Ke4 Kb3 { Game over. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Dominguez Perez, Leinier vs. Gelfand, Boris / Bermuda (10) / 09.02.2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Nxd7 Bxd7 7. O-O Bd6 8.
Nc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Qh5 f5 11. Re1 c6 12. Bg5 Qc7 13. c4 Be8 14. Qh4 dxc4
15. Bxc4+ Bf7 16. Bd3 Bg6
{ In the theoretical section,  I have recommended playing  16...Qa5  , not to weaken the pawn structure or the position of the light-squared Bishop. The biggest disadvantage of starting with  16...Bg6  is that after  17.c4  White's position seems to be better. His queenside pawns are not as weak as in the other variations, and can in fact pose some practical problems.   However, after  16...Qa5  ,  17.c4  is not too strong due to  17...Rae8  , and the Queen from  a5  not only protects the f5-pawn, but also creates threats on the back rank. }
17. Re6 { Dominguez decides against c4. } 17... Rae8 18. Rae1
{ White's position looks preferable, but Gelfand has a nice antidote. } 18...
Qa5 { With a lethal threat of ... Qxe1+. } 19. R1e3
{ 19.Bc4  Rxe6  20.Rxe6  Bf7  21.Rxd6  Bxc4  should peter out to a draw. }
19... Rxe6 20. Rxe6 Qd5
{ The cleanest way to equality was  20...Re8  21.Rxd6  Re1+  22.Bf1  Qb5  when White has nothing better than giving a series of checks on the 7th and 8th rank. }
21. Rxd6 Qxd6 22. Be7 Qc7
{ A very strong move.  22...Qd7  seems more natural, but after  23.Bxf8  Kxf8  24.Qf4!  , White still has the initiative/ Gelfand correctly spots that he should focus on controlling the f4-square. }
23. Bxf8 Kxf8 24. Qg5 Qd6
{ Very accurate! It is still necessary to keep control over the f4-square. As a bonus, Gelfand attacks the d4-pawn and defends the Bishop. }
25. h4 { 25.Bxf5?!  Qxd4  is the point. } 25... h6 26. Qe3 f4 27. Qh3 Bxd3 28.
Qc8+
{ 28.Qxd3  Qe6  is fully equal. Both sides have some weak pawns and some sort of a perpetual should be unavoidable. }
28... Ke7 29. Qxb7+ Qd7 30. Qb4+ Qd6
{ Since the pawn endgame is lost for White, Dominguez delivers the perpetual. }
31. Qb7+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Short, Nigel D vs. Kramnik, Vladimir / London Classic 3rd (2) / 04.12.2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7. exf6 Qxf6
8. dxc3 Bc5 9. Qe2+ Qe6
{ This is the position I have mentioned in the comments to this variation. Black should be comfortably equal and it is up to White if he wants to mix things up or agree to a draw. }
10. O-O O-O
{ Kramnik tried to provoke Qxe6 after which he would recapture with the f-pawn and with an imbalanced pawn structure, he gives himself more chances to play for a win. }
11. Qf3 d6 12. Bg5 { Not yet wrong, but it is a start of a wrong plan. } 12...
Qf5 13. Be7 { 13.Qxf5  Bxf5  14.Bd3  would be equal. } 13... Qxf3 14. gxf3 a6
{ Extremely strong! This is what Short must have missed. The problem is that after capturing on f8, the Bishop can't escape after ... f6. Amazing! }
15. Ba4 { 15.Bd3  Re8  16.Bh4  was probably a lesser evil. } 15... b5 16. b4
{ Short tries to complicate but it will backfire. } 16... Re8 17. Rfe1 Bb6 18.
Bb3 Bb7
{ Next is ... d5 and ... c6 when White will basically play a piece down - the guy on b3 won't participate in any way. }
19. Kg2 d5
{ Engines like to include  19...a5  20.a3  a4  21.Ba2  and only now  21...d5  . However, even after the text move, White's position is tough. }
20. Re5 c6 21. Rae1 Bc7 22. R5e2 Bc8
{ The Bishop has done its job and is now relocated to the other side of the board. }
23. a4 Bd7 24. Bh4 Rxe2 25. Rxe2 Re8 26. Rxe8+ Bxe8
{ Without the Rooks on the board, Black virtually has an extra piece. } 27. Bg3
Bd8
{ Of course, taking on g3 would be inaccurate for many reasons. Improving the pawn structure is the main of them. }
28. Be5 f6
{ The next step of converting this position is to activate the King. } 29. Bb8
Bg6 30. axb5 axb5 31. Kf1 Kf7 32. Ke2 Ke6 33. Ke3 Bb6+ 34. Ke2 Bh5
{ Now, Kramnik will push the kingside pawns to create weaknesses. } 35. Ba2 g5
36. Bb3 f5 37. Ba2 f4
{ Myself, I would probably prefer the manoeuvre ... Bd8-f6-e5 when White shouldn't be able to hold on to the weak pawns. However, it doesn't matter. Kramnik's move is equally good. }
38. Bb3 Kf5 39. Bd6 g4
{ The position of the pieces have reached the maximum potential, so it is time for some break. }
40. Kf1
{ The problem with  40.fxg4  is that after  40...Kxg4  , the King enters the game, for example,  41.f3+  Kh3  42.Bxf4  Kg2  . }
40... g3 { Smart, avoiding any blockades. } 41. fxg3 fxg3 42. Bxg3 Bxf3 43. Ba2
Be3
{ Short decided that he had seen enough. He can only move the Bishops or go Ke1-f1-e1-f1. The position would be won by placing the King on h3, playing ... h5-h4, and then forcing the King to defend the weakness on c3 to be able to play ... Bg1. }
*

