1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4 5. Bc4 c6 6. Nxe5 d5 7. exd5 Bd6 8.
Nf3 Qe7+ 9. Kf1 Nxf3 10. Qxf3 O-O 11. dxc6 Re8 12. Qe2 Qd8 13. Qd1 bxc6
{ This is the end of the variation that we have analyzed here. Black has full compensation for the sacrificed pawns. And trust me, such positions handled by Anand are a pleasure to watch! }
14. d3 Rb8
{ White is under tremendous pressure. Basically, every move has a drawback. }
15. h3 Be5 16. Bb3 c5
{ ... Qc7 is next when Black's army will be fully mobilized. } 17. Be3 Qc7 18.
Qd2 Ba6
{ The most active option, threatening to play ... c4 and after dxc4 Rbd8. } 19.
Re1 c4 20. dxc4 Bxc4+
{ 20...Rbd8  is not so attractive with the White Rook on e1 due to  21.Qc1  . }
21. Bxc4 Qxc4+ 22. Qd3 Qxd3+
{ This should be enough for a draw.  22...Qc6  was the way to still play for compensation. }
23. cxd3 Rxb2 24. d4 Bc7 { White has to deal with the threat of ... Ba5. } 25.
Re2 Rbb8 26. g3 Ba5 27. Na4 Nd5
{ With such a blockade and all pieces active, Black doesn't risk much. } 28.
Nc5 Bc3 29. Nb3 a5 { With ... a4 to come. Van Foreest decides to simplify. }
30. Bc1 Rxe2 31. Kxe2 a4 32. Nc5 Bxd4 33. Ne4 Re8 34. Kf3 Nc3
{ This should be enough but  34...Nb4  35.Rd1  Nxa2  36.Rxd4  Nxc1  37.Rxa4  was probably the cleanest. }
35. Nxc3 Bxc3 *

